{"title_page": "Siege of Novo Brdo (1440\u201341)", "text_new": "{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Siege of Novo Brdo\n| partof      = the [[Ottoman wars in Europe]] and [[Serbian-Ottoman Wars]]\n| image       = Novo Brdo Castle 07.JPG\n| caption     = Remnants of the [[Novo Brdo Fortress]]\n| date        = October 1440 &ndash; 27 June 1441\n| place       = [[Novo Brdo]], [[Serbian Despotate]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|42|36|N|21|26|E|display=inline}}\n| map_type    = \n| map_relief  = \n| latitude    = \n| longitude   = \n| map_size    = \n| map_marksize = \n| map_caption = \n| map_label   = \n| territory   = \n| result      = Eventual Ottoman victory <br> Novo Brdo temporarily captured by the Ottomans\n| status      = \n| combatants_header = \n| combatant1  = {{flag|Ottoman Empire}}\n| combatant2  = [[File:Despot_of_Serbia.png|20px]] [[Serbian Despotate]]<br> [[File:St. Blaise - National Flag of the Ragusan Republic.png|20px]] [[Republic of Ragusa]]\n| combatant3  = \n| commander1  = {{flagicon|Ottoman Empire}} [[Murad II]]<br />\n{{flagicon|Ottoman Empire}} [[Had\u0131m \u015eehabeddin]]\n| commander2  = [[File:Despot_of_Serbia.png|20px]] [[\u0110ura\u0111 Brankovi\u0107]]\n<br />\n[[File:Despot_of_Serbia.png|20px]] [[Voivode]] Prijezda\n| commander3  = \n| units1      = \n| units2      = \n| units3      = \n| strength1   = \n| strength2   = \n| strength3   = \n| casualties1 = Unknown \n| casualties2 = heavy casualties of the population of Novo Brdo\n| casualties3 = \n| notes       = \n| campaignbox = {{Serbian-Ottoman Wars (Medieval)}}\n}}\nThe '''Siege of Novo Brdo''' was a [[Siege|military blockade]] of [[Novo Brdo]], an important fortified mining town in the [[Serbian Despotate]], by the forces of the [[Ottoman Empire]]. The siege began in 1440 and lasted until the capture of the fortress on 27 June 1441. During the siege, the Serbian garrison was supported by the local community of citizens of the [[Republic of Ragusa]].\n\n== Background ==\n\nNovo Brdo was one of the largest cities in the Balkans,{{sfn|Setton|1978|p=58}}<ref name=\"Singleton1970\">{{cite book|last=Singleton|first=Frederick Bernard|title=Yugoslavia; the country and its people|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P3RpAAAAMAAJ|year=1970|publisher=Queen Anne Press|page=92|quote=In the fourteenth and fifteenth centuries the settlement of Novo Brdo, near Pristina, was described as \"the largest and finest city in all the Balkans\".}}</ref> and because of its rich gold and silver mines it was the most important non-coastal city in the Balkans in the 14th and 15th centuries.{{sfn|Babinger|1992|p=126}} The Ottomans unsuccessfully besieged it in 1412 and in 1427<ref name=\"Pani\u0107-Surep1965\">{{cite book|last=Pani\u0107-Surep|first=Milorad|title=Yugoslavia: Cultural Monuments of Serbia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wgMIAAAAMAAJ|year=1965|publisher=Turisti\u010dka \u0161tampa|p=149}}{{better source|date=November 2016}}</ref> when they used cannons constructed for the [[Siege of Constantinople (1422)|1422 siege of Constantinople]].<ref name=\"L\u0113v1997\">{{cite book|last=L\u0113v|first=Yaacov|title=War and Society in the Eastern Mediterranean: 7th - 15th Centuries|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6boJulGkWBgC&pg=PA354|year=1997|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-10032-6|page=354}}</ref>\n\nIn 1439 Ottoman forces led by Sultan [[Murad II]] attacked the [[Serbian Despotate]]. Serbian Despot [[\u0110ura\u0111 Brankovi\u0107]] fled to Hungary to seek support for the defense of his realm, organized by his son [[Grgur Brankovi\u0107|Grgur]]. [[Smederevo]] was the capital and the most important city of the Serbian Despotate. During the [[siege of Smederevo]] in 1439, Murad II ordered the marcher-lord [[Ishak-Beg]], who was on his return from Mecca, to join forces with [[Had\u0131m \u015eehabeddin]] and besiege Novo Brdo. On 6 August 1439 the Ottoman forces under Ishak-Beg defeated Serbian forces near Novo Brdo.{{sfn|Jefferson|2012|p=165}} The Ottomans captured Smederevo on 18 August 1439 which reduced the territory of the Serbian Despotate to [[Principality of Zeta|Zeta]] and a region around Novo Brdo. The forces under Murad II joined Ishak-Beg to attack Novo Brdo, but its garrison successfully repelled their attacks. The Ottomans realized that it would be difficult to capture the well-defended Novo Brdo, so Murad II ordered for retreat and a stay in [[Skopje]] during the winter. Before they did so, they robbed caravans of Ragusan merchants,<ref>{{cite book|title=Glasnik Muzeja Kosova i Metohije|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A35MAQAAIAAJ|year=1956|publisher=Muzej|page=263|quote=Posle toga, uvidev\u00e1i da ce im biti tesko da osvoje b\u00f3gate i dobro branjeno Novo Brdo, Turci presre\u00e9u karavane Dubravcana i plja\u00ebkaju ih i zauzimaju vazne prilaze ka Novom Brdu. \u0422\u0435\u043a 1440 godine Turci su ponovo napali Novo Brdo i posle ...}}</ref> while Murad II went to [[Adrianople]].<ref>{{cite book|last=\u0160olaji\u0107|first=Dragutin|title=Ratna pro\u0161lost Beograda|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Sn0aAAAAIAAJ|year=1954|publisher=Beogradske novine|page=47|quote=\u041c\u0443\u0440\u0430\u0442 \u0458\u0435 \u0441\u0430 \u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u043e\u043c \u0432\u043e\u0458\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043a\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0443\u043e \u0443 \u043f\u043e\u043c\u043e\u045b \u0418\u0441\u0430\u043a-\u0431\u0435\u0433\u0443 \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e \u0411\u0440\u0434\u043e. \u041c\u0435\u0452\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043c, \u0458\u0443\u043d\u0430\u0447\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0433 \u0411\u0440\u0434\u0430 \u043e\u0434\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0430 ...}}</ref> The Ottomans allowed Grgur Brankovi\u0107 to govern his father's former estates in southern Serbia, as Ottoman vassal.{{sfn|Fine|1994|p=531}} During spring and summer of 1440 the Ottomans again besieged Belgrade, with cannons cast in Smederevo captured a year before, but without success.<ref name=\"ParryYapp1975\">{{cite book|last1=Parry|first1=Vernon J.|last2=Yapp|first2=Malcolm|authorlink2=Malcolm Yapp|title=War, technology and society in the Middle East|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ip1tAAAAMAAJ|year=1975|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=185}}</ref>\n\n== Siege ==\n[[File:Novo Brdo Fortress Layout.JPG|thumbnail|The layout of the [[Novo Brdo Fortress]]]]\n\nIn 1440, after the [[Siege of Belgrade (1440)|failure at Belgrade]],<ref name=\"SettonHazard1989\">{{Setton-A History of the Crusades | volume = 6 |page=287|quote=Following his unsuccessful attempt on Belgrade in 1440, Murad had taken Novo Brdo with its valuable silver mines in 1441, while Turkish raiding parties plundered as far as Belgrade before being defeated by Hunyadi, who pursued them to ...}}</ref><ref name=VMJNA-1957-223>{{cite book|author=Vojni muzej JNA|location=Belgrade|title=Vesnik|volume=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h_0fAAAAMAAJ|year=1957|page=223|quote=Tek 1440 godine Turci su ponovo napali Novo Brdo i posle jednogodisnje opsade uspeli su da ga zauzmu 21 juna 1441 godine ... Posle toga Novo Brdo su oplja\u00f6kali i popalild.}}</ref> the Ottoman forces commanded by ''[[beylerbey]]'' or [[Rumelia Eyalet|Rumelia]] [[Had\u0131m \u015eehabeddin]],<ref name=\"Angold2006\">{{cite book|last=Angold|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Angold|title=The Cambridge History of Christianity: Volume 5, Eastern Christianity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1xUV-nMxNGsC&pg=PA163|date=17 August 2006|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-81113-2|page=163|quote=\u015eihabeddin Pasha was the commander of the Ottoman armies which conquered Novo Brdo in 1441.}}</ref><ref name=\"Imber1990\">{{cite book|last=Imber|first=Colin|title=The Ottoman empire: 1300&ndash;1481|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lIppAAAAMAAJ|year=1990|publisher=Isis|isbn=978-975-428-015-9|page=119|quote=Serbian annals record, in July, 1441, \u00a7ihabeddin Pasha captured Novo Brdo, the centre of the silver-mining district of southern Serbia. }}</ref> again besieged Novo Brdo.{{sfn|Jefferson|2012|p=165}}\n\nThe garrisoned Serbian forces were also supported by citizens of the [[Republic of Ragusa]],<ref name=\"Sedlar2011\">{{cite book|last=Sedlar|first=Jean W|title=East Central Europe in the Middle Ages, 1000-1500|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ANdbpi1WAIQC&pg=PA384|date=1 March 2011|publisher=University of Washington Press|isbn=978-0-295-80064-6|page=384|quote=In 1441 it participated in the defense of Novo Brdo in Bosnia, the principal source of Serbian silver; and twice it gave asylum to the Serbian Despot George Brankovic when Turkish pressure forced him into exile. In 1444 Dubrovnik's fleet ...}}</ref> Ragusa having instructed their subjects in Novo Brdo to help defend the town. Ragusans, who were predominantly merchants, were practically forced to resist the Ottomans because otherwise their property in Novo Brdo would be confiscated, like it was in the case of Ragusan merchants who happened to be outside of the town when the siege began and refused to return to it.{{sfn|Bo\u017ei\u0107|1952|p=83}}\n\nDespot \u0110ura\u0111 Brankovi\u0107 and his wife traveled from Hungary to Zeta, accompanied with several hundred cavalry and ''vojvoda'' Petar [[Spani family|Spani]].<ref name=\"umetnosti1983\">{{cite book|authorlink=Ivan Bo\u017ei\u0107|title=Glas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Uq0rAQAAIAAJ|year=1983|publisher=SANU|page=72}}</ref> They first went to [[Zagreb]], to \u0110ura\u0111's sister Katarina who was the wife of [[Ulrich II, Count of Celje]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Slavisticheski\u012d sbornik|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HqLjAAAAMAAJ|year=1989|publisher=Matica|page=100|quote=... \u0436\u0435\u043d\u0435 \u0423\u043b\u0440\u0438\u0445\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043b\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433, \u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0442\u043e\u043c \u0443 \u0411\u0430\u0440 (\u0417\u0435\u0442\u0443 \u0458\u0435 j\u043e\u0448 \u0441\u0430\u0447\u0443\u0432\u0430\u043e \u043e\u0434 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0430).}}</ref> Then Brankovi\u0107 arrived at Ragusa (Dubrovnik) at the end of July 1440 and after several days he continued his journey toward his coastal towns of [[Budva]] and [[Bar, Montenegro|Bar]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Povijest Bosne i Hercegovine: od najstarijih vremena do godine 1463..|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JtziAAAAMAAJ|year=1998|publisher=Hrvatsko kulturno dru\u0161tvo Napredak|isbn=978-9958-840-00-5|page=497}}</ref> which became the new capital of the remaining part of his despotate. In the period between 1 July 1440 and his arrival at Bar, the Ottoman forces defeated some military units from Novo Brdo in a battle near Makre\u0161 (a village near modern-day [[Gnjilane]]).<ref name=\"Novakovi\u01071966\">{{cite book|last=Novakovi\u0107|first=Stojan|authorlink=Stojan Novakovi\u0107|title=Iz srpske istorije|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n4UNAQAAIAAJ|year=1966|publisher=Matica srpska|page=184}}</ref><ref name=\"Mijatovi\u01071907\">{{cite book|last=Mijatovi\u0107|first=\u010cedomilj|authorlink=\u010cedomilj Mijatovi\u0107|title=Despot \u0110ura\u0111 Brankovi\u0107|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4aGaDd-o-K4C|year=1907|page=295|quote=\u041d\u0435\u0433\u0434\u0435 \u0438\u0437\u043c\u0435\u0452\u0443 1-\u043e\u0433 \u0458\u0443\u043b\u0430 \u0438 \u0434\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0414\u0435\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0443 \u0411\u0430\u0440 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0431p\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0441\u0435 \u0432\u043e\u0458\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0442\u0443\u043a\u043b\u0430 \u0441 \u0442\u0443\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043a\u043e\u0434 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0440\u0435\u0448\u0430. }}</ref>\n\nIn August 1440 Brankovi\u0107 arrived to Bar where he stayed until the end of the winter 1440\u201341.{{sfn|Fine|1994|p=531}} There he tried to mobilize forces to recapture the territory of the Serbian Despotate he lost to the Ottomans.{{sfn|Fine|1994|p=531}} At the same time, Brankovi\u0107 maintained communication with the garrison in Novo Brdo{{sfn|Bo\u017ei\u0107|1952|p=86}} and his son Grgur, who at the time was an Ottoman governor. That was one of the main reasons why the Ottomans, probably justifiably, accused Grgur for treason and dismissed him from his governorship in April 1441. On 8 May 1441, both Grgur and his brother Stefan were blinded, based on the order of Sultan Murad II.<ref name=\"SKA1929\">{{cite book|author=SKA|title=Godi\u0161njak|volume=38|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Yo0xAAAAMAAJ|year=1929|publisher=SKA|page=286}}</ref><ref name=\"\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u045b1972\">{{cite book|last=\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u045b|first=\u0421\u0442\u043e\u0458\u0430\u043d|title=\u0418\u0437 \u0441\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0435 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0458\u0435|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5YUNAQAAIAAJ|year=1972|publisher=Matica srpska|page=201|quote=.. \u0438 \u043a\u0430\u043a\u043e \u0438\u0445 \u0458\u0435 8. \u043c\u0430\u0458\u0430 \u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435\u043f\u0438\u043e, \u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0442\u043e\u043c \u043a\u0430\u043a\u043e \u0458\u0435 \u0458\u0443\u043d\u0430 \u0442\u0435 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0435 \u0425\u0430\u0434\u043e\u043c-\u043f\u0430\u0448\u0430 \u0443\u0437\u0435\u043e \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e \u0411\u0440\u0434\u043e \u0438 \u0441\u0432\u0435 \u0441\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0435 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0435.}}</ref> Brankovi\u0107 faced another disappointment in Zeta where he found out that the Crnojevi\u0107i rebelled against ''vojvoda'' [[Komnen (vojvoda)|Komnen]], the governor of Zeta.{{sfn|Fine|1994|p=531}}<ref name=\"SKA1929\"/> Brankovi\u0107 left Zeta in April 1441<ref>{{cite book|title=Odjeljenje dru\u0161tvenih nauka|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EKteAAAAIAAJ|year=1975|publisher=Dru\u0161tvo za nauku i umjetnost Crne Gore}}</ref> and resided in Ragusa for a while. This angered the Ottomans who requested, through their envoy Agub, that Ragusa should hand over Brankovi\u0107. Ragusans refused this request and explained in a letter to Ishak-Beg and Had\u0131m \u015eehabeddin that Ragusa has not accepted Brankovi\u0107 because he was an enemy of the sultan but because it was a free city that accepts anybody who seeks shelter in it. They also emphasized that Brankovi\u0107 being in Ragusa is the best guarantee that he would not undertake any action against the Ottomans.{{sfn|Bo\u017ei\u0107|1952|p=88}} Ragusans wanted to send their diplomats to Had\u0131m \u015eehabeddin and requested his written guarantee for their safe conduct. On 13 June 1441 Had\u0131m \u015eehabeddin, who was in [[Vu\u010ditrn]] at the time, issued the requested guarantee to the Ragusans.{{sfn|Bo\u017ei\u0107|1952|p=88}}\n \nDuring the siege of Novo Brdo its population suffered heavy casualties.{{sfn|\u0106irkovi\u0107|2004|p=104}} On 27 June 1441{{Cref2|A}} Novo Brdo surrendered to the Ottoman forces, who then robbed and burned the captured town.<ref name=\"SettonHazard1990\">{{cite book|last1=Setton|first1=Kenneth M.|authorlink1=Kenneth M. Setton|last2=Hazard|first2=Harry W.|last3=Zacour|first3=Norman P.|title=A History of the Crusades: The Impact of the Crusades on Europe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TKaPrQPFIAMC&pg=PA267|date=1 June 1990|publisher=Univ of Wisconsin Press|isbn=978-0-299-10744-4|page=267|quote=The Ottoman conquest of Novo Brdo, a center of silver production, took place on June 27, 1441; see JireSek, Geschichte der Serben, II, 178. }}</ref><ref name=VMJNA-1957-223/>\n\n== Aftermath ==\n\n\u0110ura\u0111 Brankovi\u0107 received the news about the fall of Novo Brdo when he was in Zeta. [[Stephen Vuk\u010di\u0107]], who was an Ottoman vassal at that time, used weak position of the Serbian Despot and tried to capture Zeta. After he successfully penetrated into Zeta highlands, [[Venetian Republic]] captured Zeta's coastal cities and regions based on agreement with despot Brankovi\u0107 that they will protect his possessions from falling under Ottoman control.{{sfn|\u0106irkovi\u0107|2004|p=134}} Brankovi\u0107 realized that he lost all of his territory and power base which supplied him with troops necessary to secure his suzerainty, so he moved to his estates in Hungary. Eventually, Zeta fell under control of the local tribes, with the [[Crnojevi\u0107i]] noble family trying to assert their dominance.{{sfn|Fine|1994|p=531}} The Ottomans made significant efforts to again raise Novo Brdo and gave substantial privileges to people who settled in it and worked in its mines<ref name=\"Hercegovine1954\">{{cite book|last=Hercegovine|first=Istorisko dru\u0161tvo Bosne i|title=Godi\u0161njak|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I-XjAAAAMAAJ|year=1954|page=72}}</ref> while its [[Serbs|Serb]] citizens were awarded with trading privileges.{{sfn|Bo\u017ei\u0107|1952|p=87}} Within next three years the Ottomans re-established the mint in Novo Brdo<ref name=\"Hillenbrand2000\">{{cite book|last=Hillenbrand|first=Carole|authorlink=Carole Hillenbrand|title=Studies in Honour of Clifford Edmund Bosworth, Volume II: The Sultan's Turret: Studies in Persian and Turkish Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mkttAAAAMAAJ|year=2000|publisher=Brill|isbn=978-90-04-11075-5|page=117}}</ref> which began to strike [[ak\u00e7e]] for the first time.<ref>{{cite book|title=Balkan studies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F0BpAAAAMAAJ|year=1988|publisher=\u00c9dition de lA\u0315cad\u00e9mie bulgare des sciences.|page=111|quote=The mint at Novo brdo (in Turkish \"Novar\"), was the first to start striking Ottoman ak\u00e7e \u2014 as early as 1441, when Murad Il's military commander, the eunuch Sibab ed-Din pasa captured the town, which had the greatest silver deposits and the ...}}</ref>\n\nIn 1444, during the Crusader [[Long Campaign]], Novo Brdo was recaptured from the Ottomans and again became a part of the reestablished Serbian Despotate until it finally fell to the Ottoman control on 1 June 1455.{{sfn|Setton|1978|p=58}} Among the survivors of the siege was [[Dimitrije Kantakouzenos]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Serbian poetry from the beginnings to the present|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dz1QAQAAIAAJ|year=1988|page=32|quote=As a child, Dimitrije Kantakuzin experienced the siege of Novo Brdo by the Turks, which lasted for two years after the fall of Smederevo, until 1441. He saw the town fall to the Turks, and the citizens rise up again and resist. And, in 1455, when ...}}</ref> In 1455, the Ottomans forced the besieged to surrender because they used heavy artillery. All men of any distinguished rank or importance were [[decapitated]] under orders of sultan [[Mehmed II]]. An estimated 320 boys were taken to become [[Janissary|janissaries]] (''[[dev\u015firme]]''). Approximately 700 girls and young women were given to Ottoman soldiers and their commanders.<ref>Dusan T. Batakovic, [http://www.kosovo.net/batak5.html ''\"Kosovo and Metohija Under the Turkish Rule\"''] {{in lang|en}}</ref> The siege and its aftermath were described in ''Memoirs of a janissary'', written in 1490\u20141501 by Novo Brdo resident [[Konstantin Mihailovi\u0107]], who was one of the boys taken. In 1455 the last [[voivode]] of Serbian despot in Novo Brdo was Lje\u0161 Spanovi\u0107.{{sfn|SANU|1980|p=57}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Cnote2 Begin|liststyle=upper-alpha}}\n{{Cnote2|A|Some Ottoman chronicles gives 1439 as year of Ottoman capture of Novo Brdo, while scholarly consensus accept the other primary sources and Serbian chronicles which set 1441 as a date of the fall of Novo Brdo.}}\n{{Cnote2 End}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{cite book|last=Babinger|first=Franz|authorlink=Franz Babinger|title=Mehmed the Conqueror and His Time|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PPxC6rO7vvsC&pg=PA126|year=1992|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=0-691-01078-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bo\u017ei\u0107|first=Ivan|title=\u0414\u0443\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0438 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0443 XIV \u0438 XV \u0432\u0435\u043a\u0443|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7n1TAAAAYAAJ|year=1952|publisher=\u041d\u0430\u0443\u0447\u043d\u0430 \u043a\u045a\u0438\u0433\u0430|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=\u0106irkovi\u0107|first=Sima|authorlink=Sima \u0106irkovi\u0107|year=2004|title=The Serbs|location=Malden|publisher=Blackwell Publishing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2Wc-DWRzoeIC}}\n* {{The Late Medieval Balkans}}\n* {{cite book|last=Jefferson|first=John|authorlink=John Jefferson|title=The Holy Wars of King Wladislas and Sultan Murad: The Ottoman-Christian Conflict from 1438-1444|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FpvqWWpUYSoC|year=2012|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-21904-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|author=SANU|title=Glas|volume=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kqorAQAAIAAJ|year=1980}}\n* {{The Papacy and the Levant|volume=2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Siege of Novo Brdo (1440-41)}}\n\n{{Wars and battles involving Serbs}}\n\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1440]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1441]]\n[[Category:Serbian Despotate]]\n[[Category:Sieges involving the Ottoman Empire|Novo Brdo 1440]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Serbia in the Middle Ages|Novo Brdo 1440]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Ottoman\u2013Serbian Wars|Novo Brdo 1440]]\n[[Category:1440 in the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:1441 in the Ottoman Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Siege of Novo Brdo\n| partof      = the [[Ottoman wars in Europe]] and [[Serbian-Ottoman Wars]]\n| image       = Novo Brdo Castle 07.JPG\n| caption     = Remnants of the [[Novo Brdo Fortress]]\n| date        = October 1440 &ndash; 27 June 1441\n| place       = [[Novo Brdo]], [[Serbian Despotate]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|42|36|N|21|26|E|display=inline}}\n| map_type    = \n| map_relief  = \n| latitude    = \n| longitude   = \n| map_size    = \n| map_marksize = \n| map_caption = \n| map_label   = \n| territory   = \n| result      = Eventual Ottoman victory <br> Novo Brdo temporarily captured by the Ottomans\n| status      = \n| combatants_header = \n| combatant1  = {{flag|Ottoman Empire}}\n| combatant2  = [[File:Despot_of_Serbia.png|20px]] [[Serbian Despotate]]<br> [[File:St. Blaise - National Flag of the Ragusan Republic.png|20px]] [[Republic of Ragusa]]\n| combatant3  = \n| commander1  = {{flagicon|Ottoman Empire}} [[Murad II]]<br />\n{{flagicon|Ottoman Empire}} [[Had\u0131m \u015eehabeddin]]\n| commander2  = [[File:Despot_of_Serbia.png|20px]] [[\u0110ura\u0111 Brankovi\u0107]]\n<br />\n[[File:Despot_of_Serbia.png|20px]] [[Voivode]] Prijezda\n| commander3  = \n| units1      = \n| units2      = \n| units3      = \n| strength1   = \n| strength2   = \n| strength3   = \n| casualties1 = Unknown \n| casualties2 = heavy casualties of the population of Novo Brdo\n| casualties3 = \n| notes       = \n| campaignbox = {{Serbian-Ottoman Wars (Medieval)}}\n}}\nThe '''Siege of Novo Brdo''' was a [[Siege|military blockade]] of [[Novo Brdo]], an important fortified mining town in the [[Serbian Despotate]], by the forces of the [[Ottoman Empire]]. The siege began in 1440 and lasted until the capture of the fortress on 27 June 1441. During the siege, the Serbian garrison was supported by the local community of citizens of the [[Republic of Ragusa]].\n\n== Background ==\n\nNovo Brdo was one of the largest cities in the Balkans,{{sfn|Setton|1978|p=58}}<ref name=\"Singleton1970\">{{cite book|last=Singleton|first=Frederick Bernard|title=Yugoslavia; the country and its people|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P3RpAAAAMAAJ|year=1970|publisher=Queen Anne Press|page=92|quote=In the fourteenth and fifteenth centuries the settlement of Novo Brdo, near Pristina, was described as \"the largest and finest city in all the Balkans\".}}</ref> and because of its rich gold and silver mines it was the most important non-coastal city in the Balkans in the 14th and 15th centuries.{{sfn|Babinger|1992|p=126}} The Ottomans unsuccessfully besieged it in 1412 and in 1427<ref name=\"Pani\u0107-Surep1965\">{{cite book|last=Pani\u0107-Surep|first=Milorad|title=Yugoslavia: Cultural Monuments of Serbia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wgMIAAAAMAAJ|year=1965|publisher=Turisti\u010dka \u0161tampa|p=149}}{{better source|date=November 2016}}</ref> when they used cannons constructed for the [[Siege of Constantinople (1422)|1422 siege of Constantinople]].<ref name=\"L\u0113v1997\">{{cite book|last=L\u0113v|first=Yaacov|title=War and Society in the Eastern Mediterranean: 7th - 15th Centuries|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6boJulGkWBgC&pg=PA354|year=1997|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-10032-6|page=354}}</ref>\n\nIn 1439 Ottoman forces led by sultan [[Murad II]] attacked the [[Serbian Despotate]]. Serbian Despot [[\u0110ura\u0111 Brankovi\u0107]] fled to Hungary to seek support for the defense of his realm, organized by his son [[Grgur Brankovi\u0107|Grgur]]. [[Smederevo]] was the capital and the most important city of the Serbian Despotate. During the [[siege of Smederevo]] in 1439, Murad II ordered the marcher-lord [[Ishak-Beg]], who was on his return from Mecca, to join forces with [[Had\u0131m \u015eehabeddin]] and besiege Novo Brdo. On 6 August 1439 the Ottoman forces under Ishak-Beg defeated Serbian forces near Novo Brdo.{{sfn|Jefferson|2012|p=165}} The Ottomans captured Smederevo on 18 August 1439 which reduced the territory of the Serbian Despotate to [[Principality of Zeta|Zeta]] and a region around Novo Brdo. The forces under Murad II joined Ishak-Beg to attack Novo Brdo, but its garrison successfully repelled their attacks. The Ottomans realized that it would be difficult to capture the well-defended Novo Brdo, so Murad II ordered for retreat and a stay in [[Skopje]] during the winter. Before they did so, they robbed caravans of Ragusan merchants,<ref>{{cite book|title=Glasnik Muzeja Kosova i Metohije|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A35MAQAAIAAJ|year=1956|publisher=Muzej|page=263|quote=Posle toga, uvidev\u00e1i da ce im biti tesko da osvoje b\u00f3gate i dobro branjeno Novo Brdo, Turci presre\u00e9u karavane Dubravcana i plja\u00ebkaju ih i zauzimaju vazne prilaze ka Novom Brdu. \u0422\u0435\u043a 1440 godine Turci su ponovo napali Novo Brdo i posle ...}}</ref> while Murad II went to [[Adrianople]].<ref>{{cite book|last=\u0160olaji\u0107|first=Dragutin|title=Ratna pro\u0161lost Beograda|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Sn0aAAAAIAAJ|year=1954|publisher=Beogradske novine|page=47|quote=\u041c\u0443\u0440\u0430\u0442 \u0458\u0435 \u0441\u0430 \u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u043e\u043c \u0432\u043e\u0458\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043a\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0443\u043e \u0443 \u043f\u043e\u043c\u043e\u045b \u0418\u0441\u0430\u043a-\u0431\u0435\u0433\u0443 \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e \u0411\u0440\u0434\u043e. \u041c\u0435\u0452\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043c, \u0458\u0443\u043d\u0430\u0447\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0433 \u0411\u0440\u0434\u0430 \u043e\u0434\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0430 ...}}</ref> The Ottomans allowed Grgur Brankovi\u0107 to govern his father's former estates in southern Serbia, as Ottoman vassal.{{sfn|Fine|1994|p=531}} During spring and summer of 1440 the Ottomans again besieged Belgrade, cannons cast in Smederevo captured a year before, but without success.<ref name=\"ParryYapp1975\">{{cite book|last1=Parry|first1=Vernon J.|last2=Yapp|first2=Malcolm|authorlink2=Malcolm Yapp|title=War, technology and society in the Middle East|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ip1tAAAAMAAJ|year=1975|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=185}}</ref>\n\n== Siege ==\n[[File:Novo Brdo Fortress Layout.JPG|thumbnail|The layout of the [[Novo Brdo Fortress]]]]\n\nIn 1440, after the [[Siege of Belgrade (1440)|failure at Belgrade]],<ref name=\"SettonHazard1989\">{{Setton-A History of the Crusades | volume = 6 |page=287|quote=Following his unsuccessful attempt on Belgrade in 1440, Murad had taken Novo Brdo with its valuable silver mines in 1441, while Turkish raiding parties plundered as far as Belgrade before being defeated by Hunyadi, who pursued them to ...}}</ref><ref name=VMJNA-1957-223>{{cite book|author=Vojni muzej JNA|location=Belgrade|title=Vesnik|volume=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h_0fAAAAMAAJ|year=1957|page=223|quote=Tek 1440 godine Turci su ponovo napali Novo Brdo i posle jednogodisnje opsade uspeli su da ga zauzmu 21 juna 1441 godine ... Posle toga Novo Brdo su oplja\u00f6kali i popalild.}}</ref> the Ottoman forces commanded by ''[[beylerbey]]'' or [[Rumelia Eyalet|Rumelia]] [[Had\u0131m \u015eehabeddin]],<ref name=\"Angold2006\">{{cite book|last=Angold|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Angold|title=The Cambridge History of Christianity: Volume 5, Eastern Christianity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1xUV-nMxNGsC&pg=PA163|date=17 August 2006|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-81113-2|page=163|quote=\u015eihabeddin Pasha was the commander of the Ottoman armies which conquered Novo Brdo in 1441.}}</ref><ref name=\"Imber1990\">{{cite book|last=Imber|first=Colin|title=The Ottoman empire: 1300&ndash;1481|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lIppAAAAMAAJ|year=1990|publisher=Isis|isbn=978-975-428-015-9|page=119|quote=Serbian annals record, in July, 1441, \u00a7ihabeddin Pasha captured Novo Brdo, the centre of the silver-mining district of southern Serbia. }}</ref> again besieged Novo Brdo.{{sfn|Jefferson|2012|p=165}}\n\nThe garrisoned Serbian forces were also supported by citizens of the [[Republic of Ragusa]],<ref name=\"Sedlar2011\">{{cite book|last=Sedlar|first=Jean W|title=East Central Europe in the Middle Ages, 1000-1500|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ANdbpi1WAIQC&pg=PA384|date=1 March 2011|publisher=University of Washington Press|isbn=978-0-295-80064-6|page=384|quote=In 1441 it participated in the defense of Novo Brdo in Bosnia, the principal source of Serbian silver; and twice it gave asylum to the Serbian Despot George Brankovic when Turkish pressure forced him into exile. In 1444 Dubrovnik's fleet ...}}</ref> Ragusa having instructed their subjects in Novo Brdo to help defend the town. Ragusans, who were predominantly merchants, were practically forced to resist the Ottomans because otherwise their property in Novo Brdo would be confiscated, like it was in the case of Ragusan merchants who happened to be outside of the town when the siege began and refused to return to it.{{sfn|Bo\u017ei\u0107|1952|p=83}}\n\nDespot \u0110ura\u0111 Brankovi\u0107 and his wife traveled from Hungary to Zeta, accompanied with several hundred cavalry and ''vojvoda'' Petar [[Spani family|Spani]].<ref name=\"umetnosti1983\">{{cite book|authorlink=Ivan Bo\u017ei\u0107|title=Glas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Uq0rAQAAIAAJ|year=1983|publisher=SANU|page=72}}</ref> They first went to [[Zagreb]], to \u0110ura\u0111's sister Katarina who was the wife of [[Ulrich II, Count of Celje]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Slavisticheski\u012d sbornik|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HqLjAAAAMAAJ|year=1989|publisher=Matica|page=100|quote=... \u0436\u0435\u043d\u0435 \u0423\u043b\u0440\u0438\u0445\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043b\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433, \u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0442\u043e\u043c \u0443 \u0411\u0430\u0440 (\u0417\u0435\u0442\u0443 \u0458\u0435 j\u043e\u0448 \u0441\u0430\u0447\u0443\u0432\u0430\u043e \u043e\u0434 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0430).}}</ref> Then Brankovi\u0107 arrived at Ragusa (Dubrovnik) at the end of July 1440 and after several days he continued his journey toward his coastal towns of [[Budva]] and [[Bar, Montenegro|Bar]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Povijest Bosne i Hercegovine: od najstarijih vremena do godine 1463..|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JtziAAAAMAAJ|year=1998|publisher=Hrvatsko kulturno dru\u0161tvo Napredak|isbn=978-9958-840-00-5|page=497}}</ref> which became the new capital of the remaining part of his despotate. In the period between 1 July 1440 and his arrival at Bar, the Ottoman forces defeated some military units from Novo Brdo in a battle near Makre\u0161 (a village near modern-day [[Gnjilane]]).<ref name=\"Novakovi\u01071966\">{{cite book|last=Novakovi\u0107|first=Stojan|authorlink=Stojan Novakovi\u0107|title=Iz srpske istorije|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n4UNAQAAIAAJ|year=1966|publisher=Matica srpska|page=184}}</ref><ref name=\"Mijatovi\u01071907\">{{cite book|last=Mijatovi\u0107|first=\u010cedomilj|authorlink=\u010cedomilj Mijatovi\u0107|title=Despot \u0110ura\u0111 Brankovi\u0107|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4aGaDd-o-K4C|year=1907|page=295|quote=\u041d\u0435\u0433\u0434\u0435 \u0438\u0437\u043c\u0435\u0452\u0443 1-\u043e\u0433 \u0458\u0443\u043b\u0430 \u0438 \u0434\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0414\u0435\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0443 \u0411\u0430\u0440 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0431p\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0441\u0435 \u0432\u043e\u0458\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0442\u0443\u043a\u043b\u0430 \u0441 \u0442\u0443\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043a\u043e\u0434 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0440\u0435\u0448\u0430. }}</ref>\n\nIn August 1440 Brankovi\u0107 arrived to Bar where he stayed until the end of the winter 1440\u201341.{{sfn|Fine|1994|p=531}} There he tried to mobilize forces to recapture the territory of the Serbian Despotate he lost to the Ottomans.{{sfn|Fine|1994|p=531}} At the same time, Brankovi\u0107 maintained communication with the garrison in Novo Brdo{{sfn|Bo\u017ei\u0107|1952|p=86}} and his son Grgur, who at the time was an Ottoman governor. That was one of the main reasons why the Ottomans, probably justifiably, accused Grgur for treason and dismissed him from his governorship in April 1441. On 8 May 1441, both Grgur and his brother Stefan were blinded, based on the order of Sultan Murad II.<ref name=\"SKA1929\">{{cite book|author=SKA|title=Godi\u0161njak|volume=38|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Yo0xAAAAMAAJ|year=1929|publisher=SKA|page=286}}</ref><ref name=\"\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u045b1972\">{{cite book|last=\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u045b|first=\u0421\u0442\u043e\u0458\u0430\u043d|title=\u0418\u0437 \u0441\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0435 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0458\u0435|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5YUNAQAAIAAJ|year=1972|publisher=Matica srpska|page=201|quote=.. \u0438 \u043a\u0430\u043a\u043e \u0438\u0445 \u0458\u0435 8. \u043c\u0430\u0458\u0430 \u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435\u043f\u0438\u043e, \u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0442\u043e\u043c \u043a\u0430\u043a\u043e \u0458\u0435 \u0458\u0443\u043d\u0430 \u0442\u0435 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0435 \u0425\u0430\u0434\u043e\u043c-\u043f\u0430\u0448\u0430 \u0443\u0437\u0435\u043e \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e \u0411\u0440\u0434\u043e \u0438 \u0441\u0432\u0435 \u0441\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0435 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0435.}}</ref> Brankovi\u0107 faced another disappointment in Zeta where he found out that the Crnojevi\u0107i rebelled against ''vojvoda'' [[Komnen (vojvoda)|Komnen]], the governor of Zeta.{{sfn|Fine|1994|p=531}}<ref name=\"SKA1929\"/> Brankovi\u0107 left Zeta in April 1441<ref>{{cite book|title=Odjeljenje dru\u0161tvenih nauka|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EKteAAAAIAAJ|year=1975|publisher=Dru\u0161tvo za nauku i umjetnost Crne Gore}}</ref> and resided in Ragusa for a while. This angered the Ottomans who requested, through their envoy Agub, that Ragusa should hand over Brankovi\u0107. Ragusans refused this request and explained in a letter to Ishak-Beg and Had\u0131m \u015eehabeddin that Ragusa has not accepted Brankovi\u0107 because he was an enemy of the sultan but because it was a free city that accepts anybody who seeks shelter in it. They also emphasized that Brankovi\u0107 being in Ragusa is the best guarantee that he would not undertake any action against the Ottomans.{{sfn|Bo\u017ei\u0107|1952|p=88}} Ragusans wanted to send their diplomats to Had\u0131m \u015eehabeddin and requested his written guarantee for their safe conduct. On 13 June 1441 Had\u0131m \u015eehabeddin, who was in [[Vu\u010ditrn]] at the time, issued the requested guarantee to the Ragusans.{{sfn|Bo\u017ei\u0107|1952|p=88}}\n \nDuring the siege of Novo Brdo its population suffered heavy casualties.{{sfn|\u0106irkovi\u0107|2004|p=104}} On 27 June 1441{{Cref2|A}} Novo Brdo surrendered to the Ottoman forces, who then robbed and burned the captured town.<ref name=\"SettonHazard1990\">{{cite book|last1=Setton|first1=Kenneth M.|authorlink1=Kenneth M. Setton|last2=Hazard|first2=Harry W.|last3=Zacour|first3=Norman P.|title=A History of the Crusades: The Impact of the Crusades on Europe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TKaPrQPFIAMC&pg=PA267|date=1 June 1990|publisher=Univ of Wisconsin Press|isbn=978-0-299-10744-4|page=267|quote=The Ottoman conquest of Novo Brdo, a center of silver production, took place on June 27, 1441; see JireSek, Geschichte der Serben, II, 178. }}</ref><ref name=VMJNA-1957-223/>\n\n== Aftermath ==\n\n\u0110ura\u0111 Brankovi\u0107 received the news about the fall of Novo Brdo when he was in Zeta. [[Stephen Vuk\u010di\u0107]], who was an Ottoman vassal at that time, used weak position of the Serbian Despot and tried to capture Zeta. After he successfully penetrated into Zeta highlands, [[Venetian Republic]] captured Zeta's coastal cities and regions based on agreement with despot Brankovi\u0107 that they will protect his possessions from falling under Ottoman control.{{sfn|\u0106irkovi\u0107|2004|p=134}} Brankovi\u0107 realized that he lost all of his territory and power base which supplied him with troops necessary to secure his suzerainty, so he moved to his estates in Hungary. Eventually, Zeta fell under control of the local tribes, with the [[Crnojevi\u0107i]] noble family trying to assert their dominance.{{sfn|Fine|1994|p=531}} The Ottomans made significant efforts to again raise Novo Brdo and gave substantial privileges to people who settled in it and worked in its mines<ref name=\"Hercegovine1954\">{{cite book|last=Hercegovine|first=Istorisko dru\u0161tvo Bosne i|title=Godi\u0161njak|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I-XjAAAAMAAJ|year=1954|page=72}}</ref> while its [[Serbs|Serb]] citizens were awarded with trading privileges.{{sfn|Bo\u017ei\u0107|1952|p=87}} Within next three years the Ottomans re-established the mint in Novo Brdo<ref name=\"Hillenbrand2000\">{{cite book|last=Hillenbrand|first=Carole|authorlink=Carole Hillenbrand|title=Studies in Honour of Clifford Edmund Bosworth, Volume II: The Sultan's Turret: Studies in Persian and Turkish Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mkttAAAAMAAJ|year=2000|publisher=Brill|isbn=978-90-04-11075-5|page=117}}</ref> which began to strike [[ak\u00e7e]] for the first time.<ref>{{cite book|title=Balkan studies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F0BpAAAAMAAJ|year=1988|publisher=\u00c9dition de lA\u0315cad\u00e9mie bulgare des sciences.|page=111|quote=The mint at Novo brdo (in Turkish \"Novar\"), was the first to start striking Ottoman ak\u00e7e \u2014 as early as 1441, when Murad Il's military commander, the eunuch Sibab ed-Din pasa captured the town, which had the greatest silver deposits and the ...}}</ref>\n\nIn 1444, during the Crusader [[Long Campaign]], Novo Brdo was recaptured from the Ottomans and again became a part of the reestablished Serbian Despotate until it finally fell to the Ottoman control on 1 June 1455.{{sfn|Setton|1978|p=58}} Among the survivors of the siege was [[Dimitrije Kantakouzenos]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Serbian poetry from the beginnings to the present|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dz1QAQAAIAAJ|year=1988|page=32|quote=As a child, Dimitrije Kantakuzin experienced the siege of Novo Brdo by the Turks, which lasted for two years after the fall of Smederevo, until 1441. He saw the town fall to the Turks, and the citizens rise up again and resist. And, in 1455, when ...}}</ref> In 1455, the Ottomans forced the besieged to surrender because they used heavy artillery. All men of any distinguished rank or importance were [[decapitated]] under orders of sultan [[Mehmed II]]. An estimated 320 boys were taken to become [[Janissary|janissaries]] (''[[dev\u015firme]]''). Approximately 700 girls and young women were given to Ottoman soldiers and their commanders.<ref>Dusan T. Batakovic, [http://www.kosovo.net/batak5.html ''\"Kosovo and Metohija Under the Turkish Rule\"''] {{in lang|en}}</ref> The siege and its aftermath were described in ''Memoirs of a janissary'', written in 1490\u20141501 by Novo Brdo resident [[Konstantin Mihailovi\u0107]], who was one of the boys taken. In 1455 the last [[voivode]] of Serbian despot in Novo Brdo was Lje\u0161 Spanovi\u0107.{{sfn|SANU|1980|p=57}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Cnote2 Begin|liststyle=upper-alpha}}\n{{Cnote2|A|Some Ottoman chronicles gives 1439 as year of Ottoman capture of Novo Brdo, while scholarly consensus accept the other primary sources and Serbian chronicles which set 1441 as a date of the fall of Novo Brdo.}}\n{{Cnote2 End}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{cite book|last=Babinger|first=Franz|authorlink=Franz Babinger|title=Mehmed the Conqueror and His Time|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PPxC6rO7vvsC&pg=PA126|year=1992|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=0-691-01078-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bo\u017ei\u0107|first=Ivan|title=\u0414\u0443\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0438 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0443 XIV \u0438 XV \u0432\u0435\u043a\u0443|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7n1TAAAAYAAJ|year=1952|publisher=\u041d\u0430\u0443\u0447\u043d\u0430 \u043a\u045a\u0438\u0433\u0430|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=\u0106irkovi\u0107|first=Sima|authorlink=Sima \u0106irkovi\u0107|year=2004|title=The Serbs|location=Malden|publisher=Blackwell Publishing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2Wc-DWRzoeIC}}\n* {{The Late Medieval Balkans}}\n* {{cite book|last=Jefferson|first=John|authorlink=John Jefferson|title=The Holy Wars of King Wladislas and Sultan Murad: The Ottoman-Christian Conflict from 1438-1444|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FpvqWWpUYSoC|year=2012|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-21904-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|author=SANU|title=Glas|volume=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kqorAQAAIAAJ|year=1980}}\n* {{The Papacy and the Levant|volume=2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Siege of Novo Brdo (1440-41)}}\n\n{{Wars and battles involving Serbs}}\n\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1440]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1441]]\n[[Category:Serbian Despotate]]\n[[Category:Sieges involving the Ottoman Empire|Novo Brdo 1440]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Serbia in the Middle Ages|Novo Brdo 1440]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Ottoman\u2013Serbian Wars|Novo Brdo 1440]]\n[[Category:1440 in the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:1441 in the Ottoman Empire]]\n", "name_user": "Tpsreport84", "label": "safe", "comment": "Grammar edit(s)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siege_of_Novo_Brdo_(1440%E2%80%9341)"}
{"title_page": "Pellerhaus - Nuremberg", "text_new": "[[File:Photo - Fassade Pellerhaus - um 1897.jpg|thumb|Facade of the original Pellerhaus with the Renaissance facade, coloured photo around 1897]]\nThe '''Pellerhaus''' monument (referred to as \u201c '''Mayersches Pellerhaus''' \u201d in relation to the post-war building ) is an archive and library building on Egidienplatz on [[Nuremberg|Nuremberg's]] old city centre. It extends over the area of \u200b\u200bthe historic Pellerhaus and the historic Imhoff house to the east of it, which was rebuilt after the war in the contemporary design of the late 1950s. \n\nBefore the partial destruction during the air raids on Nuremberg in 1944 and 1945 by bombs, an art and architectural renaissance building stood here. The ground floor and parts of the courtyard have been preserved and were integrated into the new building in 1955/1957. At that time, the funds for the complete reconstruction were lacking.<ref>{{citation|surname1=Swetje Bolduan, Herbert May, Nikolaus Bencker, Harald Pollmann|editor-surname1= Matthias B\u00f6ckel|title=Pellerhaus N\u00fcrnberg|publisher=Edition Hertel|publication-place=N\u00fcrnberg|at=p.&nbsp;82|isbn=978-3-9812921-0-7|date=2009|language=German\n}}</ref> From 2008 to 2018, the courtyard was reconstructed through the initiative of the cultural organisation 'The old town friends of Nuremberg' (Altstadtfreunde N\u00fcrnberg) using donations.<ref>[http://www.altstadtfreunde-nuernberg.de/pellerhof.html Altstadtfreunde N\u00fcrnberg: Wiederaufbau des Pellerhofes]</ref> On 14 July 2018, the opening ceremony was held.<ref>[https://www.altstadtfreunde-nuernberg.de/veranstaltungen/pellerhof-veranstaltungen/einzelansicht/die-pracht-ist-zurueck-1.html Altstadtfreunde: Wiederer\u00f6ffnung des Pellerhofs in N\u00fcrnberg am 14. Juli 2018]</ref><ref>[http://www.nordbayern.de/region/nuernberg/magischer-platz-nurnbergs-pellerhof-erstrahlt-wieder-1.7816379 \"Magischer Platz\": N\u00fcrnbergs Pellerhof erstrahlt wieder], nordbayern.de, 13. Juli 2018</ref> The old town friends intend to [[Reconstruction (architecture)|reconstruct]] the entire Pellerhaus to it's original design.<ref>[http://www.nordbayern.de/region/nuernberg/plane-furs-pellerhaus-altstadtfreunde-mochten-neu-bauen-1.8313177 Pl\u00e4ne f\u00fcrs Pellerhaus: Altstadtfreunde m\u00f6chten neu bauen], nordbayern.de, 16. November 2018</ref> \n\n== Historic Pellerhaus ==\n[[File:N\u00fcrnberg \u2014 2013-09-06 und 07 \u2014Mattes (33).JPG|thumb|The current south facade, \"Mayerhaus\" from 1957 (photographed in 2013).]]\n\n=== Architecture ===\nThe old Pellerhaus found its way into art history as an outstanding example of a town house from around 1600. Martin Peller had the house built from 1602 to 1605.<ref>{{citation|surname1=Swetje Bolduan, Herbert May, Nikolaus Bencker, Harald Pollmann|editor-surname1= Matthias B\u00f6ckel|title=Pellerhaus N\u00fcrnberg|publisher=Edition Hertel|publication-place=N\u00fcrnberg|at=p.&nbsp;16|isbn=978-3-9812921-0-7|date=2009|language=German\n}}</ref> Peller and his family moved into the house in 1625. He died there four years later. The Peller's family lived in the house until 1828. \n\nThe Pellerhaus was composed of a front building, courtyard and a rear building, a style typical of classic Nuremberg. However, the front building facade was an exceptionally complex form for Nuremberg. Instead of a reserved, [[eaves]]-like facade, as was customary in Nuremberg, it was more reminiscent of the trading houses of the [[Northern Germany|North German]] or [[Hanseatic]] area.\n\nTwo stories and three [[Attic|attics]] rose above the base floor of [[Rustication (architecture)|rusticated]] pillow blocks. The seven window axes were flanked by [[Pilaster|pilasters]] that ended above the triangular gable in richly decorated [[Obelisk|obelisks]]. Up to the height of the eaves, the pilasters took over the rustic structure of the basement, above which they were covered with fittings. In the top of the gable, two hermen [[Pilaster|pilasters]] carried a shell with the [[chronogram]] \"CVM Deo\", which referred to the year 1605. The facade was completed with a [[Jupiter (mythology)|Jupiter]] statue. Further accents on the central axis were a choir above the entrance portal, as well as a relief of St. Martin of Tourson the third floor, which alluded to the name of the owner Martin Peller.\n[[File:Karl Emil Otto Fritsch-Denkmaeler Deutscher Renaissance-1891-Nuernberg-Pellerhaus zu Nuernberg Aegidienplatz 1605 Facade.jpg|thumb|North view of the original Pellerhaus from Aegidienplatz, Nuremberg in 1891.]]\nThe courtyard had [[Arcade|arcades]] that rose on octagonal [[Column|pillars]], with two gallery corridors above them. The rear building did not have a gallery on its facade. Instead, it had a striking bay window, which was supposed to take away the tube-like character of the narrow courtyard. The parapets were designed with [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]]-style tracery, with no repetitive [[ornamentation]].\n\nThe interior of the Pellerhaus was also very elaborately decorated. The entrance hall is divided into nine roughly square yokes with Gothic [[Vault (architecture)|ribbed vaults]]. In the so-called \"beautiful room\" the walls were lined with lavishly carved panelling, while the ceiling was decorated with ceiling paintings. The subject of the painting was [[Phaethon]] on the [[Solar deity|sun chariot]] surrounded by ancient figures of gods and allegorical figures. Another state hall also had a magnificent wall covering and a coffered ceiling.<ref>Edgard Heiger: Verlorene Pracht, Geschichten von zerst\u00f6rten Bauten, Hildesheim 2006, S. 18\u201321, hier S. 20\u201321.</ref>\n\nThe Pellerhaus was spared extensive conversions over the years and by the time of its [[Area bombardment|destruction]], was largely in its original state. In 1929, the city of Nuremberg bought the Pellerhaus from private ownership in order to use it as a city archive.<ref>Edgard Heiger: Verlorene Pracht, Geschichten von zerst\u00f6rten Bauten, Hildesheim 2006, S. 18\u201321, hier S. 21.</ref> In 1934, the Pellerhaus was completely restored by order of the city of Nuremberg.\n\n== Destruction and Reconstruction ==\n[[File:PellerhausN\u00fcrnbergL1120833 (2).jpg|thumb|The ruins of the Pellerhaus in 1945]]\nDuring an [[air raid]] on Nuremberg on October 3, 1944, the Pellerhaus was severely damaged by [[Explosive device|explosive devices]] and burned out completely when the [[Royal Air Force]] attacked on January 2, 1945. Large parts of the house collapsed on January 3, 1945. Part of the ground floor with the entrance hall, the stair tower, the cellar and large parts of the arcade courtyard have been preserved.<ref>Hartwig Beseler, Niels Gutschow: Kriegsschicksale deutscher Architektur, Verluste \u2013 Sch\u00e4den \u2013 Wiederaufbau, Eine Dokumentation f\u00fcr das Gebiet der Bundesrepublik Deutschland, Bd. II: S\u00fcd, Wiesbaden 2000, S. 1457\u20131459.</ref><ref>{{citation|surname1=Swetje Bolduan, Herbert May, Nikolaus Bencker, Harald Pollmann|editor-surname1= Matthias B\u00f6ckel|title=Pellerhaus N\u00fcrnberg|publisher=Edition Hertel|publication-place=N\u00fcrnberg|at=p.&nbsp;63|isbn=978-3-9812921-0-7|date=2009|language=German\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1952 the \"Ideas Competition for the Reconstruction of Egidienplatz\" was announced.<ref>{{citation|surname1=Swetje Bolduan, Herbert May, Nikolaus Bencker, Harald Pollmann|editor-surname1= Matthias B\u00f6ckel|title=Pellerhaus N\u00fcrnberg|publisher=Edition Hertel|publication-place=N\u00fcrnberg|at=p.&nbsp;68|date=2009|language=German\n}}</ref> The 1st prize of the competition was won by the Nuremberg architects Fritz and his son Walter Mayer.<ref>{{citation|surname1=Swetje Bolduan, Herbert May, Nikolaus Bencker, Harald Pollmann|editor-surname1= Matthias B\u00f6ckel|title=Pellerhaus N\u00fcrnberg|publisher=Edition Hertel|publication-place=N\u00fcrnberg|at=p.&nbsp;69|isbn=978-3-9812921-0-7|date=2009|language=German\n}}</ref> The design envisaged a complete development on the site  in functional forms typical of the time. The remains of the old Pellerhaus were to be preserved and a contemporary magazine building was built on the partially reconstructed base floor, which was used to store archive materials.\n\nAfter the drafts were drawn up in 1953<ref>{{citation|surname1=Swetje Bolduan, Herbert May, Nikolaus Bencker, Harald Pollmann|editor-surname1= Matthias B\u00f6ckel|title=Pellerhaus N\u00fcrnberg|publisher=Edition Hertel|publication-place=N\u00fcrnberg|at=p.&nbsp;71|date=2009|language=German\n}}</ref> and various changes to the plan<ref>{{citation|surname1=Swetje Bolduan, Herbert May, Nikolaus Bencker, Harald Pollmann|editor-surname1= Matthias B\u00f6ckel|title=Pellerhaus N\u00fcrnberg|publisher=Edition Hertel|publication-place=N\u00fcrnberg|at=pp.&nbsp;75f|date=2009|language=German\n}}</ref> , the foundation stone was laid on April 7, 1956. On December 14, 1957, the building complex was inaugurated.<ref>{{citation|surname1=Swetje Bolduan, Herbert May, Nikolaus Bencker, Harald Pollmann|editor-surname1= Matthias B\u00f6ckel|title=Pellerhaus N\u00fcrnberg|publisher=Edition Hertel|publication-place=N\u00fcrnberg|at=p.&nbsp;78|date=2009|language=German\n}}</ref><ref>Walter Mayer: Zum Neubau der st\u00e4dtischen Bibliotheken in N\u00fcrnberg, in: Mitteilungen aus der Stadtbibliothek N\u00fcrnberg 4, 1955, 3, S. 21\u201324.</ref>\n\nThe reconstruction of the courtyard began in the spring of 1956, which also removed parts of the original Renaissance fabric. In 1960 the reconstruction was completed for the time being with the partial reconstruction of the courtyard arcades on the first floor.<ref>{{citation|surname1=Swetje Bolduan, Herbert May, Nikolaus Bencker, Harald Pollmann|editor-surname1= Matthias B\u00f6ckel|title=Pellerhaus N\u00fcrnberg|publisher=Edition Hertel|publication-place=N\u00fcrnberg|at=p.&nbsp;82|date=2009|language=German\n}}</ref> The building was put under monument protection in 1998.\n\nHeinz Schmei\u00dfner , the Nuremberg city building council and head of the reconstruction of the city in the post-war period, later described it as a mistake that the Renaissance building of the Pellerhaus was not reconstructed. The renowned [[Frankfurt]] [[Architecture criticism|architecture critic]] Dieter Bartetzko stated: \"The people of Nuremberg hated the rebuilt ''(1950's Mayersche)'' Pellerhaus, today they ignore it.\"<ref>[https://www.altstadtfreunde-nuernberg.de/fileadmin/media/documents/presse/Buerger_haben_schon_lange_mit_den_Fuessen_abgestimmt.pdf Karl-Heinz Enderle: \"B\u00fcrger haben schon lange mit den F\u00fc\u00dfen abgestimmt\"], [[Altstadtfreunde N\u00fcrnberg]], PDF, abgerufen am 15. M\u00e4rz 2019</ref>\n\n=== Reconstruction of the courtyard ===\n[[File:Pellerhof.jpg|thumb|The almost finished Pellerhof Courtyard in July 2018.]]\nIn autumn 2005 an initiative was developed by the stonemason Harald Pollmann to rebuild the Pellerhaus courtyard. The 'Old Town Friends of Nuremberg' joined the project and founded the ''Pellerhaus working group''. The monument protection authority was initially opposed to a reconstruction, since in their opinion the existing historical substance would be endangered.\n\nIn May 2006, the city council fundamentally spoke in favour of a reconstruction, contrary to the monument protection office; but excluding financial participation in the reconstruction. The initiative then developed a concept in which everyone can make a donation to cover the cost of a special cuboid of the facade.\n\nIn October 2008, the first stone for the reconstruction of the courtyard facade was laid during a ceremony. In mid-2013, the surrounding walls were completely rebuilt up to the second floor, and the reconstruction of the eastern arcades began.<ref>[http://www.nordbayern.de/region/nuernberg/pellerhof-fortschritt-wird-sichtbar-1.2821406?searched=true ''Pellerhof: Fortschritt wird sichtbar'' (N\u00fcrnberger Zeitung vom 11. April 2013, abgerufen am 3. Oktober 2013)]</ref>\n\nThe 'Old Town Friends of Nuremberg' raised a total of 4.5 million euros by February 2018. The interior courtyard of the Pellerhaus has been open to the public since July 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://museums.nuernberg.de/house-of-games/architecture/|title=Historic architecture|last=|first=|date=April 2020|website=museums.nuernberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:PellerhausN\u00fcrnbergL1120842 (2).jpg|Rear view of the Mayer facade with the arcades in the courtyard before reconstruction\nFile:Nuernberg-pellerhaus-innenhof-nseite-v-sw.jpg|North view of the courtyard, 2004\nFile:Pellerhof3.jpg|Construction status October 2011\nFile:Pellerhof2.jpg|Reconstructed fountain in the Pellerhof\nFile:Pellerhaus Eingangshalle.jpg|Entrance hall of the Pellerhaus\nFile:PellerhausN\u00fcrnbergL1120843.jpg|North facade before the reconstruction of the Pellerhof began\nFile:Pellerhof Nordfassade Februar 2018.jpg|North facade in February 2018\nFile:Pellerhof Nordfassade Juni 2018.jpg|North facade in June 2018\n</gallery>\n\n=== Reconstruction of the main facade ===\nThe building complex from the 1950s is in need of renovation after more than 60 years<ref>Bayerischer Rundfunk, Frankenschau, Bericht \u201eStreit um Pellerhaus - Altstadtfreunde erh\u00f6hen Druck auf die Stadt N\u00fcrnberg\u201c, 12. Februar 2019, 17:30 Uhr; https://www.br.de/mediathek/video/streit-um-pellerhaus-altstadtfreunde-erhoehen-druck-auf-die-stadt-nuernberg-av:5c6311da7b0e6700188c452c</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Positionsbestimmung Pellerhaus \u2013 Eine Zusammenfassung|periodical=bda-bayern.de|publisher=Bund Deutscher Architekten (N\u00fcrnberg-Mittelfranken-Oberfranken)|url=http://nuernberg-mittelfranken-oberfranken.bda-bayern.de/2017/12/positionsbestimmung-pellerhaus-eine-zusammenfassung/|url-status=|format=|access-date=|archive-url=|archive-date=|last=|date=2017-12-05|year=|language=|pages=|quote=}}</ref> and so in November 2018, the old town friends announced that they would take over the reconstruction of the entire Pellerhaus. This south facade, is counted by art historians as among the most important of secular Renaissance facades. This proposal is widely discussed in the city amidst much controversy.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sanierung oder Abriss: Die ungewisse Zukunft des Pellerhauses|periodical=BR.de|publisher=Bayerischer Rundfunk|url=https://www.br.de/nachrichten/mittelfranken/inhalt/pellerhaus-nuernberg-renaissance-100.html|url-status=1|format=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180405214627/https://www.br.de/nachrichten/mittelfranken/inhalt/pellerhaus-nuernberg-renaissance-100.html|archive-date=2018-04-05|last=Laura Grun|date=2017-06-23|year=|language=|pages=|quote=}}</ref>\n\n== Historical Photographs ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Reallexicon der Deutschen Altert\u00fcmer Fig 132 Pellers Haus in N\u00fcrnberg.jpg|South facade (illustration in the real lexicon of the German antiquities 1885)\nFile:N\u00fcrnberg Pellerhaus 001.jpg|South facade and neighboring buildings on Aegidienplatz (on the left the Black Peller House), photo (1860\u20131890)\nFile:PellerhausL1120830 (2).jpg|Coloured picture, late 19th century\nFile:Die Baudenkm\u00e4ler der Stadt N\u00fcrnberg 021 Pellerhaus.jpg|View from Aegidienplatz (1891)\nFile:Reallexicon der Deutschen Altert\u00fcmer Fig 130 Pellers Haus in N\u00fcrnberg.jpg|Courtyard, illustration (1885)\nFile:Karl Emil Otto Fritsch-Denkmaeler Deutscher Renaissance-1891-Nuernberg-Pellerhaus zu Nuernberg Aegidienplatz 1605 Hof-Ansicht.jpg|Courtyard, photo (1891)\nFile:Nuernberg Ansichtskarte 054.jpg|Courtyard, colored view (1904)\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n<references responsive=\"\" />\n\n== Literature ==\nIn alphabetical order:\n\n* Swetje Bolduan, Herbert May, Nikolaus Bencker, Harald Pollmann: ''\"Pellerhaus N\u00fcrnberg\",'' N\u00fcrnberg, 2009, Hrsg.: Matthias B\u00f6ckel, Verlag Edition Hertel, ISBN 978-3-9812921-0-7\n* Dieter B\u00fcchner: Das \"Sch\u00f6ne Zimmer\" aus dem Pellerhaus, N\u00fcrnberger Werkst\u00fccke zur Stadt- und Landesgeschichte, Band 55, Schriftenreihe des Stadtarchivs N\u00fcrnberg, N\u00fcrnberg 1965.\n* [[Erich Mulzer]]: ''N\u00fcrnberger B\u00fcrgerh\u00e4user''. N\u00fcrnberg: Spindler, 1954, 68 S. (2. Auflage, 1964)\n* Erich Mulzer: ''Das Egidienviertel und die \u00f6stliche Altstadt''. In: Erich Mulzer: ''Baedeker N\u00fcrnberg \u2013 Stadtf\u00fchrer'', 9. Auflage. Von Karl Baedeker. Ostfildern-Kemnat: Baedeker, 2000, 134 S., ISBN 3-87954-024-1\n* Reinhold Schaffer: ''Das Pellerhaus in N\u00fcrnberg''. N\u00fcrnberg; Berlin: Ulrich, 1934.\n* Gerhard Seibold: Die Viatis und Peller, Beitr\u00e4ge zur Geschichte ihrer Handelsgesellschaft, K\u00f6ln u. Wien 1977.\n* Ursula Tannert: ''Im November vor 55 Jahren war der Wiederaufbau des Pellerhauses schon einmal Thema. Aus Renaissancebau sollte Kulturzentrum werden''. In: N\u00fcrnberger Zeitung Nr. 276 vom 29. November 2007, N\u00fcrnberg plus, S. + 4 \u2013 [http://www.nz-online.de/artikel.asp?art=735417&kat=317 online]\n* Ute Wolf: ''Altstadtfreunde zum Pellerhof: \u201eSpeerspitze f\u00fcr den Wiederaufbau\u201c'', in: N\u00fcrnberger Zeitung Nr. 23, vom 28./29. Januar 2006, S. 9.\n* Ute Wolf: ''Wiederaufbau des Pellerhofes: Eindeutiger B\u00fcrgerwille'', NZ-Kommentar, in: N\u00fcrnberger Zeitung Nr. 23, vom 28./29. Januar 2006, S. 9.\n* Josef Zimmermann: ''Martin Peller von Radolfzell und das Pellerhaus in N\u00fcrnberg'', in: ''Schriften des Vereins f\u00fcr Geschichte des Bodensees und seiner Umgebung'', 78. Jg. 1960, S. 110\u2013113. ([http://www.bodenseebibliotheken.eu/page?vgeb-j1960-t-A110 Digitalisat])\n\n== Weblinks ==\n{{Commonscat}}\n\n* [http://www.baukunst-nuernberg.de/epoche.php?epoche=Renaissance&objekt=Pellerhaus Pellerhaus (Baukunst N\u00fcrnberg)]\n* [http://www.altstadtfreunde-nuernberg.de/pellerhof.html Informationen der Altstadtfreunde zur Rekonstruktion des Pellerhofs]\n* [https://www.artstation.com/artwork/KxQoW 3D-Visualisierung des Pellerhauses am heutigen Egidienplatz] \u2013 Johannes Tscharn, 3D-K\u00fcnstler (ArchViz, ArtStation), abgerufen am 15. M\u00e4rz 2019\n* [http://www.museen.nuernberg.de/fembohaus/dauerausstellung/besondere-historische-raeume/ \u201eDas Sch\u00f6ne Zimmer\u201c aus dem Pellerhaus]\n* [https://gs-schenk.de/naturstein/projekte/pellerhof-egidienplatz/ Das Bauunternehmen GS SCHENK aus F\u00fcrth dokumentiert den Wiederaufbau des Pellerhauses]\n* [http://www.marktspiegel.de/nuernberg/lokales/wieder-gefundene-pellerhof-schaetze-kehren-nach-nuernberg-zurueck-d27584.html/action/recommend/1/ Wiedergefundene Pellerhof-Fassadenpl\u00e4ne kehren nach N\u00fcrnberg zur\u00fcck], Marktspiegel, 29. November 2017\n\n[[Category:Nuremberg]]\n[[Category:Germany]]\n[[Category:Architecture]]\n[[Category:Bavaria]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pellerhaus - Nuremberg}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Photo - Fassade Pellerhaus - um 1897.jpg|thumb|Facade of the original Pellerhaus with the Renaissance facade, coloured photo around 1897]]\nThe '''Pellerhaus''' monument (referred to as \u201c '''Mayersches Pellerhaus''' \u201d in relation to the post-war building ) is an archive and library building on Egidienplatz on [[Nuremberg|Nuremberg's]] old city centre. It extends over the area of \u200b\u200bthe historic Pellerhaus and the historic Imhoff house to the east of it, which was rebuilt after the war in the contemporary design of the late 1950s. \n\nBefore the partial destruction during the air raids on Nuremberg in 1944 and 1945 by bombs, an art and architectural renaissance building stood here. The ground floor and parts of the courtyard have been preserved and were integrated into the new building in 1955/1957. At that time, the funds for the complete reconstruction were lacking.<ref>{{citation|surname1=Swetje Bolduan, Herbert May, Nikolaus Bencker, Harald Pollmann|editor-surname1= Matthias B\u00f6ckel|title=Pellerhaus N\u00fcrnberg|publisher=Edition Hertel|publication-place=N\u00fcrnberg|at=p.&nbsp;82|isbn=978-3-9812921-0-7|date=2009|language=German\n}}</ref> From 2008 to 2018, the courtyard was reconstructed through the initiative of the cultural organisation 'The old town friends of Nuremberg' (Altstadtfreunde N\u00fcrnberg) using donations.<ref>[http://www.altstadtfreunde-nuernberg.de/pellerhof.html Altstadtfreunde N\u00fcrnberg: Wiederaufbau des Pellerhofes]</ref> On 14 July 2018, the opening ceremony was held.<ref>[https://www.altstadtfreunde-nuernberg.de/veranstaltungen/pellerhof-veranstaltungen/einzelansicht/die-pracht-ist-zurueck-1.html Altstadtfreunde: Wiederer\u00f6ffnung des Pellerhofs in N\u00fcrnberg am 14. Juli 2018]</ref><ref>[http://www.nordbayern.de/region/nuernberg/magischer-platz-nurnbergs-pellerhof-erstrahlt-wieder-1.7816379 \"Magischer Platz\": N\u00fcrnbergs Pellerhof erstrahlt wieder], nordbayern.de, 13. Juli 2018</ref> The old town friends intend to [[Reconstruction (architecture)|reconstruct]] the entire Pellerhaus to it's original design.<ref>[http://www.nordbayern.de/region/nuernberg/plane-furs-pellerhaus-altstadtfreunde-mochten-neu-bauen-1.8313177 Pl\u00e4ne f\u00fcrs Pellerhaus: Altstadtfreunde m\u00f6chten neu bauen], nordbayern.de, 16. November 2018</ref> \n\n== Historic Pellerhaus ==\n[[File:N\u00fcrnberg \u2014 2013-09-06 und 07 \u2014Mattes (33).JPG|thumb|The current south facade, \"Mayerhaus\" from 1957 (photographed in 2013).]]\n\n=== Architecture ===\nThe old Pellerhaus found its way into art history as an outstanding example of a town house from around 1600. Martin Peller had the house built from 1602 to 1605.<ref>{{citation|surname1=Swetje Bolduan, Herbert May, Nikolaus Bencker, Harald Pollmann|editor-surname1= Matthias B\u00f6ckel|title=Pellerhaus N\u00fcrnberg|publisher=Edition Hertel|publication-place=N\u00fcrnberg|at=p.&nbsp;16|isbn=978-3-9812921-0-7|date=2009|language=German\n}}</ref> Peller and his family moved into the house in 1625. He died there four years later. The Peller's family lived in the house until 1828. \n\nThe Pellerhaus was composed of a front building, courtyard and a rear building, a style typical of classic Nuremberg. However, the front building facade was an exceptionally complex form for Nuremberg. Instead of a reserved, [[eaves]]-like facade, as was customary in Nuremberg, it was more reminiscent of the trading houses of the [[Northern Germany|North German]] or [[Hanseatic]] area.\n\nTwo stories and three attics rose above the base floor of rusticated pillow blocks. The seven window axes were flanked by pilasters that ended above the gable triangle in richly decorated obelisks. Up to the height of the eaves, the pilasters took over the rustic structure of the basement, above which they were covered with fittings. In the top of the gable, two hermen [[Pilaster|pilasters]] carried a shell with the [[chronogram]] \"CVM Deo\", which referred to the year 1605. The facade was completed with a [[Jupiter (mythology)|Jupiter]] statue. Further accents on the central axis were a choir above the entrance portal, as well as a relief of St. Martin of Tourson the third floor, which alluded to the name of the owner Martin Peller.\n[[File:Karl Emil Otto Fritsch-Denkmaeler Deutscher Renaissance-1891-Nuernberg-Pellerhaus zu Nuernberg Aegidienplatz 1605 Facade.jpg|thumb|North view of the original Pellerhaus from Aegidienplatz, Nuremberg in 1891.]]\nThe courtyard had [[Arcade|arcades]] that rose on octagonal [[Column|pillars]], with two gallery corridors above them. The rear building did not have a gallery on its facade. Instead, it had a striking bay window, which was supposed to take away the tube-like character of the narrow courtyard. The parapets were designed with [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]]-style tracery, with no repetitive [[ornamentation]].\n\nThe interior of the Pellerhaus was also very elaborately decorated. The entrance hall is divided into nine roughly square yokes with Gothic [[Vault (architecture)|ribbed vaults]]. In the so-called \"beautiful room\" the walls were lined with lavishly carved panelling, while the ceiling was decorated with ceiling paintings. The subject of the painting was [[Phaethon]] on the [[Solar deity|sun chariot]] surrounded by ancient figures of gods and allegorical figures. Another state hall also had a magnificent wall covering and a coffered ceiling.<ref>Edgard Heiger: Verlorene Pracht, Geschichten von zerst\u00f6rten Bauten, Hildesheim 2006, S. 18\u201321, hier S. 20\u201321.</ref>\n\nThe Pellerhaus was spared extensive conversions over the years and by the time of its destruction, was largely in its original state. In 1929, the city of Nuremberg bought the Pellerhaus from private ownership in order to use it as a city archive.<ref>Edgard Heiger: Verlorene Pracht, Geschichten von zerst\u00f6rten Bauten, Hildesheim 2006, S. 18\u201321, hier S. 21.</ref> In 1934, the Pellerhaus was completely restored by order of the city of Nuremberg.\n\n== Destruction and Reconstruction ==\n[[File:PellerhausN\u00fcrnbergL1120833 (2).jpg|thumb|The ruins of the Pellerhaus in 1945]]\nDuring an [[air raid]] on Nuremberg on October 3, 1944, the Pellerhaus was severely damaged by explosive devices and burned out completely when the [[Royal Air Force]] attacked on January 2, 1945. Large parts of the house collapsed on January 3, 1945. Part of the ground floor with the entrance hall, the stair tower, the cellar and large parts of the arcade courtyard have been preserved.<ref>Hartwig Beseler, Niels Gutschow: Kriegsschicksale deutscher Architektur, Verluste \u2013 Sch\u00e4den \u2013 Wiederaufbau, Eine Dokumentation f\u00fcr das Gebiet der Bundesrepublik Deutschland, Bd. II: S\u00fcd, Wiesbaden 2000, S. 1457\u20131459.</ref><ref>{{citation|surname1=Swetje Bolduan, Herbert May, Nikolaus Bencker, Harald Pollmann|editor-surname1= Matthias B\u00f6ckel|title=Pellerhaus N\u00fcrnberg|publisher=Edition Hertel|publication-place=N\u00fcrnberg|at=p.&nbsp;63|isbn=978-3-9812921-0-7|date=2009|language=German\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1952 the \"Ideas Competition for the Reconstruction of Egidienplatz\" was announced.<ref>{{citation|surname1=Swetje Bolduan, Herbert May, Nikolaus Bencker, Harald Pollmann|editor-surname1= Matthias B\u00f6ckel|title=Pellerhaus N\u00fcrnberg|publisher=Edition Hertel|publication-place=N\u00fcrnberg|at=p.&nbsp;68|date=2009|language=German\n}}</ref> The 1st prize of the competition was won by the Nuremberg architects Fritz and his son Walter Mayer.<ref>{{citation|surname1=Swetje Bolduan, Herbert May, Nikolaus Bencker, Harald Pollmann|editor-surname1= Matthias B\u00f6ckel|title=Pellerhaus N\u00fcrnberg|publisher=Edition Hertel|publication-place=N\u00fcrnberg|at=p.&nbsp;69|isbn=978-3-9812921-0-7|date=2009|language=German\n}}</ref> The design envisaged a complete development on the site  in functional forms typical of the time. The remains of the old Pellerhaus were to be preserved and a contemporary magazine building was built on the partially reconstructed base floor, which was used to store archive materials.\n\nAfter the drafts were drawn up in 1953<ref>{{citation|surname1=Swetje Bolduan, Herbert May, Nikolaus Bencker, Harald Pollmann|editor-surname1= Matthias B\u00f6ckel|title=Pellerhaus N\u00fcrnberg|publisher=Edition Hertel|publication-place=N\u00fcrnberg|at=p.&nbsp;71|date=2009|language=German\n}}</ref> and various changes to the plan<ref>{{citation|surname1=Swetje Bolduan, Herbert May, Nikolaus Bencker, Harald Pollmann|editor-surname1= Matthias B\u00f6ckel|title=Pellerhaus N\u00fcrnberg|publisher=Edition Hertel|publication-place=N\u00fcrnberg|at=pp.&nbsp;75f|date=2009|language=German\n}}</ref> , the foundation stone was laid on April 7, 1956. On December 14, 1957, the building complex was inaugurated.<ref>{{citation|surname1=Swetje Bolduan, Herbert May, Nikolaus Bencker, Harald Pollmann|editor-surname1= Matthias B\u00f6ckel|title=Pellerhaus N\u00fcrnberg|publisher=Edition Hertel|publication-place=N\u00fcrnberg|at=p.&nbsp;78|date=2009|language=German\n}}</ref><ref>Walter Mayer: Zum Neubau der st\u00e4dtischen Bibliotheken in N\u00fcrnberg, in: Mitteilungen aus der Stadtbibliothek N\u00fcrnberg 4, 1955, 3, S. 21\u201324.</ref>\n\nThe reconstruction of the courtyard began in the spring of 1956, which also removed parts of the original Renaissance fabric. In 1960 the reconstruction was completed for the time being with the partial reconstruction of the courtyard arcades on the first floor.<ref>{{citation|surname1=Swetje Bolduan, Herbert May, Nikolaus Bencker, Harald Pollmann|editor-surname1= Matthias B\u00f6ckel|title=Pellerhaus N\u00fcrnberg|publisher=Edition Hertel|publication-place=N\u00fcrnberg|at=p.&nbsp;82|date=2009|language=German\n}}</ref> The building was put under monument protection in 1998.\n\nHeinz Schmei\u00dfner , the Nuremberg city building council and head of the reconstruction of the city in the post-war period, later described it as a mistake that the Renaissance building of the Pellerhaus was not reconstructed. The renowned [[Frankfurt]] [[Architecture criticism|architecture critic]] Dieter Bartetzko stated: \"The people of Nuremberg hated the rebuilt ''(1950's Mayersche)'' Pellerhaus, today they ignore it.\"<ref>[https://www.altstadtfreunde-nuernberg.de/fileadmin/media/documents/presse/Buerger_haben_schon_lange_mit_den_Fuessen_abgestimmt.pdf Karl-Heinz Enderle: \"B\u00fcrger haben schon lange mit den F\u00fc\u00dfen abgestimmt\"], [[Altstadtfreunde N\u00fcrnberg]], PDF, abgerufen am 15. M\u00e4rz 2019</ref>\n\n=== Reconstruction of the courtyard ===\n[[File:Pellerhof.jpg|thumb|The almost finished Pellerhof Courtyard in July 2018.]]\nIn autumn 2005 an initiative was developed by the stonemason Harald Pollmann to rebuild the Pellerhaus courtyard. The 'Old Town Friends of Nuremberg' joined the project and founded the ''Pellerhaus working group''. The monument protection authority was initially opposed to a reconstruction, since in their opinion the existing historical substance would be endangered.\n\nIn May 2006, the city council fundamentally spoke in favour of a reconstruction, contrary to the monument protection office; but excluding financial participation in the reconstruction. The initiative then developed a concept in which everyone can make a donation to cover the cost of a special cuboid of the facade.\n\nIn October 2008, the first stone for the reconstruction of the courtyard facade was laid during a ceremony. In mid-2013, the surrounding walls were completely rebuilt up to the second floor, and the reconstruction of the eastern arcades began.<ref>[http://www.nordbayern.de/region/nuernberg/pellerhof-fortschritt-wird-sichtbar-1.2821406?searched=true ''Pellerhof: Fortschritt wird sichtbar'' (N\u00fcrnberger Zeitung vom 11. April 2013, abgerufen am 3. Oktober 2013)]</ref>\n\nThe 'Old Town Friends of Nuremberg' raised a total of 4.5 million euros by February 2018. The interior courtyard of the Pellerhaus has been open to the public since July 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://museums.nuernberg.de/house-of-games/architecture/|title=Historic architecture|last=|first=|date=April 2020|website=museums.nuernberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:PellerhausN\u00fcrnbergL1120842 (2).jpg|Rear view of the Mayer facade with the arcades in the courtyard before reconstruction\nFile:Nuernberg-pellerhaus-innenhof-nseite-v-sw.jpg|North view of the courtyard, 2004\nFile:Pellerhof3.jpg|Construction status October 2011\nFile:Pellerhof2.jpg|Reconstructed fountain in the Pellerhof\nFile:Pellerhaus Eingangshalle.jpg|Entrance hall of the Pellerhaus\nFile:PellerhausN\u00fcrnbergL1120843.jpg|North facade before the reconstruction of the Pellerhof began\nFile:Pellerhof Nordfassade Februar 2018.jpg|North facade in February 2018\nFile:Pellerhof Nordfassade Juni 2018.jpg|North facade in June 2018\n</gallery>\n\n=== Reconstruction of the main facade ===\nThe building complex from the 1950s is in need of renovation after more than 60 years<ref>Bayerischer Rundfunk, Frankenschau, Bericht \u201eStreit um Pellerhaus - Altstadtfreunde erh\u00f6hen Druck auf die Stadt N\u00fcrnberg\u201c, 12. Februar 2019, 17:30 Uhr; https://www.br.de/mediathek/video/streit-um-pellerhaus-altstadtfreunde-erhoehen-druck-auf-die-stadt-nuernberg-av:5c6311da7b0e6700188c452c</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Positionsbestimmung Pellerhaus \u2013 Eine Zusammenfassung|periodical=bda-bayern.de|publisher=Bund Deutscher Architekten (N\u00fcrnberg-Mittelfranken-Oberfranken)|url=http://nuernberg-mittelfranken-oberfranken.bda-bayern.de/2017/12/positionsbestimmung-pellerhaus-eine-zusammenfassung/|url-status=|format=|access-date=|archive-url=|archive-date=|last=|date=2017-12-05|year=|language=|pages=|quote=}}</ref> and so in November 2018, the old town friends announced that they would take over the reconstruction of the entire Pellerhaus. This south facade, is counted by art historians as among the most important of secular Renaissance facades. This proposal is widely discussed in the city amidst much controversy.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sanierung oder Abriss: Die ungewisse Zukunft des Pellerhauses|periodical=BR.de|publisher=Bayerischer Rundfunk|url=https://www.br.de/nachrichten/mittelfranken/inhalt/pellerhaus-nuernberg-renaissance-100.html|url-status=1|format=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180405214627/https://www.br.de/nachrichten/mittelfranken/inhalt/pellerhaus-nuernberg-renaissance-100.html|archive-date=2018-04-05|last=Laura Grun|date=2017-06-23|year=|language=|pages=|quote=}}</ref>\n\n== Historical Photographs ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Reallexicon der Deutschen Altert\u00fcmer Fig 132 Pellers Haus in N\u00fcrnberg.jpg|South facade (illustration in the real lexicon of the German antiquities 1885)\nFile:N\u00fcrnberg Pellerhaus 001.jpg|South facade and neighboring buildings on Aegidienplatz (on the left the Black Peller House), photo (1860\u20131890)\nFile:PellerhausL1120830 (2).jpg|Coloured picture, late 19th century\nFile:Die Baudenkm\u00e4ler der Stadt N\u00fcrnberg 021 Pellerhaus.jpg|View from Aegidienplatz (1891)\nFile:Reallexicon der Deutschen Altert\u00fcmer Fig 130 Pellers Haus in N\u00fcrnberg.jpg|Courtyard, illustration (1885)\nFile:Karl Emil Otto Fritsch-Denkmaeler Deutscher Renaissance-1891-Nuernberg-Pellerhaus zu Nuernberg Aegidienplatz 1605 Hof-Ansicht.jpg|Courtyard, photo (1891)\nFile:Nuernberg Ansichtskarte 054.jpg|Courtyard, colored view (1904)\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n<references responsive=\"\" />\n\n== Literature ==\nIn alphabetical order:\n\n* Swetje Bolduan, Herbert May, Nikolaus Bencker, Harald Pollmann: ''\"Pellerhaus N\u00fcrnberg\",'' N\u00fcrnberg, 2009, Hrsg.: Matthias B\u00f6ckel, Verlag Edition Hertel, ISBN 978-3-9812921-0-7\n* Dieter B\u00fcchner: Das \"Sch\u00f6ne Zimmer\" aus dem Pellerhaus, N\u00fcrnberger Werkst\u00fccke zur Stadt- und Landesgeschichte, Band 55, Schriftenreihe des Stadtarchivs N\u00fcrnberg, N\u00fcrnberg 1965.\n* [[Erich Mulzer]]: ''N\u00fcrnberger B\u00fcrgerh\u00e4user''. N\u00fcrnberg: Spindler, 1954, 68 S. (2. Auflage, 1964)\n* Erich Mulzer: ''Das Egidienviertel und die \u00f6stliche Altstadt''. In: Erich Mulzer: ''Baedeker N\u00fcrnberg \u2013 Stadtf\u00fchrer'', 9. Auflage. Von Karl Baedeker. Ostfildern-Kemnat: Baedeker, 2000, 134 S., ISBN 3-87954-024-1\n* Reinhold Schaffer: ''Das Pellerhaus in N\u00fcrnberg''. N\u00fcrnberg; Berlin: Ulrich, 1934.\n* Gerhard Seibold: Die Viatis und Peller, Beitr\u00e4ge zur Geschichte ihrer Handelsgesellschaft, K\u00f6ln u. Wien 1977.\n* Ursula Tannert: ''Im November vor 55 Jahren war der Wiederaufbau des Pellerhauses schon einmal Thema. Aus Renaissancebau sollte Kulturzentrum werden''. In: N\u00fcrnberger Zeitung Nr. 276 vom 29. November 2007, N\u00fcrnberg plus, S. + 4 \u2013 [http://www.nz-online.de/artikel.asp?art=735417&kat=317 online]\n* Ute Wolf: ''Altstadtfreunde zum Pellerhof: \u201eSpeerspitze f\u00fcr den Wiederaufbau\u201c'', in: N\u00fcrnberger Zeitung Nr. 23, vom 28./29. Januar 2006, S. 9.\n* Ute Wolf: ''Wiederaufbau des Pellerhofes: Eindeutiger B\u00fcrgerwille'', NZ-Kommentar, in: N\u00fcrnberger Zeitung Nr. 23, vom 28./29. Januar 2006, S. 9.\n* Josef Zimmermann: ''Martin Peller von Radolfzell und das Pellerhaus in N\u00fcrnberg'', in: ''Schriften des Vereins f\u00fcr Geschichte des Bodensees und seiner Umgebung'', 78. Jg. 1960, S. 110\u2013113. ([http://www.bodenseebibliotheken.eu/page?vgeb-j1960-t-A110 Digitalisat])\n\n== Weblinks ==\n{{Commonscat}}\n\n* [http://www.baukunst-nuernberg.de/epoche.php?epoche=Renaissance&objekt=Pellerhaus Pellerhaus (Baukunst N\u00fcrnberg)]\n* [http://www.altstadtfreunde-nuernberg.de/pellerhof.html Informationen der Altstadtfreunde zur Rekonstruktion des Pellerhofs]\n* [https://www.artstation.com/artwork/KxQoW 3D-Visualisierung des Pellerhauses am heutigen Egidienplatz] \u2013 Johannes Tscharn, 3D-K\u00fcnstler (ArchViz, ArtStation), abgerufen am 15. M\u00e4rz 2019\n* [http://www.museen.nuernberg.de/fembohaus/dauerausstellung/besondere-historische-raeume/ \u201eDas Sch\u00f6ne Zimmer\u201c aus dem Pellerhaus]\n* [https://gs-schenk.de/naturstein/projekte/pellerhof-egidienplatz/ Das Bauunternehmen GS SCHENK aus F\u00fcrth dokumentiert den Wiederaufbau des Pellerhauses]\n* [http://www.marktspiegel.de/nuernberg/lokales/wieder-gefundene-pellerhof-schaetze-kehren-nach-nuernberg-zurueck-d27584.html/action/recommend/1/ Wiedergefundene Pellerhof-Fassadenpl\u00e4ne kehren nach N\u00fcrnberg zur\u00fcck], Marktspiegel, 29. November 2017\n\n[[Category:Nuremberg]]\n[[Category:Germany]]\n[[Category:Architecture]]\n[[Category:Bavaria]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pellerhaus - Nuremberg}}\n", "name_user": "Gd123lbp", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pellerhaus_-_Nuremberg"}
{"title_page": "Wanda Urbanska", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{unreliable sources|date=May 2012}}\n{{BLP primary sources|date=May 2012}}\n{{BLP sources|date=May 2012}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Wanda Urbanska\n| image       = \n| birth_place = [[South Bend]], [[Indiana]]\n| nationality = [[United States|American]]\n| known_for   = Leading the [[Jan Karski]] US Centennial Campaign and Jan Karski Educational Foundation \n| occupation  = author and television host, and a media, public relations and political strategist\n}}\n'''Wanda Urbanska''' is an author and television host, and a media, public relations and political strategist. She formerly directed the Jan Karski US Centennial Campaign and currently is President of the Jan Karski Educational Foundation.<ref>[http://jankarski.net/1/618/About+Karski.html]</ref>  On May 29, 2012, the Campaign was successful in obtaining a [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] for Polish Underground hero of World War II, [[Jan Karski]].<ref>[http://www.whitehouse.gov/photos-and-video/video/2012/05/29/2012-presidential-medal-freedom-ceremony]</ref>\n \nThe author or coauthor of nine books, including ''The Heart of Simple Living: 7 Paths to a Better Life'' (Krause: 2010), Urbanska was host-producer of America's first nationally syndicated public TV series advocating sustainable living, ''Simple Living with Wanda Urbanska''.<ref>[http://www.financialintegrity.org/index.php?title=Simple_Living_with_Wanda_Urbanski]</ref> (The series ran on public television for four seasons from 2004 through 2008 and is now available on Hulu.com.<ref>[http://www.hulu.com/simple-living-with-wanda-urbanska]</ref>) She is published widely in the ''Los Angeles Times'', the ''Washington Post'', the ''Chicago Tribune'', ''Natural Home'', ''Mother Earth News'', and many others, and is a monthly blogger for the American Library Association's \u201c@ your library website.\u201d<ref>[http://atyourlibrary.org/wanda-urbanska]</ref>\n\nA graduate of Harvard University and a frequent visitor to Poland, her father's native land, Urbanska was awarded the prestigious [[Amicus Poloniae]] award in 2006 for promoting good will between America and Poland.<ref>[http://www.washington.polemb.net/index.php?document=256]</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nWanda Marie Urbanski was born in [[South Bend, Indiana]], when her father, Edmund Stephen Urbanski, was a visiting professor at Notre Dame. The family, which included her mother, Marie Olesen Urbanski, moved frequently during her childhood. She began writing professionally while still in high school for the ''[[Bangor Daily News]]'' in Maine and interned on-camera on Maine Public Television's live program, Maine News and Comment, during her senior year. While at Harvard, Urbanska interned at ''[[Newsweek]]'' magazine and was named one of ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]'' magazine's Top Ten College Women in 1977.  She traveled to Poland the summer of her junior year in college and, upon graduation in 1978, adopted the Polish feminine of her name professionally. In 2009 \u2013 2010, Urbanska took a seven-month sabbatical to Poland, with her then 12-year-old son, staying with a widowed friend in a townhouse in suburban Warsaw.\n\n=== Professional life===\nUrbanska began her career in [[New York City|New York]], working for ''[[The Paris Review]]'' as an associate editor. She later moved to Los Angeles where she joined the staff of the ''[[Los Angeles Herald Examiner]]'' as an assistant editor of its in-house Sunday magazine and later as a business reporter, covering retail, airlines and health care. She moved to Southwest Virginia in 1986 with her husband, Frank Levering, to take over his family\u2019s orchard business and wrote books in collaboration with him about the benefits of simple and rural living. ''Their Simple Living: One Couple's Search for a Better Life'' was published by Viking in 1992.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1986-11-13/news/vw-25191_1_singulars]</ref>  It was followed by ''Moving to a Small Town: A Guidebook for Moving from Urban to Rural America'' (1996). Urbanska co-authored ''Christmas on Jane Street: Based on a True Story'' with Billy Romp (1998). She co-authored ''Nothing's too Small to Make a Difference'' with Levering, which was published in 2004.\n \nShe hosted ''Simple Living with Wanda Urbanska'' for four seasons, which appeared on PBS stations nationally. The series advocates sustainable living based on the four multiple and overlapping principles of environmental stewardship; thoughtful consumption; community involvement; and financial responsibility.\n\n=== Personal life===\n\nUrbanska married Frank Levering in 1983 in [[Castine, Maine]]. They had one child, Henry, in 1997. Their marriage ended in divorce.\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Builders of Hope: A Social Entrepreneur's Solution for Rebuilding America'' (2011) {{ISBN|978-0-89587-568-6}}\n* ''The Heart of Simple Living: 7 Paths to a Better Life'' (2010) {{ISBN|978-1-4402-0451-7}}\n* ''Less is More: Embracing simplicity for a healthy planet, a caring economy and lasting happiness'' (2009) {{ISBN|978-0-86571-650-6}}\n*''The Singular Generation: Young Americans in the 1980s.'', Doubleday, 1986, {{ISBN|0385192649}}, 245pp.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://simplelivingfamily.wordpress.com/2010/08/26/wanda-urbanska-the-martha-stewart-of-simple-living/ Simple Living website]\n* [http://www.blairpub.com/authors/urbanska_levering.htm Blair Publishing website]\n* [http://content.usatoday.com/communities/greenhouse/post/2010/06/wanda-urbansks-simplicity-green-living/1 USA Today article about green living]\n* [http://content.usatoday.com/communities/greenhouse/post/2010/12/green-holiday-gifts-save-bucks-nature/1 USA Today article about saving money]\n* [http://content.usatoday.com/communities/greenhouse/post/2010/12/simplify-holidays-spend-less/1 USA Today article about simplifying for the holidays]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/09/your-money/three-generations-two-comfy-homes-a-few-steps-apart.html?pagewanted=all New York Times article about generational living]\n* [http://www.oprah.com/omagazine/Meet-Followers-of-the-Simple-Living-Philosophy/1 Oprah article about the simple living philosophy]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Urbanska, Wanda}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:People from South Bend, Indiana]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{unreliable sources|date=May 2012}}\n{{BLP primary sources|date=May 2012}}\n{{BLP sources|date=May 2012}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Wanda Urbanska\n| image       = \n| birth_place = [[South Bend]], [[Indiana]]\n| nationality = [[United States|American]]\n| known_for   = Leading the [[Jan Karski]] US Centennial Campaign and Jan Karski Educational Foundation \n| occupation  = author and television host, and a media, public relations and political strategist\n}}\n'''Wanda Urbanska''' is an author and television host, and a media, public relations and political strategist. She formerly directed the Jan Karski US Centennial Campaign and currently is President of the Jan Karski Educational Foundation.<ref>[http://jankarski.net/1/618/About+Karski.html]</ref>  On May 29, 2012, the Campaign was successful in obtaining a [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] for Polish Underground hero of World War II, [[Jan Karski]].<ref>[http://www.whitehouse.gov/photos-and-video/video/2012/05/29/2012-presidential-medal-freedom-ceremony]</ref>\n \nThe author or coauthor of nine books, including ''The Heart of Simple Living: 7 Paths to a Better Life'' (Krause: 2010), Urbanska was host-producer of America's first nationally syndicated public TV series advocating sustainable living, ''Simple Living with Wanda Urbanska''.<ref>[http://www.financialintegrity.org/index.php?title=Simple_Living_with_Wanda_Urbanski]</ref> (The series ran on public television for four seasons from 2004 through 2008 and is now available on Hulu.com.<ref>[http://www.hulu.com/simple-living-with-wanda-urbanska]</ref>) She is published widely in the ''Los Angeles Times'', the ''Washington Post'', the ''Chicago Tribune'', ''Natural Home'', ''Mother Earth News'', and many others, and is a monthly blogger for the American Library Association's \u201c@ your library website.\u201d<ref>[http://atyourlibrary.org/wanda-urbanska]</ref>\n\nA graduate of Harvard University and a frequent visitor to Poland, her father's native land, Urbanska was awarded the prestigious [[Amicus Poloniae]] award in 2006 for promoting good will between America and Poland.<ref>[http://www.washington.polemb.net/index.php?document=256]</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nWanda Marie Urbanski was born in [[South Bend, Indiana]], when her father, Edmund Stephen Urbanski, was a visiting professor at Notre Dame. The family, which included her mother, Marie Olesen Urbanski, moved frequently during her childhood. She began writing professionally while still in high school for the ''[[Bangor Daily News]]'' in Maine and interned on-camera on Maine Public Television's live program, Maine News and Comment, during her senior year. While at Harvard, Urbanska interned at ''[[Newsweek]]'' magazine and was named one of ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]'' magazine's Top Ten College Women in 1977.  She traveled to Poland the summer of her junior year in college and, upon graduation in 1978, adopted the Polish feminine of her name professionally. In 2009 \u2013 2010, Urbanska took a seven-month sabbatical to Poland, with her then 12-year-old son, staying with a widowed friend in a townhouse in suburban Warsaw.\n\n=== Professional life===\nUrbanska began her career in [[New York]], working for ''[[The Paris Review]]'' as an associate editor. She later moved to Los Angeles where she joined the staff of the ''[[Los Angeles Herald Examiner]]'' as an assistant editor of its in-house Sunday magazine and later as a business reporter, covering retail, airlines and health care. She moved to Southwest Virginia in 1986 with her husband, Frank Levering, to take over his family\u2019s orchard business and wrote books in collaboration with him about the benefits of simple and rural living. ''Their Simple Living: One Couple's Search for a Better Life'' was published by Viking in 1992.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1986-11-13/news/vw-25191_1_singulars]</ref>  It was followed by ''Moving to a Small Town: A Guidebook for Moving from Urban to Rural America'' (1996). Urbanska co-authored ''Christmas on Jane Street: Based on a True Story'' with Billy Romp (1998). She co-authored ''Nothing's too Small to Make a Difference'' with Levering, which was published in 2004.\n \nShe hosted ''Simple Living with Wanda Urbanska'' for four seasons, which appeared on PBS stations nationally. The series advocates sustainable living based on the four multiple and overlapping principles of environmental stewardship; thoughtful consumption; community involvement; and financial responsibility.\n\n=== Personal life===\n\nUrbanska married Frank Levering in 1983 in [[Castine, Maine]]. They had one child, Henry, in 1997. Their marriage ended in divorce.\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Builders of Hope: A Social Entrepreneur's Solution for Rebuilding America'' (2011) {{ISBN|978-0-89587-568-6}}\n* ''The Heart of Simple Living: 7 Paths to a Better Life'' (2010) {{ISBN|978-1-4402-0451-7}}\n* ''Less is More: Embracing simplicity for a healthy planet, a caring economy and lasting happiness'' (2009) {{ISBN|978-0-86571-650-6}}\n*''The Singular Generation: Young Americans in the 1980s.'', Doubleday, 1986, {{ISBN|0385192649}}, 245pp.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://simplelivingfamily.wordpress.com/2010/08/26/wanda-urbanska-the-martha-stewart-of-simple-living/ Simple Living website]\n* [http://www.blairpub.com/authors/urbanska_levering.htm Blair Publishing website]\n* [http://content.usatoday.com/communities/greenhouse/post/2010/06/wanda-urbansks-simplicity-green-living/1 USA Today article about green living]\n* [http://content.usatoday.com/communities/greenhouse/post/2010/12/green-holiday-gifts-save-bucks-nature/1 USA Today article about saving money]\n* [http://content.usatoday.com/communities/greenhouse/post/2010/12/simplify-holidays-spend-less/1 USA Today article about simplifying for the holidays]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/09/your-money/three-generations-two-comfy-homes-a-few-steps-apart.html?pagewanted=all New York Times article about generational living]\n* [http://www.oprah.com/omagazine/Meet-Followers-of-the-Simple-Living-Philosophy/1 Oprah article about the simple living philosophy]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Urbanska, Wanda}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:People from South Bend, Indiana]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toNew York(link changed toNew York City) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wanda_Urbanska"}
{"title_page": "Joe Burrow", "text_new": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{Short description|American football quarterback}}\n{{Use American English|date = September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n<!-- DO NOT ADD BEFORE THE 2020 NFL DRAFT\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name                = Joe Burrow\n| image               = LSU Football at the White House (49400533066) (cropped).jpg\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Burrow in 2019\n| number              = \n| current_team        = \n| position            = [[Quarterback]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1996|12|10}}\n| birth_place         = [[Ames, Iowa]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 3\n| weight_lb           = 221\n| high_school         = [[Athens High School (Ohio)|Athens]] (The Plains, Ohio)\n| college             = [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]]\n| draftyear           = 2020\n| draftround          = \n| draftpick           = \n| pastteams           = \n* [[]] ({{NFL Year|2020}}\u2013present)\n| status              = Unsigned draft pick\n| highlights          = \n* [[College football national championships in NCAA Division I FBS|National champion]] ([[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|2019]])\n* [[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|National Championship offensive MVP]]\n* [[Heisman Trophy]] (2019)\n* [[Maxwell Award]] (2019)\n* [[Walter Camp Award]] (2019)\n* [[Johnny Unitas Golden Arm Award]] (2019)\n* [[Davey O'Brien Award]] (2019)\n* [[Manning Award]] (2019)\n* [[AP College Football Player of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[Sporting News College Football Player of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[Unanimous All-American]] ([[2019 College Football All-America Team|2019]])\n* [[SEC Offensive Player of the Year]] ([[2019 Southeastern Conference football season|2019]])\n| statleague          = NFL\n| statseason          = 2020\n| statweek            = \n| statlabel1          = [[Touchdown|TD]]\u2013[[Interception|INT]]\n| statvalue1          = 0\u20130\n| statlabel2          = Passing yards\n| statvalue2          = 0\n| statlabel3          = Completion percentage\n| statvalue3          = 0\n| statlabel4          = [[Passer rating]]\n| statvalue4          = 0\n| statlabel5          = Rushing yards\n| statvalue5          = 0\n| statlabel6          = Rushing touchdowns\n| statvalue6          = 0\n| nflnew              = \n| pfr                 = \n}}\n-->\n{{Infobox college football player\n|name=Joe Burrow\n|image=Joe Burrow (SELU vs LSU, September 8, 2018).jpg\n|caption=Burrow in 2018\n|school=LSU Tigers\n|currentnumber=9\n|currentposition=[[Quarterback]]\n|class= {{Redshirt}} Senior\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1996|12|10}}\n|birth_place=[[Ames, Iowa]]\n|heightft=6\n|heightin=4\n|weight_lb=216\n|highlights=\n* [[College football national championships in NCAA Division I FBS|National champion]] ([[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|2019]])\n* [[Heisman Trophy]] (2019)\n* [[Maxwell Award]] (2019)\n* [[Walter Camp Award]] (2019)\n* [[Johnny Unitas Golden Arm Award]] (2019)\n* [[Davey O'Brien Award]] (2019)\n* [[Manning Award]] (2019)\n* [[AP College Football Player of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[Sporting News College Football Player of the Year|Sporting News Player of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[Unanimous All-American]] ([[2019 College Football All-America Team|2019]])\n* [[SEC Offensive Player of the Year]] ([[2019 Southeastern Conference football season|2019]])\n* [[Southeastern Conference football individual awards|First-team All-SEC]] ([[2019 All-SEC football team|2019]])\n* [[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|College Football Playoff National Championship Offensive MVP]] (2020)\n|highschool=[[Athens High School (Ohio)|Athens]] (The Plains, Ohio)\n|pastschools=\n*[[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]] (2015\u20132017)\n*[[LSU Tigers football|LSU]] (2018\u20132019)\n|bowlgames=\n*[[2017 Cotton Bowl Classic (December)|2017 Cotton Bowl]]\n*[[2019 Fiesta Bowl (January)|2019 Fiesta Bowl]]\n*[[2019 Peach Bowl]]\n*[[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|2020 National Championship Game]]\n|espn=3915511\n}}\n\n'''Joseph Lee Burrow''' (born December 10, 1996) is an [[American football]] [[quarterback]] for the [[LSU Tigers football|LSU Tigers]]. Before transferring to LSU, Burrow began his collegiate career at [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]]. In 2019, his second and final season with LSU, Burrow passed for over 5,600 yards with 60 touchdowns, the latter being the most in a single season in NCAA [[NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision|FBS]] history, while also leading LSU to victory in the [[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|2020 National Championship Game]]. He won several awards and honors for his performance, including the [[Heisman Trophy]]. Several journalists and sportswriters deemed the season to be the greatest ever by a college quarterback.\n\n==Early years==\nJoseph Lee Burrow<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://registrar.osu.edu/staff/commence_bulletins/sp2018_commence.pdf |title=2018 Spring Commencement program |website=OSU.edu |publisher=The Ohio State University |page=73}}</ref> was born in [[Ames, Iowa]], on December 10, 1996.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Peterson |first1=Randy |title=Peterson: Heisman Trophy front-runner Joe Burrow will be forever linked to Ames and that house on McKinley Drive |url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/sports/college/iowa-state/randy-peterson/2019/12/13/joe-burrow-possible-heisman-trophy-trek-started-ames-iowa/4398775002/ |website=Des Moines Register |accessdate=January 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Joe Burrow |url=https://thedraftnetwork.com/player/joe-burrow/EnLnVc2K3a |website=The Draft Network |accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref> He is the son of former [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|University of Nebraska]], [[National Football League|NFL]], and [[Canadian Football League|CFL]] player [[Jim Burrow]], who went on to a coaching career that lasted nearly 40 years. The elder Burrow, whose last coaching position was [[defensive coordinator]] for the [[Ohio Bobcats football|Ohio Bobcats]] for more than a decade, retired after the 2018 season in part to be able to see all of Joe's games in his final college season. Burrow was born in Ames, while his father was on the staff for the [[Iowa State Cyclones football|Iowa State Cyclones]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/sports/college/iowa-state/randy-peterson/2019/09/05/college-gameday-espn-tom-herman-joe-burrow-iowa-state-cyclones-lsu-texas-longhorns-big-12-picks/2220376001/ |title=Peterson's Big 12 picks: Ames roots run deep in NCAA football's biggest Week 2 game |last=Peterson |first=Randy |date=September 8, 2019 |access-date=October 1, 2019 |newspaper=Des Moines Register}}</ref> According to a 2019 ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' story, \"The Burrow athletic lineage dates back nearly a century.\" In the 1940s, one of his grandmothers set a Mississippi state high school record with an 82-point game in basketball. His paternal grandfather played basketball at [[Mississippi State Bulldogs men's basketball|Mississippi State]]; his uncle, John Burrow, played football at [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Ole Miss]]; and two older brothers also played football at Nebraska.<ref name=\"Dellenger\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.si.com/college-football/2019/07/15/joe-burrow-lsu-sec-media-days |title=Meet Joe Burrow: LSU's Toughest Renaissance Man and Maybe Savior at QB |last=Dellenger |first=Ross |date=July 15, 2019 |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |access-date=July 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe attended the [[2002 Rose Bowl]] at age six, as his father was an assistant coach for Nebraska. Not long after, he began playing in youth football leagues. Unlike his father, uncle, and brothers, who all played on defense, Burrow started out as a quarterback, because his first youth team had no one else who could play the position.<ref name=Dellenger/> The Burrow family moved to [[Fargo, North Dakota]], in 2003 when his father was hired as the defensive coordinator for the [[North Dakota State Bison football|North Dakota State Bison]]. One day while visiting the office, future [[Central Michigan Chippewas football|Central Michigan]] head coach [[Dan Enos]] commented that the seven year old had a future in football.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.inforum.com/bison-media-zone/mens-sports/football/4819431-Kolpack-Heisman-Trophy-favorite-has-roots-with-Bison-football-Fargo-elementary-school |title=Kolpack: Heisman Trophy favorite has roots with Bison football, Fargo elementary school |last=Kolpack |first=Jeff |date=December 12, 2019 |website=INFORUM |language=en |access-date=December 13, 2019}}</ref> The Burrows spent two years in Fargo before Jimmy accepted the defensive coordinator position at [[Ohio Bobcats football|Ohio University]] in [[Athens, Ohio]].\n\nBurrow attended [[Athens High School (Ohio)|Athens High School]] (2011\u201314) in [[The Plains, Ohio]], leading the school to three straight playoff appearances and the school's first seven playoff victories in school history.<ref name=\"lsu bio\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.lsusports.net/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=5200&ATCLID=211716545 |title=Joe Burrow Bio |website=LSUSports.net |publisher=LSU Tigers Athletics |access-date=September 27, 2019}}</ref> During his career, he passed for 11,416 yards with 157 passing [[touchdowns]] and rushed for 2,067 yards with 27 rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_b12cabf8-65e2-11e8-889b-c3de62778f9f.html |title=Ultimate competitor: Joe Burrow's work ethic, storied high school career could bode well for LSU |last=Mickles |first=Sheldon |date=June 1, 2018 |website=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|The Advocate]] |access-date=September 4, 2019}}</ref> He was awarded the state's [[Mr. Football Award (Ohio)|Mr. Football Award]] and Gatorade Player of the Year award as a senior in 2014. He and his Bulldog teammates went 14\u20131 that season. He was also a standout basketball player, and was named first-team all-state at point guard his senior year.<ref name=\"lsu bio\" /> Burrow was rated as a four-star football recruit, and was the eighth-highest ranked [[dual-threat quarterback]] in the class of 2015 according to the [[247Sports]] Composite.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://247sports.com/Player/Joe-Burrow-36575/high-school-60304/ |title=Joe Burrow, Athens, Dual-Threat Quarterback |website=[[247Sports.com]] |access-date=September 10, 2019}}</ref> He committed to [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]] to play football on May 27, 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cleveland.com/osu/2014/05/ohio_state_lands_pledge_from_j.html |title=Ohio State lands pledge from Joe Burrow, 3-star QB from Athens, Ohio: Buckeyes recruiting |last=Lesmerises |first=Doug |date=May 27, 2014 |website=Cleveland.com |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ohio.com/akron/sports/qb-joe-burrow-commits-to-ohio-state |title=QB Joe Burrow commits to Ohio State |date=May 27, 2014 |website=[[Akron Beacon Journal]] |publisher=[[Black Press]] |access-date=September 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, the Athens City School District school board unanimously approved a measure to rename the school's football stadium in honor of Burrow.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_c106d86c-22d0-11ea-8694-8b4408725ff9.html |title=Joe Burrow Stadium: LSU QB's high school to name football stadium after him |date=December 19, 2019 |website=The Advocate |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\n===Ohio State===\nAfter [[Redshirt (college sports)|redshirting]] his first year at Ohio State in 2015, Burrow spent the next two years as a backup to [[J. T. Barrett]]. Over the two years, he played in 10 games, completing 29 of 39 passes for 287 yards and two touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_f20ae018-92e2-11e8-ad16-b749223c17f7.html |title=LSU quarterback competition: The case for Joe Burrow |last=Suss |first=Nick |date=July 28, 2018 |work=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|The Advocate]] |access-date=October 1, 2018}}</ref> Realizing that [[Dwayne Haskins]] would be named starting quarterback at Ohio State, Burrow transferred to [[Louisiana State University]] (LSU) on May 20, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cleveland.com/osu/2018/05/what_the_joe_burrow_transfer_m.html |title=How the Joe Burrow transfer changes Dwayne Haskins: Ohio State football analysis |last=Lesmerises |first=Doug |date=May 9, 2018 |work=[[The Plain Dealer]] |access-date=October 2, 2018 |publisher=[[Advance Publications]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/23542226/quarterback-joe-burrow-transferring-lsu-tigers-ohio-state-buckeyes |title=QB Joe Burrow transferring to LSU for final two seasons |last=Khan Jr. |first=Sam |date=May 19, 2018 |work=[[ESPN]] |access-date=October 1, 2018}}</ref> Burrow had graduated from Ohio State in three years with a degree in consumer and family financial services, and would be immediately eligible as a graduate transfer.<ref name=\"fox starter\" />\n\n===LSU===\n====2018====\n[[File:GA VS LSU E101318 146.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Burrow in 2018]]\n\nIn his first year at LSU, Burrow was named the starting quarterback as a redshirt junior in [[2018 LSU Tigers football team|2018]].<ref name=\"fox starter\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.foxsports.com/college-football/story/ohio-state-transfer-qb-burrow-named-lsu-starter-vs-miami-082718 |title=Ohio State transfer Joe Burrow is LSU\u2019s starting quarterback |date=August 27, 2018 |work=[[Fox Sports]] |access-date=October 1, 2018 |agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> In an early season road trip to then-No. 7 [[2018 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]], Burrow threw for 249 yards and a touchdown en route to a 22\u201321 win. He was named SEC Offensive Player of the Week following the victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lsusports.net/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=5200&ATCLID=211772287 |title=Burrow, Tracy Earn SEC Player of the Week Honors |last=Bonnette |first=Michael |date=September 17, 2018 |website=LSUSports.net |publisher=LSU Athletics |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref> He again earned SEC Offensive Player of the Week honors following a 292-yard, three-touchdown performance against [[2018 Ole Miss Rebels football team|Ole Miss]] two weeks later.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_c7cf9240-c595-11e8-8938-13440efa4717.html |title=LSU quarterback Joe Burrow named SEC Offensive Player of the Week |last=Kubena |first=Brooks |date=October 2, 2018 |location=Baton Rouge, Louisiana |access-date=October 1, 2019 |newspaper=The Advocate}}</ref> Burrow helped lead the Tigers to a 10\u20133 record, including a win over [[2018 UCF Knights football team|UCF]] in the [[2019 Fiesta Bowl (January)|Fiesta Bowl]], and a No. 6 ranking in the final AP Poll. Burrow finished the season with 2,894 yards passing, 16 touchdowns, and five interceptions. He added 399 rushing yards and seven rushing touchdowns.<ref name=\"sports-reference\" />\n\n====2019====\n[[File:LSU Football at the White House (49400533066) (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|150px|Burrow in the [[Oval Office]] following the 2019 season]]\n\nBurrow was again named LSU's starting quarterback heading into his redshirt senior season in [[2019 LSU Tigers football team|2019]]. In the Tigers' season opener against [[2018 Georgia Southern Eagles football team|Georgia Southern]], Burrow threw for 278 yards and five touchdowns in a 55\u20133 win, and was later named SEC Co-Offensive Player of the Week (with [[Tua Tagovailoa]]).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://247sports.com/college/lsu/Article/LSU-Tigers-quarterback-Joe-Burrow-week-one-Georgia-Southern-SEC-Offensive-Player-of-the-Week-135186050/ |title=Joe Burrow grabs SEC Offensive Player of the Week |last=Dixon |first=Shea |date=September 4, 2019 |website=247Sports.com |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref> In a week two road trip to then-No. 9 [[2019 Texas Longhorns football team|Texas]], Burrow threw for 471 yards, four touchdowns, and an interception in the 45\u201338 win. His 471 yards were the second most in school history and most since [[Rohan Davey]]'s 528 against Alabama in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lsusports.net/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=5200&ATCLID=211811103 |title=Burrow, LSU Make History in Victory Over Texas |date=September 7, 2019 |website=LSUSports.net |publisher=LSU Athletics |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref> He was named Walter Camp National Offensive Player of the Week and SEC Offensive Player of the Week following the performance.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tigerdroppings.com/lsu-football/joe-burrow-named-walter-camp-offensive-player-of-the-week/85257656/ |title=Joe Burrow Named Walter Camp Offensive Player Of The Week |date=September 8, 2019 |website=tigerdroppings.com |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref> Burrow earned his third SEC Offensive Player of the Week honors on September 21 during LSU's game against [[2019 Vanderbilt Commodores football team|Vanderbilt]]. He threw for 398 yards and a school-record-setting six passing touchdowns in the Tigers' 66\u201338 win. He became the first LSU quarterback to ever throw for 350 yards in three consecutive games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.secsports.com/article/27684582/football-players-week |title=Week 4: Football Players of the Week |date=September 23, 2019 |website=SECSports.com |publisher=Southeastern Conference |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn a 42\u20136 win over [[2019 Utah State Aggies football team|Utah State]], Burrow threw for 344 yards and five touchdowns, and became the first ever Tiger quarterback to throw for 300-plus yards in four consecutive games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=401110813 |title=Joe Burrow makes history as No. 5 LSU routs Utah State |date=October 5, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 1, 2020 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> The streak came to an end the next week against then-No. 7 [[2019 Florida Gators football team|Florida]], but Burrow's 293 yards and three touchdown passes helped lead the Tigers to another win, 42\u201328.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=401110819 |title=Joe Burrow's 3 TDs lift No. 5 LSU over No. 7 Florida 42-28 |date=October 12, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 1, 2020 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> The next week, in LSU's seventh game of the season, Burrow eclipsed the LSU single-season passing touchdowns record of 28 when he added four more in a win against [[2019 Mississippi State Bulldogs football team|Mississippi State]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=401110828 |title=Joe Burrow throws 4 TDs passes, No. 2 LSU routs MSU 36-13 |date=October 19, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 1, 2020 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Burrow led the Tigers to another top-ten win, and broke the LSU record for career 300-yard games (eight) with a 321-yard, two-total-touchdown performance against then-No. 9 [[2019 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=401110833 |title=Burrow's 321 yards helps No. 2 LSU down No. 9 Auburn, 23-20 |date=October 26, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 1, 2020 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\nLSU's November 9 game against [[2019 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]] was highly anticipated as the highest ranked showdown between the two schools since the [[2012 BCS National Championship Game]]; LSU was ranked second and Alabama third in the season's inaugural [[College Football Playoff]] rankings released the week prior. The game would also feature two leading candidates for the [[Heisman Trophy]] in Burrow and Alabama quarterback [[Tua Tagovailoa]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2672771-alabama-vs-lsu-game-preview-prediction-and-players-to-watch#slide0 |title=Alabama vs. LSU: Game Preview, Prediction and Players to Watch |last=Pedersen |first=Brian |date=October 31, 2019 |website=BleacherReport}}</ref> Burrow and the Tigers came away victorious in a 46\u201341 shootout. Burrow passed for 393 yards and three touchdowns in the game,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=401110842 |title=Joe Burrow leads No. 2 LSU past No. 3 Alabama in 46-41 thriller |date=November 9, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 1, 2020 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> and was again named Walter Camp National Offensive Player of the Week and SEC Co-Offensive Player of the Week, sharing the latter with teammate [[Clyde Edwards-Helaire]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_98c5e424-0426-11ea-81b0-5b10caea9825.html |title=LSU's Joe Burrow named Walter Camp National Offensive Player of the Week |last=Kubena |first=Brooks |date=November 10, 2019 |location=Baton Rouge, LA |newspaper=The Advocate}}</ref>\n\nThe following week against [[2019 Ole Miss Rebels football team|Ole Miss]], Burrow threw for 489 yards and five touchdown passes, and passed LSU's single-season passing yards record set by Rohan Davey in 2001. He also set the LSU record of consecutive completed passes with 17 during the game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=401110850 |title=Burrow throws 5 TDs, No. 1 LSU beats Mississippi 58-37 |date=November 16, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 1, 2020 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> On November 30, Burrow helped LSU secure an undefeated regular season with a 50\u20137 blowout win over [[2019 Texas A&M Aggies football team|Texas A&M]], throwing for 352 yards and three touchdowns. During the game, he set the all-time SEC record for single-season passing yards (previously set by [[Kentucky Wildcats football|Kentucky's]] [[Tim Couch]]), and tied the conference record for single-season touchdowns of [[Missouri Tigers football|Missouri's]] [[Drew Lock]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=401110869 |title=Burrow, No. 1 LSU dominate Texas A&M, 50-7 |date=November 30, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 1, 2020 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Burrow took sole possession of the SEC single-season touchdown record the following week in the [[2019 SEC Championship Game|SEC Championship Game]], throwing for four TDs in LSU's dominant 37\u201310 win over [[2019 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia]] that secured the Tigers' place in the [[College Football Playoff]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=401132981 |title=Burrow completes Heisman coronation, LSU routs Georgia 37-10 |date=December 7, 2019 |access-date=December 7, 2019 |agency=Associated Press |website=ESPN.com}}</ref> \n\n[[File:2020-0113-OrgeronBurrowQueen.PNG|thumb|upright=1.2|left|150px|Burrow (''center'') with LSU head coach [[Ed Orgeron]] (''left'') and linebacker [[Patrick Queen]] (''right'') at LSU's 2020 National Championship post-game press event]]\nOn December 14, 2019, Burrow was awarded the 2019 [[Heisman Trophy]], winning by the largest margin in the history of the award, also earning the highest share of possible points available.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/2019/12/14/lsu-qb-joe-burrow-wins-heisman-trophy/2637969001/ |title=LSU quarterback Joe Burrow wins 2019 Heisman Trophy by record-setting margin |last=Myerberg |first=Paul |date=December 14, 2019 |website=USA Today |access-date=January 1, 2020}}</ref> Burrow's Heisman acceptance speech, in which he referenced the rampant poverty and [[food insecurity]] affecting his hometown, inspired over {{USD}}450,000 in donations towards the local food bank in [[Athens County]] from over 13,000 donors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/12/28/opinions/food-insecurity-joe-burrow-paz/index.html|title=Joe Burrow's Heisman speech is a call to action on food insecurity|last=Paz|first=Harold|date=December 28, 2019|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref> Other awards he won that year include the [[Maxwell Award]], [[Walter Camp Award]], [[Johnny Unitas Golden Arm Award]], [[Davey O'Brien Award]], and [[Manning Award]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Mannings' choice: Joe Burrow wins another award after historic season |url=https://www.wbrz.com/news/mannings-choice-joe-burrow-wins-another-award-after-historic-season/ |website=WBRZ.com |accessdate=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the playoff semifinal game at the [[2019 Peach Bowl]], Burrow recorded 29-of-39 pass attempts for 493 passing yards and seven passing touchdowns (all seven touchdowns in the first half), to go along with five rushes for 22 rushing yards and a rushing touchdown in a 63\u201328 victory over fourth-ranked [[2019 Oklahoma Sooners football team|Oklahoma]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2019-12-28/peach-bowl-joe-burrow-throws-seven-tds-no-1-lsu-routs-no-4-oklahoma |title=Peach Bowl: Joe Burrow throws for seven touchdowns as No. 1 LSU routs No. 4 Oklahoma |date=December 29, 2019 |website=Los Angeles Times |language=en-US |access-date=January 1, 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn the [[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|2020 National Championship Game]] against Clemson, Burrow threw for 463 yards with six total touchdowns, five passing, which led LSU to a 42\u201325 victory and him being named the game's offensive MVP.<ref name=\"2019Records\"/> He finished his 2019 season with 60 passing touchdowns, which broke the single-season [[NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision|FBS]] record previously held by [[Colt Brennan]] in 2006 (58).<ref name=\"2019Records\"/> His 5,671 passing yards ranks third all-time in an FBS season, tied with [[Case Keenum]] (2009).<ref name=\"2019Records\">{{cite web |last1=Kercheval |first1=Ben |title=LSU vs. Clemson: Every record Joe Burrow broke as all-time great season ends with national championship |url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/lsu-vs-clemson-every-record-joe-burrow-broke-as-all-time-great-season-ends-with-national-championship/ |publisher=CBS Sports |accessdate=January 16, 2020 |date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> His [[passer rating]] of 202 for the season was also a record.<ref name=\"2019Records\"/><ref name=\"sports-reference\" /> Several sportswriters deemed the season to be the greatest ever by a college quarterback.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wolken |first1=Dan |title=Opinion: LSU's Joe Burrow completes greatest single season by college QB with national title |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/college/columnist/dan-wolken/2020/01/14/lsu-joe-burrow-beat-clemson-win-college-football-national-title/4458538002/ |accessdate=January 16, 2020 |work=USA Today |date=January 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=LSU captures the national championship as Joe Burrow caps the greatest season ever |url=https://www.foxsports.com/college-football/story/lsu-captures-the-national-championship-as-joe-burrow-caps-the-greatest-season-ever-011420 |publisher=Fox Sports |accessdate=January 16, 2020 |date=January 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kramer |first1=Adam |title=Joe Burrow Caps Greatest Individual Season in CFB History with Title Win |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2871264-joe-burrow-caps-greatest-individual-season-in-cfb-history-with-title-win |publisher=Bleacher Report |accessdate=January 16, 2020 |date=January 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Thamel |first1=Pete |title=How Joe Burrow authored the best season in college football history |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/how-joe-burrow-authored-one-of-the-best-college-football-seasons-in-history-062313307.html |publisher=Yahoo Sports |accessdate=January 16, 2020 |date=January 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Statistics=== \n{| class=\"wikitable\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Legend\n|-\n| style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"|\n| Led the NCAA\n|-\n| style=\"background:#E0CEF2; width:3em;\"|\n| NCAA record\n|-\n| '''Bold'''\n| Career high\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | &nbsp;\n! colspan=\"8\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Passing\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Rushing\n|-\n! Season !! Team !! GP !! Rating !! Att !! Comp !! Pct !! Yds !! TD !! Int !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! TD\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[2015 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2015]] || [[2015 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]] || colspan=\"12\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''Redshirt''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[2016 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2016]] || [[2016 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]]\n| 5 || 169.9 || 28|| 22 || '''78.6''' || 226 || 2 || 0 || 12 || 58 || 4.8 || 1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[2017 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2017]] || [[2017 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]]\n| 5 || 110.2 || 11 || 7 || 63.6 || 61 || 0 || 0 || 3 || -5 || -1.7 || 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[2018 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2018]] || [[2018 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]]\n| 13 || 133.2 || 379 || 219 || 57.8 || 2,894 || 16 || 5 || '''128''' || '''399''' || 3.1 || '''7'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[2019 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2019]] || [[2019 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]]\n| '''15''' || style=\"background:#E0CEF2;\"| '''202.0''' || '''527''' || '''402''' || style=\"background:#cfecec;\"| 76.3 || style=\"background:#cfecec;\"| '''5,671''' || style=\"background:#E0CEF2;\" | '''60''' || '''6''' || 115 || 368 || '''3.2''' || 5\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | '''Career'''\n| '''37''' || '''172.4''' || '''945''' || '''650''' || '''6