{Navboxes|title=Joe Burrow|list=\n{{LSU Tigers quarterback navbox}}\n{{2019 LSU Tigers football navbox}}\n{{Heisman Trophy}}\n{{Maxwell Award}}\n{{Walter Camp Award}}\n{{AP College Football Player of the Year}}\n{{Sporting News College Football Player of the Year}}\n{{2019 NCAA Division I FBS College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{Davey O'Brien Award}}\n{{Johnny Unitas Award}}\n{{Manning Award}}\n{{Southeastern Conference Football Player of the Year navbox}}\n{{NCAA major college football passing yardage leaders}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burrow, Joe}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:Heisman Trophy winners]]\n[[Category:LSU Tigers football players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Maxwell Award winners]]\n[[Category:Ohio State Buckeyes football players]]\n[[Category:People from Athens, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Ames, Iowa]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{Short description|American football quarterback}}\n{{Use American English|date = September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n<!-- DO NOT ADD BEFORE THE 2020 NFL DRAFT\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name                = Joe Burrow\n| image               = LSU Football at the White House (49400533066) (cropped).jpg\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Burrow in 2019\n| number              = \n| current_team        = \n| position            = [[Quarterback]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1996|12|10}}\n| birth_place         = [[Ames, Iowa]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 3\n| weight_lb           = 221\n| high_school         = [[Athens High School (Ohio)|Athens]] (The Plains, Ohio)\n| college             = [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]]\n| draftyear           = 2020\n| draftround          = \n| draftpick           = \n| pastteams           = \n* [[]] ({{NFL Year|2020}}\u2013present)\n| status              = Unsigned draft pick\n| highlights          = \n* [[College football national championships in NCAA Division I FBS|National champion]] ([[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|2019]])\n* [[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|National Championship offensive MVP]]\n* [[Heisman Trophy]] (2019)\n* [[Maxwell Award]] (2019)\n* [[Walter Camp Award]] (2019)\n* [[Johnny Unitas Golden Arm Award]] (2019)\n* [[Davey O'Brien Award]] (2019)\n* [[Manning Award]] (2019)\n* [[AP College Football Player of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[Sporting News College Football Player of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[Unanimous All-American]] ([[2019 College Football All-America Team|2019]])\n* [[SEC Offensive Player of the Year]] ([[2019 Southeastern Conference football season|2019]])\n| statleague          = NFL\n| statseason          = 2020\n| statweek            = \n| statlabel1          = [[Touchdown|TD]]\u2013[[Interception|INT]]\n| statvalue1          = 0\u20130\n| statlabel2          = Passing yards\n| statvalue2          = 0\n| statlabel3          = Completion percentage\n| statvalue3          = 0\n| statlabel4          = [[Passer rating]]\n| statvalue4          = 0\n| statlabel5          = Rushing yards\n| statvalue5          = 0\n| statlabel6          = Rushing touchdowns\n| statvalue6          = 0\n| nflnew              = \n| pfr                 = \n}}\n-->\n{{Infobox college football player\n|name=Joe Burrow\n|image=Joe Burrow (SELU vs LSU, September 8, 2018).jpg\n|caption=Burrow in 2018\n|school=LSU Tigers\n|currentnumber=9\n|currentposition=[[Quarterback]]\n|class= {{Redshirt}} Senior\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1996|12|10}}\n|birth_place=[[Ames, Iowa]]\n|heightft=6\n|heightin=4\n|weight_lb=216\n|highlights=\n* [[College football national championships in NCAA Division I FBS|National champion]] ([[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|2019]])\n* [[Heisman Trophy]] (2019)\n* [[Maxwell Award]] (2019)\n* [[Walter Camp Award]] (2019)\n* [[Johnny Unitas Golden Arm Award]] (2019)\n* [[Davey O'Brien Award]] (2019)\n* [[Manning Award]] (2019)\n* [[AP College Football Player of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[Sporting News College Football Player of the Year|Sporting News Player of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[Unanimous All-American]] ([[2019 College Football All-America Team|2019]])\n* [[SEC Offensive Player of the Year]] ([[2019 Southeastern Conference football season|2019]])\n* [[Southeastern Conference football individual awards|First-team All-SEC]] ([[2019 All-SEC football team|2019]])\n* [[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|College Football Playoff National Championship Offensive MVP]] (2020)\n|highschool=[[Athens High School (Ohio)|Athens]] (The Plains, Ohio)\n|pastschools=\n*[[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]] (2015\u20132017)\n*[[LSU Tigers football|LSU]] (2018\u20132019)\n|bowlgames=\n*[[2017 Cotton Bowl Classic (December)|2017 Cotton Bowl]]\n*[[2019 Fiesta Bowl (January)|2019 Fiesta Bowl]]\n*[[2019 Peach Bowl]]\n*[[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|2020 National Championship Game]]\n|espn=3915511\n}}\n\n'''Joseph Lee Burrow''' (born December 10, 1996) is an [[American football]] [[quarterback]] for the [[LSU Tigers football|LSU Tigers]]. Before transferring to LSU, Burrow began his collegiate career at [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]]. In 2019, his second and final season with LSU, Burrow passed for over 5,600 yards with 60 touchdowns, the latter being the most in a single season in NCAA [[NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision|FBS]] history, while also leading LSU to victory in the [[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|2020 National Championship Game]]. He won several awards and honors for his performance, including the [[Heisman Trophy]]. Several journalists and sportswriters deemed the season to be the greatest ever by a college quarterback.\n\n==Early years==\nJoseph Lee Burrow<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://registrar.osu.edu/staff/commence_bulletins/sp2018_commence.pdf |title=2018 Spring Commencement program |website=OSU.edu |publisher=The Ohio State University |page=73}}</ref> was born in [[Ames, Iowa]], on December 10, 1996.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Peterson |first1=Randy |title=Peterson: Heisman Trophy front-runner Joe Burrow will be forever linked to Ames and that house on McKinley Drive |url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/sports/college/iowa-state/randy-peterson/2019/12/13/joe-burrow-possible-heisman-trophy-trek-started-ames-iowa/4398775002/ |website=Des Moines Register |accessdate=January 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Joe Burrow |url=https://thedraftnetwork.com/player/joe-burrow/EnLnVc2K3a |website=The Draft Network |accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref> He is the son of former [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|University of Nebraska]], [[National Football League|NFL]], and [[Canadian Football League|CFL]] player [[Jim Burrow]], who went on to a coaching career that lasted nearly 40 years. The elder Burrow, whose last coaching position was [[defensive coordinator]] for the [[Ohio Bobcats football|Ohio Bobcats]] for more than a decade, retired after the 2018 season in part to be able to see all of Joe's games in his final college season. Burrow was born in Ames, while his father was on the staff for the [[Iowa State Cyclones football|Iowa State Cyclones]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/sports/college/iowa-state/randy-peterson/2019/09/05/college-gameday-espn-tom-herman-joe-burrow-iowa-state-cyclones-lsu-texas-longhorns-big-12-picks/2220376001/ |title=Peterson's Big 12 picks: Ames roots run deep in NCAA football's biggest Week 2 game |last=Peterson |first=Randy |date=September 8, 2019 |access-date=October 1, 2019 |newspaper=Des Moines Register}}</ref> According to a 2019 ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' story, \"The Burrow athletic lineage dates back nearly a century.\" In the 1940s, one of his grandmothers set a Mississippi state high school record with an 82-point game in basketball. His paternal grandfather played basketball at [[Mississippi State Bulldogs men's basketball|Mississippi State]]; his uncle, John Burrow, played football at [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Ole Miss]]; and two older brothers also played football at Nebraska.<ref name=\"Dellenger\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.si.com/college-football/2019/07/15/joe-burrow-lsu-sec-media-days |title=Meet Joe Burrow: LSU's Toughest Renaissance Man and Maybe Savior at QB |last=Dellenger |first=Ross |date=July 15, 2019 |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |access-date=July 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe attended the [[2002 Rose Bowl]] at age six, as his father was an assistant coach for Nebraska. Not long after, he began playing in youth football leagues. Unlike his father, uncle, and brothers, who all played on defense, Burrow started out as a quarterback, because his first youth team had no one else who could play the position.<ref name=Dellenger/> The Burrow family moved to [[Fargo, North Dakota]], in 2003 when his father was hired as the defensive coordinator for the [[North Dakota State Bison football|North Dakota State Bison]]. One day while visiting the office, future [[Central Michigan Chippewas football|Central Michigan]] head coach [[Dan Enos]] commented that the seven year old had a future in football.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.inforum.com/bison-media-zone/mens-sports/football/4819431-Kolpack-Heisman-Trophy-favorite-has-roots-with-Bison-football-Fargo-elementary-school |title=Kolpack: Heisman Trophy favorite has roots with Bison football, Fargo elementary school |last=Kolpack |first=Jeff |date=December 12, 2019 |website=INFORUM |language=en |access-date=December 13, 2019}}</ref> The Burrows spent two years in Fargo before Jimmy accepted the defensive coordinator position at [[Ohio Bobcats football|Ohio University]] in [[Athens, Ohio]].\n\nBurrow attended [[Athens High School (Ohio)|Athens High School]] (2011\u201314) in [[The Plains, Ohio]], leading the school to three straight playoff appearances and the school's first seven playoff victories in school history.<ref name=\"lsu bio\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.lsusports.net/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=5200&ATCLID=211716545 |title=Joe Burrow Bio |website=LSUSports.net |publisher=LSU Tigers Athletics |access-date=September 27, 2019}}</ref> During his career, he passed for 11,416 yards with 157 passing [[touchdowns]] and rushed for 2,067 yards with 27 rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_b12cabf8-65e2-11e8-889b-c3de62778f9f.html |title=Ultimate competitor: Joe Burrow's work ethic, storied high school career could bode well for LSU |last=Mickles |first=Sheldon |date=June 1, 2018 |website=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|The Advocate]] |access-date=September 4, 2019}}</ref> He was awarded the state's [[Mr. Football Award (Ohio)|Mr. Football Award]] and Gatorade Player of the Year award as a senior in 2014. He and his Bulldog teammates went 14\u20131 that season. He was also a standout basketball player, and was named first-team all-state at point guard his senior year.<ref name=\"lsu bio\" /> Burrow was rated as a four-star football recruit, and was the eighth-highest ranked [[dual-threat quarterback]] in the class of 2015 according to the [[247Sports]] Composite.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://247sports.com/Player/Joe-Burrow-36575/high-school-60304/ |title=Joe Burrow, Athens, Dual-Threat Quarterback |website=[[247Sports.com]] |access-date=September 10, 2019}}</ref> He committed to [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]] to play football on May 27, 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cleveland.com/osu/2014/05/ohio_state_lands_pledge_from_j.html |title=Ohio State lands pledge from Joe Burrow, 3-star QB from Athens, Ohio: Buckeyes recruiting |last=Lesmerises |first=Doug |date=May 27, 2014 |website=Cleveland.com |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ohio.com/akron/sports/qb-joe-burrow-commits-to-ohio-state |title=QB Joe Burrow commits to Ohio State |date=May 27, 2014 |website=[[Akron Beacon Journal]] |publisher=[[Black Press]] |access-date=September 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, the Athens City School District school board unanimously approved a measure to rename the school's football stadium in honor of Burrow.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_c106d86c-22d0-11ea-8694-8b4408725ff9.html |title=Joe Burrow Stadium: LSU QB's high school to name football stadium after him |date=December 19, 2019 |website=The Advocate |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\n===Ohio State===\nAfter [[Redshirt (college sports)|redshirting]] his first year at Ohio State in 2015, Burrow spent the next two years as a backup to [[J. T. Barrett]]. Over the two years, he played in 10 games, completing 29 of 39 passes for 287 yards and two touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_f20ae018-92e2-11e8-ad16-b749223c17f7.html |title=LSU quarterback competition: The case for Joe Burrow |last=Suss |first=Nick |date=July 28, 2018 |work=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|The Advocate]] |access-date=October 1, 2018}}</ref> Realizing that [[Dwayne Haskins]] would be named starting quarterback at Ohio State, Burrow transferred to [[Louisiana State University]] (LSU) on May 20, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cleveland.com/osu/2018/05/what_the_joe_burrow_transfer_m.html |title=How the Joe Burrow transfer changes Dwayne Haskins: Ohio State football analysis |last=Lesmerises |first=Doug |date=May 9, 2018 |work=[[The Plain Dealer]] |access-date=October 2, 2018 |publisher=[[Advance Publications]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/23542226/quarterback-joe-burrow-transferring-lsu-tigers-ohio-state-buckeyes |title=QB Joe Burrow transferring to LSU for final two seasons |last=Khan Jr. |first=Sam |date=May 19, 2018 |work=[[ESPN]] |access-date=October 1, 2018}}</ref> Burrow had graduated from Ohio State in three years with a degree in consumer and family financial services, and would be immediately eligible as a graduate transfer.<ref name=\"fox starter\" />\n\n===LSU===\n====2018====\n[[File:GA VS LSU E101318 146.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Burrow in 2018]]\n\nIn his first year at LSU, Burrow was named the starting quarterback as a redshirt junior in [[2018 LSU Tigers football team|2018]].<ref name=\"fox starter\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.foxsports.com/college-football/story/ohio-state-transfer-qb-burrow-named-lsu-starter-vs-miami-082718 |title=Ohio State transfer Joe Burrow is LSU\u2019s starting quarterback |date=August 27, 2018 |work=[[Fox Sports]] |access-date=October 1, 2018 |agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> In an early season road trip to then-No. 7 [[2018 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]], Burrow threw for 249 yards and a touchdown en route to a 22\u201321 win. He was named SEC Offensive Player of the Week following the victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lsusports.net/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=5200&ATCLID=211772287 |title=Burrow, Tracy Earn SEC Player of the Week Honors |last=Bonnette |first=Michael |date=September 17, 2018 |website=LSUSports.net |publisher=LSU Athletics |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref> He again earned SEC Offensive Player of the Week honors following a 292-yard, three-touchdown performance against [[2018 Ole Miss Rebels football team|Ole Miss]] two weeks later.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_c7cf9240-c595-11e8-8938-13440efa4717.html |title=LSU quarterback Joe Burrow named SEC Offensive Player of the Week |last=Kubena |first=Brooks |date=October 2, 2018 |location=Baton Rouge, Louisiana |access-date=October 1, 2019 |newspaper=The Advocate}}</ref> Burrow helped lead the Tigers to a 10\u20133 record, including a win over [[2018 UCF Knights football team|UCF]] in the [[2019 Fiesta Bowl (January)|Fiesta Bowl]], and a No. 6 ranking in the final AP Poll. Burrow finished the season with 2,894 yards passing, 16 touchdowns, and five interceptions. He added 399 rushing yards and seven rushing touchdowns.<ref name=\"sports-reference\" />\n\n====2019====\n[[File:LSU Football at the White House (49400533066) (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|150px|Burrow in the [[Oval Office]] following the 2019 season]]\n\nBurrow was again named LSU's starting quarterback heading into his redshirt senior season in [[2019 LSU Tigers football team|2019]]. In the Tigers' season opener against [[2018 Georgia Southern Eagles football team|Georgia Southern]], Burrow threw for 278 yards and five touchdowns in a 55\u20133 win, and was later named SEC Co-Offensive Player of the Week (with [[Tua Tagovailoa]]).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://247sports.com/college/lsu/Article/LSU-Tigers-quarterback-Joe-Burrow-week-one-Georgia-Southern-SEC-Offensive-Player-of-the-Week-135186050/ |title=Joe Burrow grabs SEC Offensive Player of the Week |last=Dixon |first=Shea |date=September 4, 2019 |website=247Sports.com |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref> In a week two road trip to then-No. 9 [[2019 Texas Longhorns football team|Texas]], Burrow threw for 471 yards, four touchdowns, and an interception in the 45\u201338 win. His 471 yards were the second most in school history and most since [[Rohan Davey]]'s 528 against Alabama in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lsusports.net/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=5200&ATCLID=211811103 |title=Burrow, LSU Make History in Victory Over Texas |date=September 7, 2019 |website=LSUSports.net |publisher=LSU Athletics |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref> He was named Walter Camp National Offensive Player of the Week and SEC Offensive Player of the Week following the performance.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tigerdroppings.com/lsu-football/joe-burrow-named-walter-camp-offensive-player-of-the-week/85257656/ |title=Joe Burrow Named Walter Camp Offensive Player Of The Week |date=September 8, 2019 |website=tigerdroppings.com |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref> Burrow earned his third SEC Offensive Player of the Week honors on September 21 during LSU's game against [[2019 Vanderbilt Commodores football team|Vanderbilt]]. He threw for 398 yards and a school-record-setting six passing touchdowns in the Tigers' 66\u201338 win. He became the first LSU quarterback to ever throw for 350 yards in three consecutive games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.secsports.com/article/27684582/football-players-week |title=Week 4: Football Players of the Week |date=September 23, 2019 |website=SECSports.com |publisher=Southeastern Conference |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn a 42\u20136 win over [[2019 Utah State Aggies football team|Utah State]], Burrow threw for 344 yards and five touchdowns, and became the first ever Tiger quarterback to throw for 300-plus yards in four consecutive games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=401110813 |title=Joe Burrow makes history as No. 5 LSU routs Utah State |date=October 5, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 1, 2020 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> The streak came to an end the next week against then-No. 7 [[2019 Florida Gators football team|Florida]], but Burrow's 293 yards and three touchdown passes helped lead the Tigers to another win, 42\u201328.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=401110819 |title=Joe Burrow's 3 TDs lift No. 5 LSU over No. 7 Florida 42-28 |date=October 12, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 1, 2020 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> The next week, in LSU's seventh game of the season, Burrow eclipsed the LSU single-season passing touchdowns record of 28 when he added four more in a win against [[2019 Mississippi State Bulldogs football team|Mississippi State]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=401110828 |title=Joe Burrow throws 4 TDs passes, No. 2 LSU routs MSU 36-13 |date=October 19, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 1, 2020 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Burrow led the Tigers to another top-ten win, and broke the LSU record for career 300-yard games (eight) with a 321-yard, two-total-touchdown performance against then-No. 9 [[2019 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=401110833 |title=Burrow's 321 yards helps No. 2 LSU down No. 9 Auburn, 23-20 |date=October 26, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 1, 2020 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\nLSU's November 9 game against [[2019 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]] was highly anticipated as the highest ranked showdown between the two schools since the [[2012 BCS National Championship Game]]; LSU was ranked second and Alabama third in the season's inaugural [[College Football Playoff]] rankings released the week prior. The game would also feature two leading candidates for the [[Heisman Trophy]] in Burrow and Alabama quarterback [[Tua Tagovailoa]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2672771-alabama-vs-lsu-game-preview-prediction-and-players-to-watch#slide0 |title=Alabama vs. LSU: Game Preview, Prediction and Players to Watch |last=Pedersen |first=Brian |date=October 31, 2019 |website=BleacherReport}}</ref> Burrow and the Tigers came away victorious in a 46\u201341 shootout. Burrow passed for 393 yards and three touchdowns in the game,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=401110842 |title=Joe Burrow leads No. 2 LSU past No. 3 Alabama in 46-41 thriller |date=November 9, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 1, 2020 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> and was again named Walter Camp National Offensive Player of the Week and SEC Co-Offensive Player of the Week, sharing the latter with teammate [[Clyde Edwards-Helaire]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_98c5e424-0426-11ea-81b0-5b10caea9825.html |title=LSU's Joe Burrow named Walter Camp National Offensive Player of the Week |last=Kubena |first=Brooks |date=November 10, 2019 |location=Baton Rouge, LA |newspaper=The Advocate}}</ref>\n\nThe following week against [[2019 Ole Miss Rebels football team|Ole Miss]], Burrow threw for 489 yards and five touchdown passes, and passed LSU's single-season passing yards record set by Rohan Davey in 2001. He also set the LSU record of consecutive completed passes with 17 during the game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=401110850 |title=Burrow throws 5 TDs, No. 1 LSU beats Mississippi 58-37 |date=November 16, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 1, 2020 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> On November 30, Burrow helped LSU secure an undefeated regular season with a 50\u20137 blowout win over [[2019 Texas A&M Aggies football team|Texas A&M]], throwing for 352 yards and three touchdowns. During the game, he set the all-time SEC record for single-season passing yards (previously set by [[Kentucky Wildcats football|Kentucky's]] [[Tim Couch]]), and tied the conference record for single-season touchdowns of [[Missouri Tigers football|Missouri's]] [[Drew Lock]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=401110869 |title=Burrow, No. 1 LSU dominate Texas A&M, 50-7 |date=November 30, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 1, 2020 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Burrow took sole possession of the SEC single-season touchdown record the following week in the [[2019 SEC Championship Game|SEC Championship Game]], throwing for four TDs in LSU's dominant 37\u201310 win over [[2019 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia]] that secured the Tigers' place in the [[College Football Playoff]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=401132981 |title=Burrow completes Heisman coronation, LSU routs Georgia 37-10 |date=December 7, 2019 |access-date=December 7, 2019 |agency=Associated Press |website=ESPN.com}}</ref> \n\n[[File:2020-0113-OrgeronBurrowQueen.PNG|thumb|upright=1.2|left|150px|Burrow (''center'') with LSU head coach [[Ed Orgeron]] (''left'') and linebacker [[Patrick Queen]] (''right'') at LSU's 2020 National Championship post-game press event]]\nOn December 14, 2019, Burrow was awarded the 2019 [[Heisman Trophy]], winning by the largest margin in the history of the award, also earning the highest share of possible points available.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/2019/12/14/lsu-qb-joe-burrow-wins-heisman-trophy/2637969001/ |title=LSU quarterback Joe Burrow wins 2019 Heisman Trophy by record-setting margin |last=Myerberg |first=Paul |date=December 14, 2019 |website=USA Today |access-date=January 1, 2020}}</ref> Burrow's Heisman acceptance speech, in which he referenced the rampant poverty and [[food insecurity]] affecting his hometown, inspired over {{USD}}450,000 in donations towards the local food bank in [[Athens County]] from over 13,000 donors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/12/28/opinions/food-insecurity-joe-burrow-paz/index.html|title=Joe Burrow's Heisman speech is a call to action on food insecurity|last=Paz|first=Harold|date=December 28, 2019|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref> Other awards he won that year include the [[Maxwell Award]], [[Walter Camp Award]], [[Johnny Unitas Golden Arm Award]], [[Davey O'Brien Award]], and [[Manning Award]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Mannings' choice: Joe Burrow wins another award after historic season |url=https://www.wbrz.com/news/mannings-choice-joe-burrow-wins-another-award-after-historic-season/ |website=WBRZ.com |accessdate=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the playoff semifinal game at the [[2019 Peach Bowl]], Burrow recorded 29-of-39 pass attempts for 493 passing yards and seven passing touchdowns (all seven touchdowns in the first half), to go along with five rushes for 22 rushing yards and a rushing touchdown in a 63\u201328 victory over fourth-ranked [[2019 Oklahoma Sooners football team|Oklahoma]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2019-12-28/peach-bowl-joe-burrow-throws-seven-tds-no-1-lsu-routs-no-4-oklahoma |title=Peach Bowl: Joe Burrow throws for seven touchdowns as No. 1 LSU routs No. 4 Oklahoma |date=December 29, 2019 |website=Los Angeles Times |language=en-US |access-date=January 1, 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn the [[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|2020 National Championship Game]] against Clemson, Burrow threw for 463 yards with six total touchdowns, five passing, which led LSU to a 42\u201325 victory and him being named the game's offensive MVP.<ref name=\"2019Records\"/> He finished his 2019 season with 60 passing touchdowns, which broke the single-season [[NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision|FBS]] record previously held by [[Colt Brennan]] in 2006 (58).<ref name=\"2019Records\"/> His 5,671 passing yards ranks third all-time in an FBS season, tied with [[Case Keenum]] (2009).<ref name=\"2019Records\">{{cite web |last1=Kercheval |first1=Ben |title=LSU vs. Clemson: Every record Joe Burrow broke as all-time great season ends with national championship |url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/lsu-vs-clemson-every-record-joe-burrow-broke-as-all-time-great-season-ends-with-national-championship/ |publisher=CBS Sports |accessdate=January 16, 2020 |date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> His [[passer rating]] of 202 for the season was also a record.<ref name=\"2019Records\"/><ref name=\"sports-reference\" /> Several sportswriters deemed the season to be the greatest ever by a college quarterback.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wolken |first1=Dan |title=Opinion: LSU's Joe Burrow completes greatest single season by college QB with national title |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/college/columnist/dan-wolken/2020/01/14/lsu-joe-burrow-beat-clemson-win-college-football-national-title/4458538002/ |accessdate=January 16, 2020 |work=USA Today |date=January 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=LSU captures the national championship as Joe Burrow caps the greatest season ever |url=https://www.foxsports.com/college-football/story/lsu-captures-the-national-championship-as-joe-burrow-caps-the-greatest-season-ever-011420 |publisher=Fox Sports |accessdate=January 16, 2020 |date=January 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kramer |first1=Adam |title=Joe Burrow Caps Greatest Individual Season in CFB History with Title Win |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2871264-joe-burrow-caps-greatest-individual-season-in-cfb-history-with-title-win |publisher=Bleacher Report |accessdate=January 16, 2020 |date=January 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Thamel |first1=Pete |title=How Joe Burrow authored the best season in college football history |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/how-joe-burrow-authored-one-of-the-best-college-football-seasons-in-history-062313307.html |publisher=Yahoo Sports |accessdate=January 16, 2020 |date=January 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Statistics=== \n{| class=\"wikitable\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Legend\n|-\n| style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"|\n| Led the NCAA\n|-\n| style=\"background:#E0CEF2; width:3em;\"|\n| NCAA record\n|-\n| '''Bold'''\n| Career high\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | &nbsp;\n! colspan=\"8\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Passing\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Rushing\n|-\n! Season !! Team !! GP !! Rating !! Att !! Comp !! Pct !! Yds !! TD !! Int !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! TD\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[2015 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2015]] || [[2015 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]] || colspan=\"12\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''Redshirt''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[2016 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2016]] || [[2016 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]]\n| 5 || 169.9 || 28|| 22 || '''78.6''' || 226 