{"title_page": "Dirty Projectors", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{short description|American rock group}}\n{{Lede too short|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Dirty Projectors\n| background          = group_or_band\n| image               = Dirty Projectors 2009.jpg\n| landscape           = yes\n| caption             = Dirty Projectors in 2009\n| origin              = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States\n| genre               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Indie rock]]\n* [[art rock]]<ref>{{cite web\n| url        = http://www.spin.com/2010/07/bjorkdirty-projectors-mount-wittenberg-orca-self-released/\n| title      = Bjork/Dirty Projectors, \u2018Mount Wittenberg Orca\u2019 (Self-Released)\n| website    = [[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]\n| accessdate = August 8, 2016\n}}</ref>\n* [[alternative R&B]]\n* [[indietronica]]\n}}\n| years_active        = 2002\u2013present\n| label               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Domino Recording Company|Domino]]\n* [[Dead Oceans]]\n* [[Marriage Records]]\n* [[Western Vinyl]]\n* [[States Rights Records]]\n}}\n| website             = [http://dirtyprojectors.net/ Dirtyprojectors.net]\n| current_members     = \n* [[David Longstreth]]\n* [[Ava Luna|Felicia Douglass]]\n* [[Bobby (band)|Maia Friedman]]\n* Mike Daniel Johnson\n* Kristin Slipp\n| past_members        = \n* [[Nat Baldwin]]\n* [[Rostam Batmanglij]]\n* [[Jona Bechtolt]]\n* [[Olga Bell]]\n* [[Tyondai Braxton]]\n* Anneli Chambliss\n* Emily Cheeger\n* [[Amber Coffman]]\n* Haley Louise Dekle\n* [[Angel Deradoorian]]\n* [[Jordan Dykstra]]\n* Teresa Eggers\n* Alex Farrill\n* [[Adam Forkner]]\n* Will Glass\n* [[Larkin Grimm]]\n* Clarice Jensen\n* Spencer Kingman\n* [[Ezra Koenig]]\n* [[Jake Longstreth]]\n* [[Charlie Looker]]\n* [[Delicate Steve|Steve Marion]]\n* Brian McOmber\n* Sharon Nakhimovsky\n* Francisco Javier Paredes\n* Jessica Pavone\n* [[Mauro Refosco]]\n* Yasemin Schatz\n* [[Nadia Sirota]]\n* Susanna Waiche\n* [[Jenn Wasner]]\n}}\n{{multiple image\n| direction = vertical\n| width     = 220\n| footer    = Dirty Projectors performing in 2008\n| image1    = Dirty Projectors 2008.05.31 004.jpg\n| alt1      = \n| caption1  = Dave Longstreth\n| image2    = Dirty Projectors 2008.05.31 006.jpg\n| alt2      = \n| caption2  = [[Amber Coffman]]\n}}\n\n'''Dirty Projectors''' is an American [[indie rock]] band from [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], formed in 2002. The band currently consists of primary recording artist and core member [[David Longstreth]] (vocals, guitar), alongside Mike Daniel Johnson (drums), [[Bobby (band)|Maia Friedman]] (guitar, keyboards, backing vocals), [[Ava Luna|Felicia Douglass]] (percussion, keyboards, backing vocals) and Kristin Slipp (keyboards, backing vocals).\n\nSince its formation the band has released eight full-length studio albums, and has had numerous lineup changes, with major contributions from guitarist and vocalist [[Amber Coffman]] from 2006 to 2013.<ref>{{Cite news\n| url          = https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/16/magazine/the-dirty-projectors-go-solo.html\n| title        = The Dirty Projectors Go Solo\n| last         = Weiner\n| first        = Jonah\n| date         = February 16, 2017\n| work         = The New York Times\n| access-date  = May 13, 2017\n| issn         = 0362-4331\n| archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20170420094543/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/16/magazine/the-dirty-projectors-go-solo.html\n| archive-date = April 20, 2017\n| url-status     = live\n}}</ref><ref name=Breakup>{{cite web\n| last1      = Pareles\n| first1     = Jon\n| title      = Dirty Projectors Confronts a Breakup, Emerging With a New Sound\n| url        = https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/22/arts/music/dirty-projectors-self-titled-review.html\n| website    = The New York Times\n| accessdate = March 31, 2017\n| date       = February 22, 2017\n}}</ref> In 2018, the band released its eighth studio album, ''[[Lamp Lit Prose]]''.\n\n== History ==\n=== Early years and ''Rise Above'' (2002\u201307) ===\nWhile studying at [[Yale University|Yale]], Longstreth spent part of the years 2001 and 2002 working on a number of musical ideas, together with his brother [[Jake Longstreth|Jake]].<ref>{{cite web\n| url         = http://pitchfork.com/features/interviews/8883-dirty-projectors\n| title       = Dirty Projectors\n| last        = Stosuy\n| first       = Brandon\n| date        = July 2, 2012\n| website     = Pitchfork\n| access-date = February 7, 2017\n}}</ref> This resulted in the album, ''[[The Graceful Fallen Mango]]'', that was released in 2002 under his own name and introduced his distinctive use of song arrangements and his combination of [[lo-fi music|lo-fi]] and hi-fi production.<ref>{{cite web\n| author     = Heather Phares\n| url        = http://www.allmusic.com/artist/dirty-projectors-mn0000148004/biography\n| title      = Dirty Projectors &#124; Biography\n| publisher  = AllMusic\n| accessdate = May 24, 2014\n}}</ref> With the help of [[Adam Forkner]] of [[Yume Bitsu]], Longstreth recorded and released ''[[The Glad Fact]]'' on the [[Western Vinyl]] label under the name \"The Dirty Projectors\" in 2003. Two years later, the band released ''[[The Getty Address]]'', a concept album about the musician [[Don Henley]] that features extensive orchestral and choral accompaniment. The stripped-down ''[[New Attitude EP]]'' followed in 2006 and featured inklings of the band's later vocal interplay and guitar work.\n\nIn 2007, the band released ''[[Rise Above (Dirty Projectors album)|Rise Above]]'', an album of [[Black Flag (band)|Black Flag]] songs as re-imagined from memory. The album introduced the band's distinctive contrast between Longstreth's vocals and the [[hocket]]ed harmonies of [[Amber Coffman]] and Susanna Waiche, who was later replaced by [[Angel Deradoorian]]. In support of the album, the band performed songs for a Take Away Show acoustic video session shot by [[Vincent Moon]].\n\n=== Domino Records, ''Bitte Orca'', and ''Mount Wittenberg Orca'' (2008\u201311) ===\nIn April 2008, Dirty Projectors signed with [[Domino Recording Company|Domino Records]], and the label announced the release of their fifth full-length album, ''[[Bitte Orca]]'', for June 9, 2009. ''Bitte Orca'' introduced additional backing vocalist/auxiliary percussionist Haley Dekle as a new member and bassist [[Nat Baldwin]] returning to the band (he previously was a member of Dirty Projectors from 2005 to 2006). That year, the band also collaborated with [[David Byrne]] on the song \"Knotty Pine\" for the compilation album ''[[Dark Was the Night (album)|Dark Was the Night]]'' produced by the [[Red Hot Organization]]. Byrne joined the Dirty Projectors onstage to perform this song, along with \"Ambulance Man,\" another collaborative track not included on the compilation, at the \"Dark Was the Night Live\" concert at New York City's Radio City Music Hall on May 3, 2009.\n\n\u201cStillness Is the Move\" was the first single released from ''Bitte Orca'', a [[West African music|West African]] and [[alternative R&B]]-influenced hybrid, sung by Coffman and inspired by the Wim Wenders film ''[[Wings of Desire]]''.<ref>{{cite news\n| url        = https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/07/arts/music/07sisa.html/\n| title      = Report: The Experimental, Led by the Obsessive (New York, NY; 06/03/09)\n| last       = Sisario\n| first      = Ben\n| newspaper  = [[The New York Times]]\n| accessdate = February 12, 2011\n| date       = June 7, 2009\n}}</ref> ''Bitte Orca'' was met with positive reviews,<ref>{{cite web\n| url        = http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/13159-bitte-orca/\n| title      = Dirty Projectors: Bitte Orca &#124; Album Reviews\n| work       = Pitchfork\n| date       = June 9, 2009\n| accessdate = May 24, 2014\n}}</ref> including Rolling Stone magazine rating the album as number 6 on their best 25 albums of 2009.<ref>{{cite web\n| url        = http://www.albumoftheyear.org/list/17-rolling-stones-25-best-albums-of-2009.php\n| title      = Rolling Stone's 25 Best Albums of 2009\n| publisher  = Albumoftheyear.org\n| accessdate = May 24, 2014\n}}</ref>\n\nDirty Projectors were to release a new EP in September 2009 titled ''Temecula Sunrise.''<ref>{{cite web\n| last        = Lindsay\n| first       = Andrew\n| url         = http://stereokill.net/2009/08/17/dirty-projectors-to-release-new-ep/\n| title       = Dirty Projectors to release new EP\n| publisher   = stereokill.net\n| date        = August 17, 2009\n| accessdate  = June 7, 2012\n| url-status     = dead\n| archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090921160510/http://stereokill.net/2009/08/17/dirty-projectors-to-release-new-ep/\n| archivedate = September 21, 2009\n}}</ref> While the EP was never released, two of its tracks, \"Ascending Melody\" and \"Emblem of the World\", were instead offered for free download on the Dirty Projectors website in early 2010.<ref>[http://pitchfork.com/news/37535-dirty-projects-release-free-digital-single/] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114151132/http://pitchfork.com/news/37535-dirty-projects-release-free-digital-single/ |date=January 14, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nOn May 8, 2009, members of Dirty Projectors collaborated with [[Bj\u00f6rk]] to perform an original composition by Longstreth, written for five voices and acoustic guitar, as part of a charity concert to benefit [[Housing Works]], a nonprofit organization dedicated to providing shelter for homeless men, women, and children suffering from AIDS. The concert was held at the Housing Works Bookstore & Caf\u00e9 in downtown New York City.<ref>{{cite web\n| url        = http://pitchfork.com/news/35294-report-bjork-and-dirty-projectors-new-york-ny-050809/\n| title      = Report: Bj\u00f6rk and Dirty Projectors (New York, NY; 05/08/09) \u2013 The avant-pop acts combine forces in a NYC bookstore.\n| last       = Dombal\n| first      = Ryan\n| accessdate = May 11, 2009\n}}</ref> On June 30, 2010, Dirty Projectors announced the release of ''[[Mount Wittenberg Orca]]'', a digital-only [[extended play|EP]] with Bj\u00f6rk based on the artists' collaboration.<ref>[http://pitchfork.com/news/39240-bjork-and-dirty-projectors-to-release-collaboration-imount-wittenberg-orcai/] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110303150045/http://pitchfork.com/news/39240-bjork-and-dirty-projectors-to-release-collaboration-imount-wittenberg-orcai/ |date=March 3, 2011 }}</ref> ''Mount Wittenberg Orca'' was released physically by Domino Records in 2011.\n\n=== ''Swing Lo Magellan'' (2012\u20132015) ===\nOn March 30, 2012, Dirty Projectors released the first single from their sixth album, ''[[Swing Lo Magellan]]'', \"Gun Has No Trigger\". The album was released on July 10 in the United States and on July 9 internationally.<ref>{{cite web\n| last       = Battan\n| first      = Carrie\n| url        = http://pitchfork.com/news/45984-listen-to-a-new-dirty-projectors-song-gun-has-no-trigger/\n| title      = Listen to a New Dirty Projectors Song, \"Gun Has No Trigger\"\n| work       = Pitchfork\n| date       = March 30, 2012\n| accessdate = June 7, 2012\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n| url        = http://pitchfork.com/news/45992-dirty-projectors-announce-new-album/\n| title      = Dirty Projectors Announce New Album\n| work       = Pitchfork\n| date       = April 2, 2012\n| accessdate = June 7, 2012\n}}</ref>\n\nOn September 7, 2012, Dirty Projectors released a short film, directed by Longstreth, called \"Hi Custodian\".<ref>{{cite web\n| url        = http://www.stillinrock.com/2012/09/video-dirty-projectors-hi-custodian.html\n| title      = Brooklyn based Music Blog: Video : Dirty Projectors \u2013 Hi Custodian (Experimental Pop Folk)\n| publisher  = Still in Rock\n| date       = February 26, 2004\n| accessdate = May 24, 2014\n}}</ref>\n\nOn November 6, 2012, Dirty Projectors released ''[[About to Die EP]]'', a digital- and vinyl-release EP featuring several new tracks.<ref>{{cite web\n| url        = http://pitchfork.com/news/47900-dirty-projectors-share-about-to-die-video-announce-new-ep-with-new-tracks\n| title      = Dirty Projectors Share 'About to Die' Video, Announce New EP With New Tracks\n| work       = Pitchfork\n| date       = September 20, 2012\n| accessdate = May 24, 2014\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, members of Dirty Projectors made a cameo appearance as themselves in the [[Noah Baumbach]] film ''[[Mistress America]]''.\n\n=== ''Dirty Projectors'' (2016\u20132018) ===\nOn September 19, 2016, Dirty Projectors began releasing videos and images on social media teasing new music.<ref>{{cite web\n| url        = http://pitchfork.com/news/68402-dirty-projectors-tease-new-music-watch/\n| title      = Dirty Projectors Tease New Music: Watch\n| work       = Pitchfork\n| date       = September 19, 2016\n| accessdate = March 3, 2017\n}}</ref> After the release of tracks \"Keep Your Name\", \"Little Bubble\" and \"Up in Hudson\", it was announced that the seventh, [[Dirty Projectors (album)|self-titled album]], would be released on February 24, 2017 via Domino. The album was ultimately released three days early, on February 21, 2017. It marked a return to the group's solo roots for Longstreth (who at this point relocated to [[Los Angeles]], [[California]] to build a recording studio called \"[[Ivo Shandor]]\"), introduced a more [[electronica|electronic-based]] [[alternative R&B]] sound, and addressed his breakup with Coffman, his former bandmate and girlfriend.<ref name=Breakup />\n\n=== ''Lamp Lit Prose'' (2018) ===\nOn July 13, 2018, Dirty Projectors released their eighth album, ''[[Lamp Lit Prose]]'', after teasing three singles, \"Break Thru\", \"That's a Lifestyle\", and \"I Feel Energy\". This album marked the revival of Dirty Projectors as a group project, with David Longstreth on lead vocals and guitar; returning members Nat Baldwin and Mike Daniel Johnson on bass/bass synth and drums, respectively; and introducing Maia Friedman on guitar, keyboards, and backing vocals, Felicia Douglass on percussion, keyboards, and backing vocals, and Kristin Slipp on keyboards and backing vocals.\n\n=== ''Windows Open'' (2020) ===\nOn March 27, 2020, Dirty Projectors released a new EP titled ''Windows Open''. The EP featured lead vocals and writing from Friedman with writing, production, and mixing handled by Longstreth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/dirty-projectors-announce-new-window-opens-ep-share-new-song-search-for-life-listen/|title=Dirty Projectors Announce New Windows Open EP, Share New Song \u201cSearch for Life\u201d|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\nOliver Hill from [[Vagabon]] added string arrangements to the album. <ref>https://www.dominomusic.com/news/us/dirty-projectors-announce-windows-open-new-ep-out-march-27</ref>\n\n== Musical style ==\nWhile often associated with the late 2000s New York indie rock scene, critics have linked Dirty Projectors to musicians from many genres, including [[New wave music|new wave]] artists [[David Byrne]] and [[Squeeze (band)|Squeeze]], pop stars [[Beyonc\u00e9]] and [[Mariah Carey]], and [[progressive rock]] musicians [[Frank Zappa]] and [[Yes (band)|Yes]].<ref name=\"AV Club\">{{cite web\n| last       = O'Neal\n| first      = Sean\n| url        = http://www.avclub.com/article/dirty-projectors-david-longstreth-doesnt-think-the-35143/\n| title      = Dirty Projectors' David Longstreth doesn't think they sound like that\n| publisher  = The A.V. Club\n| date       = November 10, 2009\n| accessdate = June 7, 2012\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| url       = https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/07/arts/music/07sisa.html?pagewanted=all\n| newspaper = [[The New York Times]]\n| first     = Ben\n| last      = Sisario\n| title     = The Experimental, Led by the Obsessive\n| date      = June 7, 2009\n}}</ref> In a 2009 interview, Longstreth embraced some of these comparisons but expressed a dislike for several of those musicians, commenting, \"[[Steely Dan]] is a band I\u2019m not that into,\" \"I\u2019m not a huge [[Yes (band)|Yes]] guy,\" and \"[[Frank Zappa]] I fucking hate.\"<ref name=\"AV Club\" />\n\n== Members ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''Current members'''\n* [[David Longstreth]] \u2013 lead vocals, guitar, various instruments <small>(2002\u2013present)</small>\n* Mike Daniel Johnson \u2013 drums <small>(2012\u20132013; 2017\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Bobby (band)|Maia Friedman]] \u2013 guitar, keyboards, lead and backing vocals <small>(2018\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Ava Luna|Felicia Douglass]] \u2013 percussion, keyboards, lead and backing vocals <small>(2018\u2013present)</small>\n* Kristin Slipp \u2013 keyboards, lead and backing vocals <small>(2018\u2013present)</small>\n\n{{col-2}}\n'''Former members'''\n* [[Nat Baldwin]] \u2013 bass, keyboards <small>(2005\u20132006; 2007\u20132013; 2016; 2017; 2018\u20132019)</small>\n* [[Olga Bell]] \u2013 keyboards, backing vocals <small>(2011\u20132013; 2017)</small>\n* [[Tyondai Braxton]] \u2013 keyboards <small>(2017)</small>\n* [[Mauro Refosco]] \u2013 percussion <small>(2017)</small>\n* Francisco Javier Paredes \u2013 percussion <small>(2017)</small>\n* [[Amber Coffman]] \u2013 co-lead and backing vocals, guitar <small>(2006\u20132013)</small>\n* Haley Louise Dekle \u2013 percussion, backing vocals <small>(2008\u20132013)</small>\n* [[Delicate Steve|Steve Marion]] \u2013 guitar, backing vocals <small>(2013)</small>\n* [[Jenn Wasner]] \u2013 guitar, backing vocals <small>(2012)</small>\n* Brian McOmber \u2013 drums <small>(2006\u20132012)</small>\n* [[Angel Deradoorian]] \u2013 co-lead and backing vocals, guitar, keyboards, bass <small>(2007\u20132012; 2013)</small>\n* [[Jordan Dykstra]] \u2013 viola <small>(2008\u20132009)</small>\n* Sharon Nakhimovsky \u2013 violin <small>(2007)</small>\n* [[Charlie Looker]] \u2013 guitar, backing vocals <small>(2005\u20132006)</small>\n* Susanna Waiche \u2013 backing vocals <small>(2006)</small>\n* [[Adam Forkner]] \u2013 drums <small>(2002\u20132005)</small>\n* [[Ezra Koenig]] \u2013 saxophone, guitar, backing vocals <small>(2004\u20132005; 2016)</small>\n* [[Rostam Batmanglij]] \u2013 clarinet, keyboards, backing vocals <small>(2004\u20132005)</small>\n* [[Larkin Grimm]] \u2013 backing vocals <small>(2004\u20132005)</small>\n* Spencer Kingman \u2013 guitar, backing vocals <small>(2005\u20132006)</small>\n* Anneli Chambliss \u2013 backing vocals <small>(2005)</small>\n* Emily Cheeger \u2013 backing vocals <small>(2005)</small>\n* Yasemin Schatz \u2013 flute <small>(2004)</small>\n* Teresa Eggers \u2013 backing vocals <small>(2017)</small>\n* Alex Farrill \u2013 keyboards, drums, backing vocals <small>(2005)</small>\n* Clarice Jensen \u2013 viola <small>(2012; 2017)</small>\n* Will Glass \u2013 drums <small>(2005\u20132006)</small>\n* [[Jona Bechtolt]] \u2013 keyboards, drums <small>(2004\u20132005)</small>\n* Jessica Pavone \u2013 viola <small>(2007)</small>\n* [[Nadia Sirota]] \u2013 viola <small>(2012; 2017)</small>\n* [[Jake Longstreth]] \u2013 backing vocals <small>(2002; 2016)</small>\n{{col-end}}\n\n== Discography ==\n=== Studio albums ===\n* ''[[The Glad Fact]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Morning Better Last!]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Slaves' Graves and Ballads]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[The Getty Address]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Rise Above (Dirty Projectors album)|Rise Above]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Bitte Orca]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Swing Lo Magellan]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Dirty Projectors (album)|Dirty Projectors]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Lamp Lit Prose]]'' (2018)\n\n=== EPs ===\n* ''[[New Attitude EP|New Attitude]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Mount Wittenberg Orca]]'' (2010) <small>(with [[Bj\u00f6rk]])</small>\n* ''[[About to Die]]'' (2012)\n* ''Windows Open'' (2020)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/dirty-projectors-announce-new-window-opens-ep-share-new-song-search-for-life-listen/|title=Dirty Projectors Announce New ''Windows Open'' EP, Share New Song \"Search for Life\": Listen|website=Pitchfork|last=Minsker|first=Evan|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{official website|http://dirtyprojectors.net/}}\n* [http://www.dominorecordco.com/artists/dirty-projectors/ Dirty Projectors Domino Records page]\n* [http://www.westernvinyl.com/dirty_projectors.htm Dirty Projectors Western Vinyl page]\n* {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p601780/biography}}\n* [https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=15735067 Dirty Projectors in concert on NPR Music]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091010192614/http://www.beyondrace.com/inside/latestissue/1432-dirty-projectors Dirty Projectors] on [http://beyondrace.com/ ''Beyond Race Magazine'' (''BRM'')]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130207081054/http://www.deadoceans.com/artist.php?name=dirtyprojectors Dead Oceans Page]\n* [http://core.thomaslaupstad.com/rob-da-bank-2010-07-10-with-dirty-projectors-bjork/ Dirty Projectors & Bj\u00f6rk on the Rob da Bank show]\n\n{{Dirty Projectors}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Indie rock musical groups from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2002]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:2002 establishments in New York City]]\n[[Category:Domino Recording Company artists]]\n[[Category:Dead Oceans artists]]\n[[Category:Western Vinyl artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{short description|American rock group}}\n{{Lede too short|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Dirty Projectors\n| background          = group_or_band\n| image               = Dirty Projectors 2009.jpg\n| landscape           = yes\n| caption             = Dirty Projectors in 2009\n| origin              = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States\n| genre               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Indie rock]]\n* [[art rock]]<ref>{{cite web\n| url        = http://www.spin.com/2010/07/bjorkdirty-projectors-mount-wittenberg-orca-self-released/\n| title      = Bjork/Dirty Projectors, \u2018Mount Wittenberg Orca\u2019 (Self-Released)\n| website    = [[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]\n| accessdate = August 8, 2016\n}}</ref>\n* [[alternative R&B]]\n* [[indietronica]]\n}}\n| years_active        = 2002\u2013present\n| label               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Domino Recording Company|Domino]]\n* [[Dead Oceans]]\n* [[Marriage Records]]\n* [[Western Vinyl]]\n* [[States Rights Records]]\n}}\n| website             = [http://dirtyprojectors.net/ Dirtyprojectors.net]\n| current_members     = \n* [[David Longstreth]]\n* [[Ava Luna|Felicia Douglass]]\n* [[Bobby (band)|Maia Friedman]]\n* Mike Daniel Johnson\n* Kristin Slipp\n| past_members        = \n* [[Nat Baldwin]]\n* [[Rostam Batmanglij]]\n* [[Jona Bechtolt]]\n* [[Olga Bell]]\n* [[Tyondai Braxton]]\n* Anneli Chambliss\n* Emily Cheeger\n* [[Amber Coffman]]\n* Haley Louise Dekle\n* [[Angel Deradoorian]]\n* [[Jordan Dykstra]]\n* Teresa Eggers\n* Alex Farrill\n* [[Adam Forkner]]\n* Will Glass\n* [[Larkin Grimm]]\n* Clarice Jensen\n* Spencer Kingman\n* [[Ezra Koenig]]\n* [[Jake Longstreth]]\n* [[Charlie Looker]]\n* [[Delicate Steve|Steve Marion]]\n* Brian McOmber\n* Sharon Nakhimovsky\n* Francisco Javier Paredes\n* Jessica Pavone\n* [[Mauro Refosco]]\n* Yasemin Schatz\n* [[Nadia Sirota]]\n* Susanna Waiche\n* [[Jenn Wasner]]\n}}\n{{multiple image\n| direction = vertical\n| width     = 220\n| footer    = Dirty Projectors performing in 2008\n| image1    = Dirty Projectors 2008.05.31 004.jpg\n| alt1      = \n| caption1  = Dave Longstreth\n| image2    = Dirty Projectors 2008.05.31 006.jpg\n| alt2      = \n| caption2  = [[Amber Coffman]]\n}}\n\n'''Dirty Projectors''' is an American [[indie rock]] band from [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], formed in 2002. The band currently consists of primary recording artist and core member [[David Longstreth]] (vocals, guitar), alongside Mike Daniel Johnson (drums), [[Bobby (band)|Maia Friedman]] (guitar, keyboards, backing vocals), [[Ava Luna|Felicia Douglass]] (percussion, keyboards, backing vocals) and Kristin Slipp (keyboards, backing vocals).\n\nSince its formation the band has released eight full-length studio albums, and has had numerous lineup changes, with major contributions from guitarist and vocalist [[Amber Coffman]] from 2006 to 2013.<ref>{{Cite news\n| url          = https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/16/magazine/the-dirty-projectors-go-solo.html\n| title        = The Dirty Projectors Go Solo\n| last         = Weiner\n| first        = Jonah\n| date         = February 16, 2017\n| work         = The New York Times\n| access-date  = May 13, 2017\n| issn         = 0362-4331\n| archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20170420094543/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/16/magazine/the-dirty-projectors-go-solo.html\n| archive-date = April 20, 2017\n| url-status     = live\n}}</ref><ref name=Breakup>{{cite web\n| last1      = Pareles\n| first1     = Jon\n| title      = Dirty Projectors Confronts a Breakup, Emerging With a New Sound\n| url        = https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/22/arts/music/dirty-projectors-self-titled-review.html\n| website    = The New York Times\n| accessdate = March 31, 2017\n| date       = February 22, 2017\n}}</ref> In 2018, the band released its eighth studio album, ''[[Lamp Lit Prose]]''.\n\n== History ==\n=== Early years and ''Rise Above'' (2002\u201307) ===\nWhile studying at [[Yale University|Yale]], Longstreth spent part of the years 2001 and 2002 working on a number of musical ideas, together with his brother [[Jake Longstreth|Jake]].<ref>{{cite web\n| url         = http://pitchfork.com/features/interviews/8883-dirty-projectors\n| title       = Dirty Projectors\n| last        = Stosuy\n| first       = Brandon\n| date        = July 2, 2012\n| website     = Pitchfork\n| access-date = February 7, 2017\n}}</ref> This resulted in the album, ''[[The Graceful Fallen Mango]]'', that was released in 2002 under his own name and introduced his distinctive use of song arrangements and his combination of [[lo-fi music|lo-fi]] and hi-fi production.<ref>{{cite web\n| author     = Heather Phares\n| url        = http://www.allmusic.com/artist/dirty-projectors-mn0000148004/biography\n| title      = Dirty Projectors &#124; Biography\n| publisher  = AllMusic\n| accessdate = May 24, 2014\n}}</ref> With the help of [[Adam Forkner]] of [[Yume Bitsu]], Longstreth recorded and released ''[[The Glad Fact]]'' on the [[Western Vinyl]] label under the name \"The Dirty Projectors\" in 2003. Two years later, the band released ''[[The Getty Address]]'', a concept album about the musician [[Don Henley]] that features extensive orchestral and choral accompaniment. The stripped-down ''[[New Attitude EP]]'' followed in 2006 and featured inklings of the band's later vocal interplay and guitar work.\n\nIn 2007, the band released ''[[Rise Above (Dirty Projectors album)|Rise Above]]'', an album of [[Black Flag (band)|Black Flag]] songs as re-imagined from memory. The album introduced the band's distinctive contrast between Longstreth's vocals and the [[hocket]]ed harmonies of [[Amber Coffman]] and Susanna Waiche, who was later replaced by [[Angel Deradoorian]]. In support of the album, the band performed songs for a Take Away Show acoustic video session shot by [[Vincent Moon]].\n\n=== Domino Records, ''Bitte Orca'', and ''Mount Wittenberg Orca'' (2008\u201311) ===\nIn April 2008, Dirty Projectors signed with [[Domino Recording Company|Domino Records]], and the label announced the release of their fifth full-length album, ''[[Bitte Orca]]'', for June 9, 2009. ''Bitte Orca'' introduced additional backing vocalist/auxiliary percussionist Haley Dekle as a new member and bassist [[Nat Baldwin]] returning to the band (he previously was a member of Dirty Projectors from 2005 to 2006). That year, the band also collaborated with [[David Byrne]] on the song \"Knotty Pine\" for the compilation album ''[[Dark Was the Night (album)|Dark Was the Night]]'' produced by the [[Red Hot Organization]]. Byrne joined the Dirty Projectors onstage to perform this song, along with \"Ambulance Man,\" another collaborative track not included on the compilation, at the \"Dark Was the Night Live\" concert at New York City's Radio City Music Hall on May 3, 2009.\n\n\u201cStillness Is the Move\" was the first single released from ''Bitte Orca'', a [[West African music|West African]] and [[alternative R&B]]-influenced hybrid, sung by Coffman and inspired by the Wim Wenders film ''[[Wings of Desire]]''.<ref>{{cite news\n| url        = https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/07/arts/music/07sisa.html/\n| title      = Report: The Experimental, Led by the Obsessive (New York, NY; 06/03/09)\n| last       = Sisario\n| first      = Ben\n| newspaper  = [[The New York Times]]\n| accessdate = February 12, 2011\n| date       = June 7, 2009\n}}</ref> ''Bitte Orca'' was met with positive reviews,<ref>{{cite web\n| url        = http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/13159-bitte-orca/\n| title      = Dirty Projectors: Bitte Orca &#124; Album Reviews\n| work       = Pitchfork\n| date       = June 9, 2009\n| accessdate = May 24, 2014\n}}</ref> including Rolling Stone magazine rating the album as number 6 on their best 25 albums of 2009.<ref>{{cite web\n| url        = http://www.albumoftheyear.org/list/17-rolling-stones-25-best-albums-of-2009.php\n| title      = Rolling Stone's 25 Best Albums of 2009\n| publisher  = Albumoftheyear.org\n| accessdate = May 24, 2014\n}}</ref>\n\nDirty Projectors were to release a new EP in September 2009 titled ''Temecula Sunrise.''<ref>{{cite web\n| last        = Lindsay\n| first       = Andrew\n| url         = http://stereokill.net/2009/08/17/dirty-projectors-to-release-new-ep/\n| title       = Dirty Projectors to release new EP\n| publisher   = stereokill.net\n| date        = August 17, 2009\n| accessdate  = June 7, 2012\n| url-status     = dead\n| archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090921160510/http://stereokill.net/2009/08/17/dirty-projectors-to-release-new-ep/\n| archivedate = September 21, 2009\n}}</ref> While the EP was never released, two of its tracks, \"Ascending Melody\" and \"Emblem of the World\", were instead offered for free download on the Dirty Projectors website in early 2010.<ref>[http://pitchfork.com/news/37535-dirty-projects-release-free-digital-single/] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114151132/http://pitchfork.com/news/37535-dirty-projects-release-free-digital-single/ |date=January 14, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nOn May 8, 2009, members of Dirty Projectors collaborated with [[Bj\u00f6rk]] to perform an original composition by Longstreth, written for five voices and acoustic guitar, as part of a charity concert to benefit [[Housing Works]], a nonprofit organization dedicated to providing shelter for homeless men, women, and children suffering from AIDS. The concert was held at the Housing Works Bookstore & Caf\u00e9 in downtown New York City.<ref>{{cite web\n| url        = http://pitchfork.com/news/35294-report-bjork-and-dirty-projectors-new-york-ny-050809/\n| title      = Report: Bj\u00f6rk and Dirty Projectors (New York, NY; 05/08/09) \u2013 The avant-pop acts combine forces in a NYC bookstore.\n| last       = Dombal\n| first      = Ryan\n| accessdate = May 11, 2009\n}}</ref> On June 30, 2010, Dirty Projectors announced the release of ''[[Mount Wittenberg Orca]]'', a digital-only [[extended play|EP]] with Bj\u00f6rk based on the artists' collaboration.<ref>[http://pitchfork.com/news/39240-bjork-and-dirty-projectors-to-release-collaboration-imount-wittenberg-orcai/] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110303150045/http://pitchfork.com/news/39240-bjork-and-dirty-projectors-to-release-collaboration-imount-wittenberg-orcai/ |date=March 3, 2011 }}</ref> ''Mount Wittenberg Orca'' was released physically by Domino Records in 2011.\n\n=== ''Swing Lo Magellan'' (2012\u20132015) ===\nOn March 30, 2012, Dirty Projectors released the first single from their sixth album, ''[[Swing Lo Magellan]]'', \"Gun Has No Trigger\". The album was released on July 10 in the United States and on July 9 internationally.<ref>{{cite web\n| last       = Battan\n| first      = Carrie\n| url        = http://pitchfork.com/news/45984-listen-to-a-new-dirty-projectors-song-gun-has-no-trigger/\n| title      = Listen to a New Dirty Projectors Song, \"Gun Has No Trigger\"\n| work       = Pitchfork\n| date       = March 30, 2012\n| accessdate = June 7, 2012\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n| url        = http://pitchfork.com/news/45992-dirty-projectors-announce-new-album/\n| title      = Dirty Projectors Announce New Album\n| work       = Pitchfork\n| date       = April 2, 2012\n| accessdate = June 7, 2012\n}}</ref>\n\nOn September 7, 2012, Dirty Projectors released a short film, directed by Longstreth, called \"Hi Custodian\".<ref>{{cite web\n| url        = http://www.stillinrock.com/2012/09/video-dirty-projectors-hi-custodian.html\n| title      = Brooklyn based Music Blog: Video : Dirty Projectors \u2013 Hi Custodian (Experimental Pop Folk)\n| publisher  = Still in Rock\n| date       = February 26, 2004\n| accessdate = May 24, 2014\n}}</ref>\n\nOn November 6, 2012, Dirty Projectors released ''[[About to Die EP]]'', a digital- and vinyl-release EP featuring several new tracks.<ref>{{cite web\n| url        = http://pitchfork.com/news/47900-dirty-projectors-share-about-to-die-video-announce-new-ep-with-new-tracks\n| title      = Dirty Projectors Share 'About to Die' Video, Announce New EP With New Tracks\n| work       = Pitchfork\n| date       = September 20, 2012\n| accessdate = May 24, 2014\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, members of Dirty Projectors made a cameo appearance as themselves in the [[Noah Baumbach]] film ''[[Mistress America]]''.\n\n=== ''Dirty Projectors'' (2016\u20132018) ===\nOn September 19, 2016, Dirty Projectors began releasing videos and images on social media teasing new music.<ref>{{cite web\n| url        = http://pitchfork.com/news/68402-dirty-projectors-tease-new-music-watch/\n| title      = Dirty Projectors Tease New Music: Watch\n| work       = Pitchfork\n| date       = September 19, 2016\n| accessdate = March 3, 2017\n}}</ref> After the release of tracks \"Keep Your Name\", \"Little Bubble\" and \"Up in Hudson\", it was announced that the seventh, [[Dirty Projectors (album)|self-titled album]], would be released on February 24, 2017 via Domino. The album was ultimately released three days early, on February 21, 2017. It marked a return to the group's solo roots for Longstreth (who at this point relocated to [[Los Angeles]], [[California]] to build a recording studio called \"[[Ivo Shandor]]\"), introduced a more [[electronica|electronic-based]] [[alternative R&B]] sound, and addressed his breakup with Coffman, his former bandmate and girlfriend.<ref name=Breakup />\n\n=== ''Lamp Lit Prose'' (2018) ===\nOn July 13, 2018, Dirty Projectors released their eighth album, ''[[Lamp Lit Prose]]'', after teasing three singles, \"Break Thru\", \"That's a Lifestyle\", and \"I Feel Energy\". This album marked the revival of Dirty Projectors as a group project, with David Longstreth on lead vocals and guitar; returning members Nat Baldwin and Mike Daniel Johnson on bass/bass synth and drums, respectively; and introducing Maia Friedman on guitar, keyboards, and backing vocals, Felicia Douglass on percussion, keyboards, and backing vocals, and Kristin Slipp on keyboards and backing vocals.\n\n=== ''Windows Open'' (2020) ===\nOn March 27, 2020, Dirty Projectors released a new EP titled ''Windows Open''. The EP featured lead vocals and writing from Friedman with writing, production, and mixing handled by Longstreth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/dirty-projectors-announce-new-window-opens-ep-share-new-song-search-for-life-listen/|title=Dirty Projectors Announce New Windows Open EP, Share New Song \u201cSearch for Life\u201d|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n[[Oliver Hill]] from [[Vagabon]] added string arrangements to the album. <ref>https://www.dominomusic.com/news/us/dirty-projectors-announce-windows-open-new-ep-out-march-27</ref>\n\n== Musical style ==\nWhile often associated with the late 2000s New York indie rock scene, critics have linked Dirty Projectors to musicians from many genres, including [[New wave music|new wave]] artists [[David Byrne]] and [[Squeeze (band)|Squeeze]], pop stars [[Beyonc\u00e9]] and [[Mariah Carey]], and [[progressive rock]] musicians [[Frank Zappa]] and [[Yes (band)|Yes]].<ref name=\"AV Club\">{{cite web\n| last       = O'Neal\n| first      = Sean\n| url        = http://www.avclub.com/article/dirty-projectors-david-longstreth-doesnt-think-the-35143/\n| title      = Dirty Projectors' David Longstreth doesn't think they sound like that\n| publisher  = The A.V. Club\n| date       = November 10, 2009\n| accessdate = June 7, 2012\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| url       = https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/07/arts/music/07sisa.html?pagewanted=all\n| newspaper = [[The New York Times]]\n| first     = Ben\n| last      = Sisario\n| title     = The Experimental, Led by the Obsessive\n| date      = June 7, 2009\n}}</ref> In a 2009 interview, Longstreth embraced some of these comparisons but expressed a dislike for several of those musicians, commenting, \"[[Steely Dan]] is a band I\u2019m not that into,\" \"I\u2019m not a huge [[Yes (band)|Yes]] guy,\" and \"[[Frank Zappa]] I fucking hate.\"<ref name=\"AV Club\" />\n\n== Members ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''Current members'''\n* [[David Longstreth]] \u2013 lead vocals, guitar, various instruments <small>(2002\u2013present)</small>\n* Mike Daniel Johnson \u2013 drums <small>(2012\u20132013; 2017\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Bobby (band)|Maia Friedman]] \u2013 guitar, keyboards, lead and backing vocals <small>(2018\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Ava Luna|Felicia Douglass]] \u2013 percussion, keyboards, lead and backing vocals <small>(2018\u2013present)</small>\n* Kristin Slipp \u2013 keyboards, lead and backing vocals <small>(2018\u2013present)</small>\n\n{{col-2}}\n'''Former members'''\n* [[Nat Baldwin]] \u2013 bass, keyboards <small>(2005\u20132006; 2007\u20132013; 2016; 2017; 2018\u20132019)</small>\n* [[Olga Bell]] \u2013 keyboards, backing vocals <small>(2011\u20132013; 2017)</small>\n* [[Tyondai Braxton]] \u2013 keyboards <small>(2017)</small>\n* [[Mauro Refosco]] \u2013 percussion <small>(2017)</small>\n* Francisco Javier Paredes \u2013 percussion <small>(2017)</small>\n* [[Amber Coffman]] \u2013 co-lead and backing vocals, guitar <small>(2006\u20132013)</small>\n* Haley Louise Dekle \u2013 percussion, backing vocals <small>(2008\u20132013)</small>\n* [[Delicate Steve|Steve Marion]] \u2013 guitar, backing vocals <small>(2013)</small>\n* [[Jenn Wasner]] \u2013 guitar, backing vocals <small>(2012)</small>\n* Brian McOmber \u2013 drums <small>(2006\u20132012)</small>\n* [[Angel Deradoorian]] \u2013 co-lead and backing vocals, guitar, keyboards, bass <small>(2007\u20132012; 2013)</small>\n* [[Jordan Dykstra]] \u2013 viola <small>(2008\u20132009)</small>\n* Sharon Nakhimovsky \u2013 violin <small>(2007)</small>\n* [[Charlie Looker]] \u2013 guitar, backing vocals <small>(2005\u20132006)</small>\n* Susanna Waiche \u2013 backing vocals <small>(2006)</small>\n* [[Adam Forkner]] \u2013 drums <small>(2002\u20132005)</small>\n* [[Ezra Koenig]] \u2013 saxophone, guitar, backing vocals <small>(2004\u20132005; 2016)</small>\n* [[Rostam Batmanglij]] \u2013 clarinet, keyboards, backing vocals <small>(2004\u20132005)</small>\n* [[Larkin Grimm]] \u2013 backing vocals <small>(2004\u20132005)</small>\n* Spencer Kingman \u2013 guitar, backing vocals <small>(2005\u20132006)</small>\n* Anneli Chambliss \u2013 backing vocals <small>(2005)</small>\n* Emily Cheeger \u2013 backing vocals <small>(2005)</small>\n* Yasemin Schatz \u2013 flute <small>(2004)</small>\n* Teresa Eggers \u2013 backing vocals <small>(2017)</small>\n* Alex Farrill \u2013 keyboards, drums, backing vocals <small>(2005)</small>\n* Clarice Jensen \u2013 viola <small>(2012; 2017)</small>\n* Will Glass \u2013 drums <small>(2005\u20132006)</small>\n* [[Jona Bechtolt]] \u2013 keyboards, drums <small>(2004\u20132005)</small>\n* Jessica Pavone \u2013 viola <small>(2007)</small>\n* [[Nadia Sirota]] \u2013 viola <small>(2012; 2017)</small>\n* [[Jake Longstreth]] \u2013 backing vocals <small>(2002; 2016)</small>\n{{col-end}}\n\n== Discography ==\n=== Studio albums ===\n* ''[[The Glad Fact]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Morning Better Last!]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Slaves' Graves and Ballads]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[The Getty Address]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Rise Above (Dirty Projectors album)|Rise Above]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Bitte Orca]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Swing Lo Magellan]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Dirty Projectors (album)|Dirty Projectors]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Lamp Lit Prose]]'' (2018)\n\n=== EPs ===\n* ''[[New Attitude EP|New Attitude]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Mount Wittenberg Orca]]'' (2010) <small>(with [[Bj\u00f6rk]])</small>\n* ''[[About to Die]]'' (2012)\n* ''Windows Open'' (2020)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/dirty-projectors-announce-new-window-opens-ep-share-new-song-search-for-life-listen/|title=Dirty Projectors Announce New ''Windows Open'' EP, Share New Song \"Search for Life\": Listen|website=Pitchfork|last=Minsker|first=Evan|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{official website|http://dirtyprojectors.net/}}\n* [http://www.dominorecordco.com/artists/dirty-projectors/ Dirty Projectors Domino Records page]\n* [http://www.westernvinyl.com/dirty_projectors.htm Dirty Projectors Western Vinyl page]\n* {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p601780/biography}}\n* [https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=15735067 Dirty Projectors in concert on NPR Music]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091010192614/http://www.beyondrace.com/inside/latestissue/1432-dirty-projectors Dirty Projectors] on [http://beyondrace.com/ ''Beyond Race Magazine'' (''BRM'')]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130207081054/http://www.deadoceans.com/artist.php?name=dirtyprojectors Dead Oceans Page]\n* [http://core.thomaslaupstad.com/rob-da-bank-2010-07-10-with-dirty-projectors-bjork/ Dirty Projectors & Bj\u00f6rk on the Rob da Bank show]\n\n{{Dirty Projectors}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Indie rock musical groups from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2002]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:2002 establishments in New York City]]\n[[Category:Domino Recording Company artists]]\n[[Category:Dead Oceans artists]]\n[[Category:Western Vinyl artists]]\n", "name_user": "Dfsghjkgfhdg", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWindows Open (2020):Removed incorrect wiki link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dirty_Projectors"}
