 shown to increase by $28,000. You go from $194,400 to $223,200. Why do you need this increase? Mr. Murphy. We are acquiring about 2,000 more square feet of office space in the Universal Building, where we are presently housed. I think that accounts, perhaps, for the increase in our rent. Is that correct, Mr. Kiefer?\"</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[United States government role in civil aviation]]\n* [[National Transportation Safety Board|NTSB]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat}}\n{{Wikisource|Portal:Civil_Aeronautics_Board}}\n* [https://www.archives.gov/research/guide-fed-records/groups/197.html Records of the Civil Aeronautics Board] - [[United States National Archives]]\n* [https://archive.org/stream/oversightofcivil01unit/oversightofcivil01unit_djvu.txt Oversight of Civil Aeronautics Board practices and procedures]\n* [https://ntl.bts.gov/ National Transportation Library] - Includes air accident reports and other materials from the CAB, Air Safety Board, and Bureau of Air Commerce, dating to 1934\n\n{{Aviation accident orgs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 1938]]\n[[Category:1938 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:1985 disestablishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Organizations investigating aviation accidents and incidents]]\n[[Category:Aviation organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Transport safety organizations]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Independent agencies of the United States government]]\n[[Category:Transportation government agencies of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Zxtxtxz", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:fix ref cite", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Civil_Aeronautics_Board"}
{"title_page": "Arthur Gardner (producer)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{infobox person\n|name=Arthur Gardner\n|birth_name=Arthur Goldberg\n|birth_date=June 7, 1910\n|birth_place=[[Marinette, Wisconsin]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date={{nowrap| {{Death date and age|2014|12|19|1910|6|7}}}}\n|death_place=[[Beverly Hills, California]]\n|residence=Beverly Hills, California\n|occupation=film producer, actor\n|years_active=1930\u20131982<ref name=\"obit\"/>\n}}\n'''Arthur Gardner''' (born '''Arthur Goldberg'''; June 7, 1910 \u2013 December 19, 2014) was an American actor and film producer. He was known for his television western, ''[[The Rifleman]]''. He was a voting member of the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]].\n\n==Biography ==\nGardner was born Arthur Goldberg in [[Marinette, Wisconsin]]. He started his show business career as an actor when he was 18 years old. In 1929 he arrived in Hollywood, where [[Carl Laemmle]] employed him as an extra for the film studio [[Universal Studios|Universal]]. One of his first roles was as a student in 1930's ''[[All Quiet on the Western Front (1930 film)|All Quiet on the Western Front]]''. He was the last surviving member of the cast and crew. Gardner and [[Luise Rainer]] were in 1938's ''[[Dramatic School (film)|Dramatic School]]'', and, up until his death two weeks before Rainer, were the last two surviving members, both at the age of 104.<ref>http://www.fandango.com/arthurgardner/information/p91020</ref>\n\nDuring [[World War II]], Gardner served in the Army Air Forces' [[First Motion Picture Unit]] in [[Culver City, California]], where he met [[Jules Levy (producer)|Jules Levy]] and [[Arnold Laven]]. The three formed the [[Levy-Gardner-Laven]] production company in 1951. Gardner's producing credits include the television series ''[[The Rifleman]]'' (1958\u20131963) and ''[[The Big Valley]]'' (1965\u20131969). His feature film credits include 1974's ''[[McQ]]'' and 1975's ''[[Brannigan (film)|Brannigan]],'' both starring [[John Wayne]].<ref name=\"AGardn\">{{cite web | url=http://www.therifleman.net/iconic-tv-western/ | title=The iconic tv western | publisher=therifleman.com | date=2014 | accessdate=May 1, 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502003839/http://www.therifleman.net/iconic-tv-western/ | archive-date=May 2, 2014 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life ==\nGardner lived in [[Beverly Hills, California]] from 1963 until his death there on December 19, 2014 at the age of 104.<ref name=\"obit\">Ryan Parker. \"[http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-arthur-gardner-dies-20141219-story.html Hollywood producer Arthur Gardner dies at 104]\", ''Los Angeles Times'', December 19, 2014. Accessed December 20, 2014.</ref> His son Steve Gardner is an attorney. His son Douglas is an Assistant Director.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of centenarians (actors, filmmakers and entertainers)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0306831|Arthur Gardner}}\n* {{EmmyTVLegends name|arthur-gardner|Arthur Gardner}}\n* [http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/movies/2012/02/oscars-2012-winners-voting-time-network-members-academy-awards-arthur-gardner-ronald-reagan.html Oscars' oldest voter, 101, offers link to Hollywood's Golden Age] - ''Los Angeles Times'' article\n* [https://variety.com/2010/scene/news/tv-pioneer-reaches-milestone-1118017692/ TV pioneer reaches milestone] - ''Variety'' article\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gardner, Arthur}}\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Marinette, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Beverly Hills, California]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Film producers from California]]\n[[Category:American centenarians]]\n[[Category:Jewish American male actors]]\n[[Category:First Motion Picture Unit personnel]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Wisconsin]]\n\n\n{{US-film-producer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{infobox person\n|name=Arthur Gardner\n|birth_name=Arthur Goldberg\n|birth_date=June 7, 1910\n|birth_place=[[Marinette, Wisconsin]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date={{nowrap| {{Death date and age|2014|12|19|1910|6|7}}}}\n|death_place=[[Beverly Hills, California]]\n|residence=Beverly Hills, California\n|occupation=film producer, actor\n|years_active=1930\u20131982<ref name=\"obit\"/>\n}}\n'''Arthur Gardner''' (born '''Arthur Goldberg'''; June 7, 1910 \u2013 December 19, 2014) was an American actor and film producer. He was known for his television western, ''[[The Rifleman]]''. He was a voting member of the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]].\n\n==Biography ==\nGardner was born Arthur Goldberg in [[Marinette, Wisconsin]]. He started his show business career as an actor when he was 18 years old. In 1929 he arrived in Hollywood, where [[Carl Laemmle]] employed him as an extra for the film studio [[Universal Studios|Universal]]. One of his first roles was as a student in 1930's ''[[All Quiet on the Western Front (1930 film)|All Quiet on the Western Front]]''. He was the last surviving member of the cast and crew. Gardner and [[Luise Rainer]] were in 1938's ''[[Dramatic School (film)|Dramatic School]]'', and, up until his death two weeks before Rainer, were the last two surviving members, both at the age of 104.<ref>http://www.fandango.com/arthurgardner/information/p91020</ref>\n\nDuring [[World War II]], Gardner served in the Army Air Forces' [[First Motion Picture Unit]] in [[Culver City, California]], where he met [[Jules V. Levy]] and [[Arnold Laven]]. The three formed the [[Levy-Gardner-Laven]] production company in 1951. Gardner's producing credits include the television series ''[[The Rifleman]]'' (1958\u20131963) and ''[[The Big Valley]]'' (1965\u20131969). His feature film credits include 1974's ''[[McQ]]'' and 1975's ''[[Brannigan (film)|Brannigan]],'' both starring [[John Wayne]].<ref name=\"AGardn\">{{cite web | url=http://www.therifleman.net/iconic-tv-western/ | title=The iconic tv western | publisher=therifleman.com | date=2014 | accessdate=May 1, 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502003839/http://www.therifleman.net/iconic-tv-western/ | archive-date=May 2, 2014 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life ==\nGardner lived in [[Beverly Hills, California]] from 1963 until his death there on December 19, 2014 at the age of 104.<ref name=\"obit\">Ryan Parker. \"[http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-arthur-gardner-dies-20141219-story.html Hollywood producer Arthur Gardner dies at 104]\", ''Los Angeles Times'', December 19, 2014. Accessed December 20, 2014.</ref> His son Steve Gardner is an attorney. His son Douglas is an Assistant Director.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of centenarians (actors, filmmakers and entertainers)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0306831|Arthur Gardner}}\n* {{EmmyTVLegends name|arthur-gardner|Arthur Gardner}}\n* [http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/movies/2012/02/oscars-2012-winners-voting-time-network-members-academy-awards-arthur-gardner-ronald-reagan.html Oscars' oldest voter, 101, offers link to Hollywood's Golden Age] - ''Los Angeles Times'' article\n* [https://variety.com/2010/scene/news/tv-pioneer-reaches-milestone-1118017692/ TV pioneer reaches milestone] - ''Variety'' article\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gardner, Arthur}}\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Marinette, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Beverly Hills, California]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Film producers from California]]\n[[Category:American centenarians]]\n[[Category:Jewish American male actors]]\n[[Category:First Motion Picture Unit personnel]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Wisconsin]]\n\n\n{{US-film-producer-stub}}\n", "name